<SECOND>AM-Apollo-Houston Celebration, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0751,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>``Splashdown'' Party Celebrates Apollo 11 Lunar Landing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with color from party; picks up
4th graf pvs, `On July...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ;ADDS byline.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Space, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three Apollo 11 astronauts had
another ``splashdown'' Thursday, this time in the form of a party
with thousands of NASA employees celebrating the 20th anniversary
of their lunar landing.
   Astronauts Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin and Michael Collins
arrived from Washington, where they had lunch with President Bush.
   ``Twenty years ago, I sat in mission control when these guys
came down and I wouldn't miss this for the world,'' said Hans Mark,
a former Johnson Space Center director who is now chancellor for
the University of Texas.
   The space center party was patterned after the informal
celebrations that followed each Apollo mission. A crowd estimated
at 10,000 attended the event.
   ``This is just like the splashdown party 20 years ago, except
then they threw everybody in the pool,'' said Cookie Leisenring, a
former employee of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, who was trying to take pictures of the astronauts.
   Collins, Aldrin and Armstrong each got loud applause upon
arrival.
   Separate outdoor areas were designated for different departments
such as engineering and development, and recovery crew. Inside, a
band played in a gym-sized room decorated with star-shaped ballons
and blue balloons with the U.S. flag on them.
   Mark said the astronauts were very pleased to return and visit
with old friends. Many of those in the crowd wore buttons showing
Armstong on the moon and reading, ``July 20, 1969-1989 We Were
There.''
   On July 20, 1969, Armstrong and Aldrin planted their footsteps
on the moon while Collins circled above in the spacecraft that
later carried the three men back to Earth. The splashdown party is
one of many events being hel????z~2to commemorate that
historic flight.
   After the party, the three former astronauts were to attend a
private party where they would watch a light display on Clear Lake
dubbed ``Thousand Points of Light.''
   That celebration was to begin at 9:56 p.m. _ the moment
Armstrong stepped on the moon two decades ago _ when a group of
boats simultaneously switch on strings of lights.
</TEXT>
