<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-SpaceSpending 1stLd-Writethru   07-20 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Space Spending, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0832,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Spending Bill for Housing, Space and Veterans Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: CORRECTS $400 million to $400 billion in 10th graf: ``Schumer
estimated,'' ^By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved a $65 billion spending bill
for housing, space and veterans programs Thursday but decided to
cut funding for a controversial program at the Department of
Housing and Urban Development.
   The bill, passed by a voice vote, provides no new money for a
HUD program currently being investigated by four congressional
panels and the Justice Department for fraud and mismanagement.
   A HUD inspector general's report alleged several former HUD
officials and Republican party fundraisers, including former
Secretary of Interior James Watt used political influence to get
funding for projects on which they were highly paid consultants or
developers.
   ``We did not want to fund a program which is having such
difficulty,'' said Rep. Bill Green of New York, ranking Republican
on the House Appropriations subcommittee that oversees funding for
HUD, the Veterans Administration and independent agencies.
   The bill also would reclassify all deputy assistant secretaries,
administrators and directors at HUD and other agencies covered by
the legislation as career positions. Persons now in these positions
are political appointees of the president.
   However, it was funding for a planned space station on the moon
and expanded U.S. exploration that dominated debate on the bill on
Thursday, the 20th anniversary of man's first lunar landing.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., attempted to transfer $714 million
from the space station to veterans medical services, pollution
control and research and low-income and elderly housing.
   ``The space station is not the way to go to space. It is the B-2
bomber of the space program,'' said Schumer.
   Schumer estimated the space station and a proposal by President
Bush for a manned mission to Mars would cost $400 billion.
   ``I am a believer in space technology,'' said Schumer, ``but you
can't have everything.''
   ``As we reach for the stars, let us not forget those who live
underneath them'' he added.
   While Schumer's proposal might save money in the short term,
Green warned that decreasing spending for space by small amounts at
a time would drive the overall costs up.
   ``The one thing that is going to drive the cost of the space
station through the roof is to nickel and dime it,'' said Green.
   Schumer ``really saves a penny this year but he will be spending
pounds and pounds in later years,'' added Green.
   Schumer's proposal was defeated by a 291-125 vote.
   The House appropriations bill earmarks $1.65 billion of NASA's
$12.2 billion budget for the space station. The bill reduces the
Bush administration budget request for NASA by $1 billion.
   The bill also provides:
   _$15.1 billion for HUD, including $9.1 billion for assisted
housing and $456 million to fully fund programs under the Stewart
B. McKinney Homeless Act
   _$29.5 billion for the Veterans Administration, including $820
million for veterans medical care
   _$35.5 million for the Consumer Product Safety Commission
   _$5.4 billion for the Environmental Protection Agency
</TEXT>
