<FIRST>u a AM-DC-10Crash-Engine 1stLd-Writethru a0402 07-20 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash-Engine, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0402, a0405,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Engine Suspected of Failing Had Past Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines urgent series, clarifying that problems were with No.
2 engine, but officials could not immediately confirm it was the same engine
on the jet that crashed. UPDATES with details of other problems, quotes
from passenger who said jet had problems earlier in the day.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-DC-10 Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal records indicate past major problems
with the tail engine of a United Airlines DC-10 that crashed
Wednesday as it attempted to make an emergency landing with about
290 people aboard.
   The jet's tail engine, or engine No. 2, failed just prior to the
crash, and the 15-year-old plane experienced ``complete hydraulic
failure,'' Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Fred Farrar
said.
   However, it could not be determined Wednesday night whether the
tail engine that experienced the previous problems was the same No.
2 engine that was on the jet when it crashed.
   Meanwhile, a passenger who rode same DC-10 from Philadelphia to
Denver Wednesday morning said the plane had been delayed because of
technical problems.
   Mrs. Ruth Dinsmore of Mount Laurel, N.J., said passengers boarded
tha plane and and it began to leave the terminal at Philadelphia
International Airport shortly after 10 a.m., when ``everything sort
of shut off.''
   Mrs. Dinsmore said the pilot came on the PA system and said ``a
little gizmo'' had gone wrong.
   She said the plane taxied back to the terminal, where the plane
sat for about 15 minutes while the ``gizmo'' was being fixed.
   FAA records, obtained for The Associated Press by the Aircraft
Owners and Pilots Association, indicate that on Oct. 7, 1988, the
No. 2 engine overheated and shut down just after takeoff from O'Hare
Airport in Chicago.
   An inspection of the engine later revealed that a turbine blade
had failed and broken free from the engine's platform.
   On Sept. 30, 1988, the No. 2 engine also reportedly quit
operating at 16,000 feet because of ``extensive high pressure and
low pressure turbine damage,'' the report said.
   The primary cause of the shutdown was a blade that separated at
the blade root due to an ``ailing edge crack,'' the report said.
   On July 20, 1983, the report said, the No. 2 engine shut down due
to ``vibration.'' An inspection revealed a broken turbine blade, the
report said.
   The report also indicated problems with the other two engines on
the plane.
   On Sept. 26, 1986, the plane's No. 1 engine was replaced after an
inspection revealed a cracked second-stage blade.
   On Nov. 13, 1987, the report said, the flight crew reported that
the No.3 engine vibrated and lost power as the plane climbed to
4,000 feet after taking off from Los Angeles. An engine tear-down
later revealed that an engine blade failed and caused additional
bearing failure.
</TEXT>
