<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-20 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group that wants to improve the image
of taverns in the state's eastern Panhandle elected a topless bar
owner as president, and he says his job hasn't been easy.
   ``I'm not interested in getting publicity about the fact that I
own a topless bar. Luckily, it hasn't blown up in my face, yet,''
said C.B. ``Butch'' Pennington, owner of the Opequon Hill Lounge and
president of the Tri-County Club and Tavern Owners Association.
   The association was created following an April gambling raid on
33 bars in the Panhandle in which police confiscated 70 illegal
gambling devices, including poker machines.
   ``The biggest mistake that people have is that all you go into a
tavern for is to drink and gamble,'' Pennington said. ``That's just
not so. You go in to talk to people. It's like going into a friend's
house. You relax and swap stories.''
   Pennington said the owners were upset by the raid because the
state Supreme Court previously ruled that poker machines are legal.
The group plans to lobby state and local government to improve
business conditions for tavern owners.
   ``We just want to show them that we're in a legitimate business
and, like everybody else, we deserve a fair shake,'' Pennington
said. ``We know more than just how to mix drinks. There are some
things we can do to help old folks, children, charities, things like
that.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The postman may always ring twice, but
sometimes he rings 32 years too late.
   Mildred St. Onge received her mail as usual Tuesday only to find
a post card addressed to Mr. and Mrs. Gordon Simmons. Mrs. Simmons
was her name in 1957, the year marked on the card. Her brother and
sister-in-law had sent it while vacationing in Florida 32 years ago.
   ``I didn't believe it. I really didn't believe it,'' said Mrs.
St. Onge, 67, who has been widowed twice. ``My brother has been dead
since 1977 and my husband (Simmons) has been dead since 1963.''
   New Bedford Postmaster Antone L. Silva has seen three such late
letter deliveries in his 24 years on the job. He said the card could
have gone astray within the post office, or been misdelivered and
mailed again years later.
   ``Thirty-two years is a long time,'' said Mrs. St. Onge, who was
35 when the card was mailed. ``My husband would have laughed.''
</TEXT>
