<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CannibalismDig     07-20 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cannibalism Dig,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archaeologists Unearth Remains of At Least 2 Bodies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists have uncovered the bones
of as many as four people in a mass grave near the reputed site
where self-proclaimed cannibal Alferd Packer's victims perished, the
scientists said Wednesday.
   The diggers, who found the bodies of at least two men and
possibly four on Tuesday, said they also found burlap and a green
suspender clip holding remnants of brown cloth.
   ``The cloth is most remarkable,'' said archaeologist Jim Ayres.
``It could help us put a date on things.''
   The scientists are part of an expedition formed by George
Washington University law professor James Starrs, who is looking for
clues to the truth about what occurred on the snow-packed mountain
ridge in 1874.
   Packer, who formed a gold-hunting party with five other men, said
the group became stranded on the ridge two miles south of Lake City
during a bitter winter.
   Packer, the lone survivor, wandered into what is now Lake City in
April 1874.
   He told authorities that Shannon Bell, a member of the group,
killed the other four gold seekers and that he was forced to kill
Bell in self-defense. Packer said he consumed the remains of the
five in order to survive.
   He was convicted of manslaughter and sentenced to 40 years in
prison. The case has been a topic of debate ever since.
   The archaeologists' findings indicated the men's bodies were
wrapped in burlap and buried in a mass grave, said Walter Birkby,
curator of physical anthropology at Arizona State University in
Tucson.
   The bones were in a jumbled mass, forcing scientists to move
slowly in uncovering them.
   As the scientists worked in the dig site, which Starrs calls the
``bone zone,'' residents and onlookers kept watch nearby.
   Ayres said the scientists would test the cloth, suspender clip
and other artifacts to estimate their age.
   The scientific expedition began Monday.
</TEXT>
