<FIRST>r a PM-Names     07-20 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0902</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Sylvester Stallone says he really isn't a
macho, monosyllabic guy, although he admits he's played that role in
so many films that he'd almost forgotten how to talk.
   ``It's not really me. It was a book that I interpreted,''
Stallone said of his Rambo films. ``I inherited the mantle. I'm not
monosyllabic. I'm not that quiet. I'm not a loner by nature.''
   A clean-shaven, neatly dressed and bespectacled Stallone met with
reporters Tuesday in Cincinnati where he is filming scenes for a
Warner Bros. picture co-starring Kurt Russell. Stallone plays an
undercover policeman who is refined and articulate _ a man more
inclined to wearing suits and dabbling in the stock market.
   His next film, ``Lockup,'' opens in early August, and Stallone
said he is more optimistic about it than he has been about any film
since the first ``Rocky'' in 1976.
   ``It's an ensemble,'' he said. ``It isn't just me out there with
a rifle, swinging from a tree for 2{ hours. At least I get to act,
get to talk, which I'd almost forgotten how to do in the past few
films. It's like the re-education of Sylvester Stallone.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimillionaire publisher Malcolm S.
Forbes and nine members of the biking club Capitalist Tools rolled
into this historic Mississippi River town on a seven-day journey
down the Great River Road.
   ``We began where the Mississippi began, and we're going to where
it ends,'' Forbes said of the 2,100-mile trek.
   The motorcyclists spent Tuesday night at a bed-and-breakfast inn
and left Wednesday for New Orleans, their final destination.
   The 69-year-old publisher said he found the route more enjoyable
than his normal commute.
   ``We've gone through 10 states and experienced less traffic than
one hour of driving from New Jersey to New York,'' he said. ``You
feel like you're really getting to the heart of America.''
   The trip did have its wrong turns, though.
   ``We followed Highway 72 on a 1988 Rand-McNally map of Tennessee
and the road got rougher and rougher ... the bridge was out,'' he
said. The crew asked a farmer if it was possible to cross the river
and he replied, ``If you can leap these bikes 40 feet you can
cross,'' Forbes said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folk singer Joan Baez sang a new song
protesting the recent violence in China. The performance was at a
charity concert attended by Prince Charles and Princess Diana.
   The 48-year-old U.S. singer said she had thought about singing
``Lady Di,'' which she wrote eight years ago, but decided, ``It just
wouldn't have been protocol.''
   Instead, she sang the China protest song at the Prince's Trust
Rock Gala at Birmingham's National Exhibition Center. Wednesday
night's concert drew about 10,000 people and raised $800,000 for the
trust, which helps young people.
   Baez, who met the royal couple before the show, said she was
flattered to be invited. ``I am pleased that I can still enjoy
performing,'' she said. ``I'll try to go on for another 10 years,
but then I'll have to put my teeth in a jar.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HULL, Quebec (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Duke and Duchess of York thanked a crowd
for a warm welcome after getting a rough reception a few days
earlier on their Canadian tour.
   ``Sarah and I are particularly touched by the warm welcome of
Quebecers,'' Prince Andrew told a gathering at a civic welcome
Wednesday outside City Hall. ``Thank you for the most wonderful
welcome.''
   The thanks seemed intended, in part, to quiet some controversy
fanned by the British press, which reported that Sarah was shaken
when the couple was booed Sunday at the closing ceremonies of a
summer festival in Quebec City.
   For his part, Mayor Michel Legere offered a down-to-earth
greeting, urging the royal couple to ``have a Hull of a good time.''
   Later the duchess, the former Sarah Ferguson, visited a
rehabilitation center in adjacent Ottawa and spoke to victims of
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis _ a degenerative neuro-muscular
affliction also known as Lou Gehrig's disease.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former ``Hollywood Squares'' host Peter
Marshall has sued actor Burt Reynolds and game show host Bert Convy,
contending they broke a contract to hire him as host of a new quiz
show.
   Marshall claimed in Wednesday's Superior Court lawsuit that he
was host of the successful pilot of ``3rd Degree'' and was promised
he would continue in that role for the 1989-90 season, said his
lawyer, Dorothy Wolpert.
   Although announcements were made that the former ``Hollywood
Squares'' host would preside over ``3rd Degree,'' he was told on
June 30 that he would not get the job after all, the suit alleged.
   Soon thereafter, it was announced that Convy was not being
renewed as host of ``Win, Lose or Draw'' and would replace Marshall
on ``3rd Degree,'' the suit said.
   The suit seeks $1 million in compensatory damages and asks for
punitive damages in an amount to be set by the court.
   ``3rd Degree'' is produced by Burt &amp; Bert Productions and Kline &amp;
Friends, Inc. The suit accuses Reynolds' and Convy's company and the
other company of breach of contract and fraud by replacing Marshall.
