<FIRST>r i PM-Guatemala-Volcano     07-20 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guatemala-Volcano,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Santiaguito Volcano Erupts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Santiaguito volcano spewed red-hot lava
and a 15,000-foot column of ash and steam, a seismology official
said.
   A resident of the city of Coatepeque, 25 miles south of the
volcano, said ash fell on the city when the volcano erupted
Wednesday and lava could be seen glowing on the mountain after dark.
   Eddy Sanchez, assistant director of the seismology station in
Guatemala City, said Santiaguito, 140 miles west of the capital, is
constantly active but Wednesday's eruption was unusual.
   The National Emergency Committee and authorities in Coatepeque
said they were on alert. If the activity continues, coffee and other
fields in the western provinces of Quezaltenango, San Marcos and
Retalhuleu could be affected, emergency officials said.
   Santiaguito is considered a second crater of the adjacent
12,447-foot Santa Maria volcano.
   The town of El Palmar was moved from the slopes of the volcano in
1988 after lava flows formed dams above it. The dams broke, causing
mudslides that nearly destroyed El Palmar.
</TEXT>
