<FIRST>r w PM-Lucas Bjt   07-20 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lucas, Bjt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lucas Could Face More Questions on Civil Rights Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Should stand</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Lucas could face more grilling on his
nomination to be the nation's civil rights chief as the Senate
Judiciary Committee seeks to resolve questions about his fitness for
the job.
   ``There are a lot of charges against him. We need to get to the
bottom of them,'' Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., said Wednesday after
Lucas was questioned for more than three hours about his views, his
qualifications and his character.
   Lucas defended both his commitment to the drive against
discrimination and his actions when customs inspectors found $8,800
worth of undeclared goods in his luggage.
   Afterward, Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., who chaired the proceeding,
said members reserved the right to recall him for more questioning.
   Heflin told reporters Lucas should be questioned again about a
number of issues, including the fact that the black Republican from
Michigan made misstatements on a sworn application to be admitted to
the New York bar in 1981.
   Lucas did not disclose on the form that he had once failed the
District of Columbia bar examination when asked if he had taken the
test in other states.
   Lucas testified that when he filled out the 1981 form he
interpreted the question to pertain only to any previous
applications to the New York bar. ``There was no intent to
mislead,'' he said.
   Several Democrats on the panel questioned whether Lucas, a
lifelong Democrat who became a Republican in 1985, had the legal
credentials and commitment to assistant attorney general for civil
rights.
   ``It remains to be seen whether Mr. Lucas is the right man for
this important job,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
   ``If a case is brought to me involving a cross burning on the
lawn of a citizen, believe me, this is not just cold facts to me,''
said Lucas, 61, who was sheriff and later chief executive of Wayne
County, Mich., which includes Detroit.
   ``I have been there. I have smelled the smoke,'' Lucas said.
   Lucas defended a series of recent Supreme Court decisions that
civil rights lawyers say will make it harder to win discrimination
cases in federal courts.
   Lucas, echoing a pledge by Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, said
he would monitor the impact of those decisions on discrimination
suits and push for legislation if the rulings thwart civil rights
enforcement.
   But Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said he was troubled by
Lucas' defense of the recent high court rulings, adding, ``I've been
around long enough to know time slips away.''
   Metzenbaum also questioned Lucas about why he was fined $594 by
the U.S. Customs Service in 1985 for failing to declare $8,884 worth
of merchandise the Lucas family brought back from a trip to the Far
East.
   ``How do you explain concealing receipts and merchandise from the
customs inspectors?'' Metzenbaum said, reading from an April 24,
1985, report of the incident at the Seattle airport.
   The report said ``there was a deliberate effort by all (family)
members to conceal goods and receipts.''
   Lucas explained that customs agents found several pieces of
undeclared jewelry in a cosmetics case carried by one of his
daughters who accompanied him on the business trip to South Korea
and Japan.
   Lucas said he reported $4,800 worth of merchandise, relying on
what his wife and two daughters told him they had bought.
   ``I reported exactly what I was advised of. I did not personally
examine any of these things,'' Lucas said.
   Lucas said he discussed the incident with FBI agents who
investigated his background before his nomination by President Bush
as well as with committee staff members.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel called the customs
violation ``pretty minor-league stuff.''
   ``Our feeling is that he had a very strong appearance today,
answered any and all questions put before him by the committee,''
Runkel said. ``We are ever more confident that he'll be confirmed.''
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, calling Lucas ``a take-charge guy who
gets things done, who does what's right,'' vowed to fight hard for
his Senate confirmation.
</TEXT>
