<FIRST>r w PM-Technology-FOI     07-20 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Technology-FOI,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOE, NASA Call for Export Restrictions on Technical Information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE ANN ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Freedom of Information Act gives foreign
competitors ``unique access'' to U.S. technology, and an Energy
Department official suggests restrictions might be needed to stem
the flow.
   ``The government's role is to make sure that U.S. industry has
the initial opportunity to develop U.S.-sponsored'' research,
Richard H. Williamson, deputy assistant energy secretary for
international affairs, said Wednesday.
   ``The Freedom of Information Act ... has granted foreigners
unique access to our technology,'' he said.
   Williamson and Kenneth S. Pedersen of the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration told the House subcommittee on
international scientific cooperation they support restricting the
FOI law to limit foreign access to information where it could hurt
U.S. competitiveness.
   The panel was considering how foreign access to U.S. science and
technology compares to U.S. access to foreign technology.
   Pedersen and Williamson conceded that providing exemptions would
be difficult.
   ``It is an effort to balance two very important objectives,''
Pedersen said.
   NASA, he said, wants to continue to provide access without giving
foreign competitors an edge. He proposed giving certain technology
to U.S. industry for a specified time before making it available for
general release.
   ``We aren't looking for an open-ended authority,'' Pedersen said.
``We're trying to get a door on the barn before too many horses
leave.''
   George P. Millburn of the Defense Department, which already has
some FOI exemptions, told the subcommittee the Pentagon supports the
NASA and DOE requests.
   Deputy Secretary of Commerce Thomas Murrin said the United States
wants to ``support, foster and encourage'' the exchange of
scientific and technological information.
   But he and others testified that the United States is often
shortchanged in such exchanges.
   ``Many of our scientists and engineers are still subject to what
is known as the `Not Invented Here Syndrome,' which makes those
afflicted by it undervalue the importance of research performed
elsewhere,'' Murrin said.
   ``The Japanese, on the other hand, eagerly seek new scientific
and technological knowledge from any source,'' he said.
</TEXT>
