<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-1979     07-20 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-1979,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Crash Comes 10 Years after Nation's Worst _ Also a DC-10</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's worst aviation disaster occurred 10
years ago when an American Airlines DC-10 crashed on takeoff from
O'Hare International Airport.
   On May 25, 1979, Flight 191 lost an engine, banked sideways out
of control and slammed into a field, exploding into an inferno. The
furrow plowed in the field by the jetliner's left wing is still
visible.
   The jetliner was reduced to scattered debris. All 258 passengers
and 13 crew members were killed, as were two people on the ground.
   ``To this day, it's something that's hard to comprehend, how a
big plane like that could disintegrate into little pieces,'' said
Ray Devito of Mokena, who had driven his girlfriend to airport to
catch the ill-fated Los Angeles-bound flight.
   Wednesday's crash in Sioux City, Iowa, is the first major
domestic accident involving a DC-10 since the Chicago disaster a
decade ago.
   The National Transportation Safety Board laid the primary blame
for the 1979 crash on the airline, citing ``maintenance-induced
damage'' _ a 10-inch crack in the engine mount _ that caused the
left engine to tear loose. It also criticized McDonnell Douglas'
design as vulnerable to maintenance damage.
   The NTSB also said the Federal Aviation Administration had been
remiss by not learning that a similar crack had recently been
repaired in a Continental Airlines DC-10.
   Since the accident, the FAA has been ``very specific about what
has to be reported to us and what doesn't,'' spokesman Fred Farrar
said last spring.
   Elaine Bendell, a spokeswoman for McDonnell Douglas in Long
Beach, Calif., said the only change made in the DC-10 pylon design
was a shift to flathead rather than raised-head bolts.
</TEXT>
