<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe     07-20 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce Agrees to Testify Twice More</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Housing Secretary Samuel Pierce will
testify at least twice more before a congressional panel
investigating scandals in programs under his stewardship at the
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of the subcommittee, said
Wednesday that Pierce will return in the fall to discuss
contradictions between his earlier testimony and witnesses'
statements that he was directly involved in approving questionable
HUD projects.
   Pierce had already agreed to return to the House Government
Operations employment and housing subcommittee Aug. 3 to answer
questions about a $15 million North Carolina project headed by a
former law partner of Pierce's.
   Pierce told congressional investigators in May he was not
directly involved in funding decisions in many of HUD's programs
which have been criticized for alleged influence-peddling and
mismanagement during his eight-year tenure.
   But Shirley McVay Wiseman, former assistant for housing,
testified Friday that Pierce personally ordered her to approve
funding for the project in Durham, N.C.
   Lantos said staff members for the panel met with Pierce on
Wednesday.
   ``There was no discussion with respect to the substance of his
statements,'' Lantos said. ``That would have been inappropriate.''
   ``It was a relaxed, lengthy, cordial and productive meeting,'' he
said.
   Lantos said the panel's questions next month would be limited to
Pierce's role in funding the North Carolina project to convert a
defunct hosiery mill to housing for the elderly. The project was
pushed by a former Pierce law partner.
   HUD staff members had opposed government funding because the
project was too expensive and its location on top of a toxic waste
site made it environmentally unsafe.
   Because of HUD's approval, developers received more than $11.3
million in rent subsidies, a $2.3 million Urban Development Action
Grant and more than $3 million in tax credits.
   Pierce also agreed to return to discuss ``a range of issues'' in
September or October, said Lantos.
   The chairman said he could not predict when the panel's
investigation would end, only that it was certain to continue into
the fall.
   ``The HUD crisis is an ocean without a shore,'' said Lantos.
</TEXT>
