<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-KALFlight     07-20 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-KAL Flight,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigating Pilot Says Why KAL Pilot Knowingly Stayed Off Course</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired pilot who investigated the downing of
Korean Air Lines Flight 007 says the crew of the ill-fated flight
radioed false position reports as he 1,500 miles into Soviet
airspace before being shot down.
   Frank Houston of Seattle told a disbelieving KAL attorney
Wednesday that a crew member probably misprogrammed one of the three
computerized navigation systems aboard the jet before the Boeing 747
took off from Anchorage, Alaska.
   The pilot, copilot and flight engineer ignored numerous other
plane instruments and navigational aids on the ground as they flew
300 miles off their assigned course, Houston testified in the second
day of the civil trial.
   ``All three of them disregarded all those instruments?'' asked
Marshall Turner, an attorney representing the airline.
   ``That's about what I'm telling you, yes,'' replied Houston, who
worked with an international team that investigated the Sept. 1,
1983 shootdown that killed all 269 people aboard.
   The families of the passengers are trying to prove willful
misconduct by KAL, alleging the plane's crew knowingly continued off
course because they would have had to turn back and face
disciplinary action to correct the problem.
   Turner, noting improperly set instruments would have told the
crew they were 300 miles from the airport while they were still on
the ground, asked whether the crew then reported false position
reports during the flight.
   ``I am sure of it,'' replied Houston.
   Turner then asked the question that has been central to the
Flight 007 mystery since a Soviet fighter jet shot the plane out of
the night sky: Why didn't the crew merely turn left and get out of
Soviet territory?
   ``That's what boggles our mind, why didn't they?'' said Houston.
   Turner said Houston's conclusion that plane spent its last three
hours in Soviet territory ``sheer speculation.''
   But the available radar data for the initial part of the flight
and information provided by the Soviets and Japanese governments
shows ``that airplane was well right of course,'' said Houston.
``There is mountains of evidence and it's irrefutable.''
   The crew thought they could ``sneak through Russia?'' asked U.S.
District Court Judge Aubrey Robinson.
   Houston said the pilot probably concluded, ``I think I'll take a
shot at it.''
   The pilot may have believed he could ``get away with it, and he
damn near did,'' said Houston.
</TEXT>
