<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TeenQueen     07-20 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teen Queen,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Pageant Winner's Challenge of Her Disqualification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who won a Nevada beauty contest
lost her court bid to compete in the Miss Teen USA pageant after she
was disqualified for competing in two states.
   U.S. District Court Judge Roger Foley said Wednesday that Miss
Nevada Teen, Heather Anne McLeod, should have realized that
competing in preliminary teen pageants in Nevada and California
could disqualify her.
   ``She should have known the rules,'' Foley said.
   The 5-foot-8 green-eyed blonde said she was disappointed but glad
to have had her day in court, which was attended by about 10 high
school-age boys.
   ``I respect the judge's decision and we knew it was a gamble from
the beginning,'' Miss McLeod said. ``You win some, you lose some.
Life goes on.
   ``I just hope this doesn't happen to another girl because the
rules just aren't clear. I was doing everything honestly.''
   She and her attorneys haven't decided yet whether to pursue
$200,000 in damages against Miss Universe Inc.
   Miss McLeod, 18, who lives in Reno with her parents but had
attended college in California, contended she didn't have a copy of
the rules forbidding competing in two state contests the same year.
   She also said she was encouraged by operators of both state
pageants, owned by Miss Universe Inc., to enter. Affidavits from the
operators show they did encourage her to compete and weren't aware
she could be disqualified.
   Stacey Bentley, 18, of Las Vegas, who was the first runner-up in
the Miss Nevada Teen contest, will continue to represent Nevada in
the national pageant in San Bernardino, Calif. The finals are
Tuesday.
   Following an anonymous telephone tip, Miss McLeod was
disqualified from the Miss Teen USA pageant June 30, eight days
after winning the Nevada pageant in Las Vegas. She lost the
California contest in April.
   No testimony was allowed in the case, but Miss McLeod said in an
affidavit she didn't understand that competing in two states was
prohbitited.
   She said the California pageant application didn't bar competing
in more than one state and the Nevada application was vague, just
asking whether she had participated in another state contest.
   Her attorney, Carvel Sims of Baton Rouge, La., said Miss McLeod
never said she was a current resident of California, but only that
she had attended the University of California at San Diego.
   Sims said Miss McLeod moved to Reno with her family in August
1988 when she was still 17 and considers Nevada her home state.
   The judge agreed with Kristina Pickering, the attorney for Miss
Universe Inc., who argued it was apparent from the applications that
Miss McLeod knew she must be a resident of each state to compete.
   ``She wrote her own ticket into this mess and now she's asking
this court to bail her out,'' Ms. Pickering said.
</TEXT>
