<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     07-20 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Socialist Star is Born</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOHRIYAMA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children await her with bunches of
flowers. Crowds follow her slavishly, shout her name and seek
handshakes. Scores of undercover police officers trail her
protectively as she traverses the campaign trail.
   Takako Doi, the charismatic leader of Japan's once lightly
regarded Socialists, is getting something that few politicians from
her party have had: superstar treatment.
   ``To be honest, I never imagined she would become this popular
three years ago,'' said Sukio Iwatare, a party official and veteran
lawmaker, as Ms. Doi spoke Wednesday to a crowd in Kohriyama in the
northern Fukushima prefecture.
   ``I think it is nothing but her lovable personality that led to
this Doi fever. It is amazing that she can easily draw thousands of
people everywhere she goes.''
   Pollsters and analysts say a new sales tax and an
influence-peddling scandal have turned voters against the Liberal
Democratic Party, the conservative group that has dominated Japanese
politicans for 34 years.
   Women's groups also have criticized new Prime Minister Sousuke
Uno after allegations surfaced that he kept paid mistresses.
   Ms. Doi's popularity is expected to make the Socialists the main
beneficiaries of voters' ire in Sunday's elections for half the 252
seats in the upper house of Parliament.
   Her party, the largest opposition group in Parliament, hopes to
increase its representation in the chamber from 43 to at least 65.
Pollsters say the Liberal Democrats likely will fall from 142 seats
to fewer than 120.
   Three years ago, Ms. Doi became the first woman to head a major
Japanese political party. Her predecessor had resigned over the
labor-backed party's defeat in Japan's last national elections.
   Since then, the 61-year-old Ms. Doi has moved the party away from
doctrinaire leftist ideas.
   On Wednesday, about 3,000 people packed the parking lots in front
of Kohriyama's railway station as Ms. Doi campaigned for the party's
local candidate. Some watched from balconies of nearby department
stores.
   ``It is time to bring changes in politics,'' Ms. Doi called out
from the top of a campaign truck.
   After a pause for cheers, she added: ``Give us a chance to run
the government. We can do it. We can make tomorrow's Japan better
together.''
   The candidate, Choei Aita, a 60-year-old former labor union
official challenging two ruling party incumbents, said Ms. Doi
``talks about specific policies but she makes it so easy to
understand for ordinary people.''
   He added that her speech gave him ``a very good feeling'' about
winning Sunday.
   If the opposition were to win control of Parliament's more
powerful lower house, in elections that don't have to be held before
next year, Ms. Doi could become Japan's first woman prime minister.
   ``Though there are many more hurdles to be cleared, the
opposition camp never had such a golden opportunity to take over the
government before,'' said Takayoshi Miyagawa, president and noted
political analyst at Seiji Koho Center, a prominent research firm.
   ``And if the opposition actually takes over the government, the
head of the largest party in the opposition camp would naturally
become prime minister,'' he added.
   The opposition, however, has been criticized for concentrating on
criticism rather than presenting alternative policy proposals.
   Doi emphasizes that her party would not bring make drastic
changes if it gained power.
   ``Continuity is important in politics,'' she told a news
conference after her speech. ``It is wrong to think we were trying
to bring drastic changes to this country.''
   The Liberal Democrats say the Socialists would take such steps as
scrapping the U.S.-Japan Security Treaty. Ms. Doi said her party
would not unilaterally abandon the pact.
</TEXT>
