<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TaxBill     07-20 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Bill,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Child Care Benefits</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Should stand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee, badly split
by disagreements over catastrophic health insurance and capital
gains, is having no trouble boosting federal aid to low-income
working parents with children.
   A bill whose chief goal is cutting the federal deficit has been
fattened to include $16 billion in direct credits and
state-administered grants to help parents pay expenses of child care.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the committee, hailed
the child care package as ``a giant step forward.'' Noting the Bush
administration disagrees with some of the provisions, he called on
the administration to ``commit itself to its campaign promise and do
something for children.''
   The child care plan was added to the bill on a 26-10 vote
Wednesday after the panel was unable to settle disputes over capital
gains and catastrophic insurance for older Americans.
   Bush has called for a cut in the capital gains tax, which applies
to profits from the sale of stock and other assets, on grounds it
would spur the economy and increase revenues.
   Many Democrats concede a one-year revenue gain but say a cut
would lose revenues after that. Besides, they note, most of the tax
benefits from a reduction in the capital gains tax would go to those
with incomes over $100,000 a year.
   The fight over catastrophic illness also includes an element of
rich-vs.-poor. Higher-income retirees are complaining loudly because
they must pay a larger share of the cost so the benefits can be
available to those with little or no income. Those with higher
incomes want all taxpayers to share the cost of catastrophic
coverage.
   Because of the complaints, Congress members have shown widespread
support for delaying the surtax of up to $800 that the higher-income
retirees must pay. But since members of the Ways and Means Committee
cannot agree on that, the panel may simply decide to repeal the
entire program.
   The split over approving the child care amendments has had a more
partisan tone. All Democrats and three Republicans voted for the
package; seven Republicans, favoring a less costly approach
recommended by Bush, voted no.
   The Ways and Means child care plan, which would take effect in
1991, is closer to a version passed by the Senate than to the
president's proposal. The committee provisions would benefit
families in which both spouses work outside the home as well as
those families in which one spouse stays at home to care for the
children.
   It would expand the existing earned-income credit, which is worth
up to $910 a year in tax cuts _ or in cash if there is no tax
liability _ for working families with children and incomes up to
about $18,000.
   The committee voted to raise the maximum credit to $1,217 for a
family with one child, $1,540 if there are two children, and $1,790
if a family has two or more children. Under current law, the credit
is the same regardless of the number of children.
   The plan would create a new credit for families with one or more
children under age 6. This credit, which would be in addition to the
earned-income credit, would be for 6 percent of the families' first
$6,500 of earned income, with a top credit of $430 in 1991.
   A third part of the committee's package would authorize $1.55
billion worth of federal grants for social services, with 80 percent
of the money earmarked for improving child care services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0033 </DOCNO>
