<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-20 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Shares Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen in Tokyo on
Thursday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained
moderately.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose 107.70
points, or 0.32 percent, ending the day's trading at 33,664.87. The
index gained 213.44 points on Wednesday.
   The dollar ended trading at 142.23 yen, up 0.43 yen from its
closing the previous day. It opened higher at 142.80 yen and ranged
between 142.05 and 142.90 yen.
   Despite the dollar-buying mood at the market's opening, market
players turned to selling for profit-taking, and the currency
slipped from the opening rate, said a trader with the Bank of Tokyo,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Many investors, however, were making little moves except for
position adjustments, he added.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly conducted a dollar-selling market
intervention to halt its further rise against the yen. The central
bank does not comment on its monetary actions.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the index's rise followed
gains in the Dow Jones industrial average of 30 major issues in New
York overnight.
   While institutional investors were reluctant to make major moves
ahead of the Japanese parliamentary election Sunday, individuals
actively bought, said one trader with a major securities firm in
Tokyo, speaking anonymously.
</TEXT>
