<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0509EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DebtLimit     07-20 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Debt Limit,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Takes First Step To Avoid Exceeding Debt Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department is moving to avoid
exceeding the national debt limit next month even while urging
Congress to extend the ceiling before lawmakers leave for a
month-long August recess.
   ``It is virtually certain, absent such action, that Treasury will
run out of cash and default on its obligations on Aug. 15,''
Undersecretary Robert R. Glauber told Senate Finance taxation and
debt management subcommittee Wednesday.
   ``I urge you to seek the cooperation of your colleagues and to
act quickly on the debt limit in order to prevent unnecessary
problems in Treasury financing operations and default on the
government's obligations,'' he said.
   The government is seeking a $300 billion increase in the current
$2.8 trillion long-term debt ceiling. Without an increase, Treasury
officials say the government would have problems issuing paychecks
and Social Security payments in September.
   The House already has passed such legislation.
   Shortly before Glauber appeared on Capitol Hill, the Treasury
Department announced it was suspending indefinitely the sale of
special securities for state and local governments. Such action has
been taken before when Congress was unable to agree on legislation
raising the debt limit.
   State and local governments buy the special Treasury securities
as a temporary investment vehicle for money they raise in the bond
market. If the securities are not available, it could force
cancellation of bond sales by state and local governments, leading
to confusion and turmoil in the municipal bond market.
   Glauber did not mention the suspension in his testimony on
Capitol Hill, but he did warn of the other effects of congressional
inaction on the debt limit increase.
   ``Without an increase in the debt limit by Aug. 1, full
investment of the Social Security trust funds may not be possible,''
he said.
   The Treasury is required by law to invest the trust fund assets
in interest-bearing government securities, which are a form of
government debt and are counted with other government bonds and
notes against the debt limit.
   While Congress normally appropriates money to cover any interest
lost to the trust funds during a period when they cannot be
invested, this action has raised complaints from interest groups
representing the elderly.
   Glauber also warned that congressional inaction into September
would prevent the Treasury from paying the government payroll for
September, including payroll and pension checks exceeding $23
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
