<SECOND>PM-BRF--Blizzard Deaths,0121</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 3,000 Gold Prospectors Still Trapped by Snows, 67 Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 3,000 gold prospectors have been
stranded for two months in remote western China by blizzards and bad
weather and 67 have died of starvation, exposure or illness, an
official newspaper said today.
   Worker's Daily said 8,000 miners and 1,000 of their vehicles were
trapped by blizzards in May in the Hoh Xil Lake area of Qinghai
province, more than 16,500 feet above sea level.
   Rescue workers have sent in 39 trucks, but 3,000 people remain
stranded, the paper said. The government dropped 8.5 tons of food
into the area two weeks ago after two previous attempts failed
because of bad weather.
