<FIRST>r w PM-ForeignAid     07-20 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foreign Aid,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Foreign Aid Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House plans to vote Friday on a $14.35
billion foreign aid bill that puts $15 million behind President
Bush's promise to encourage economic reform in Hungary and Poland.
   Bush announced the programs last week during visits to Eastern
Europe, pledging a $100 million fund to support private business
initiatives in Poland and $25 million to encourage enterprises in
Hungary.
   The measure, passed by the House Appropriations Committee on
Wednesday, provides economic, military and development aid for
friendly countries around the world. It goes before the full House
on Friday.
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chairman of the panel's foreign
operations subcommittee, said the $15 million figure was an informal
estimate of the cost of beginning to meet Bush's pledges in fiscal
1990, which begins Oct. 1. The administration has so far made no
formal request to Congress for the aid, he said.
   Of that amount, $10 million is for Poland and $5 million for
Hungary.
   In its report, the Appropriations Committee called Poland's June
elections and other developments encouraging and ``reasons to
believe that real progress can take place and can be sustained over
a period of time.''
   Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., said Republicans and the Bush
administration will support the foreign aid bill in the House, but
will work in the Senate to shift more money to military aid and make
a series of other changes.
   The bill also included:
   _$160 million for a new Multilateral Assistance Initiative for
the Philippines, $40 million less than the administration has
requested. ``I don't think, given the Philippine track record (of
poor management), we ought to be putting in a dime,'' Obey said. But
he said the $160 million represented a compromise with the
administration, which sees the program as a key to bolstering the
fledgling democracy led by Corazon Aquino.
   _A maximum of $85 million in military aid to the government of El
Salvador. In a gesture of support to newly elected president Alfredo
Cristiani of the right-wing ARENA party, the committee declined to
attach strings to the aid. Some liberal lawmakers had sought to
release the aid in two increments, depending on the new government's
performance in suppressing the activities of right-wing death squads.
   _A total of $410 million for migration and refugee assistance,
$40 million more than the administration asked. The committee noted
increased emigration of Soviet Jews as well as growing refugee needs
in Africa and along the Thai-Cambodian border.
   _$105 million for the African Development Fund, which provides
low-interest loans for development programs in the poorest
countries; $144 million to the African Development Bank, which makes
market-rate loans for agriculture and public works projects; $515
million for development aid to sub-Saharan Africa; and $50 million
in development money for countries bordering South Africa. The bill
also recommends $2 million be set aside for protection of African
elephants.
   _Mild restrictions on the $958 million allocation to the
International Development Association as an indication of
displeasure over loans to China, whose crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators has provoked outrage on Capitol Hill.
   As usual, Israel and Egypt receive the lion's share of U.S. aid
money. Israel would get $3 billion in combined military and economic
aid, and Egypt would receive $2 billion.
   The bill also provides $20 million for a program to promote peace
in Northern Ireland; $230 million in military aid to Pakistan; $12
million for the West Bank and Gaza strip for education, health and
agriculture programs; $270 million as part of various drug control
programs; and $65 million for the United Nations Children's Fund.
</TEXT>
