<FIRST>r w PM-Senate-ForeignPolicy     07-20 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate-Foreign Policy,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Rebuke Mexico Over Drugs, Dabble in World Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Senate resumes debate about 10 a.m. EDT; top likely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is demanding increased cooperation
from Mexico in the war on drugs in a move described by opponents as
a direct rebuke to that country's new president, Carlos Salinas de
Gortari.
   Senators added the provision Wednesday to a $4.6 billion State
Department authorization bill for next year, along with dabbling in
dozens of other world issues from Fidel Castro's right to hold power
in Cuba to bare grocery shelves in Romania.
   But senators were unable to resolve a dispute over an amendment
proposed by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., barring official U.S. talks
with representatives of the Palestine Liberation Organization who
have been involved in terrorism against Americans.
   In one provision, senators said they would not accept any nominee
for administrator of the Panama Canal who is selected by Panama's
current ruler, Gen. Manuel Noriega.
   The treaty under which the United States will turn over the canal
to Panama calls for a Panamanian administrator acceptable to the
White House to be appointed next year by Panama and confirmed by the
Senate.
   Helms also sponsored the provision dealing with Mexico, arguing
the United States' southern neighbor remains the primary source of
heroin and marijuana and a leading transit point for U.S.-bound
cocaine.
   Despite anti-drug rhetoric from the Salinas government, Mexico
still has not granted U.S. requests for the right to fly drug
surveillance flights over the country, to pursue drug smugglers into
Mexico, or to grant access to bank records sought by U.S. drug
investigators, said Helms, a perennial critic of Mexico.
   The non-binding amendment expressed the ``sense of Congress''
that Mexico should negotiate with the United States on those and
other drug issues.
   Helms said the amendment was intended to support Salinas'
anti-drug statements and to send ``a signal as to how we will
measure their cooperation next year'' when it comes time to certify
whether Mexico is eligible for continued U.S. trade preferences and
other aid.
   But Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said the move would damage U.S.
relations with the new Mexican government, calling it ``a
counterproductive and failed attempt to engage in another round of
Mexico bashing.''
   In a flurry of other foreign-policy pronouncements, the Senate:
   _Approved a provision intended to slow down an emerging
U.S.-Korean deal for co-production of a military fighter plane. The
provision calls for a study on how such a deal would affect U.S.
industrial capacity and long-term competitiveness.
   _Voted 99-0 to call on Cuban President Fidel Castro to hold a
national plebiscite on whether he should continue in power, and if a
majority does not support him, to step down.
   _Approved a provision to rename a small park across the street
from the Chinese Embassy in Washington as ``Tiananmen Square Park''
in honor of pro-democracy demonstrators killed in Beijing's
crackdown last month.
   _Called on the administration to bar the import of Romanian meat
and wine ``until such time as the Romanian government ceases to
withhold food from the Romanian people.''
</TEXT>
