<FIRST>r w PM-RootSued     07-20 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Root Sued,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot of Wandering Plane Sued</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wandering Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Georgia company claims the pilot who crashed
his private plane into notoriety unlawfully billed the firm twice
for work he did and illegally converted thousands of dollars of
company money to his own use.
   Sonrise Management Services Inc. of Columbus, Ga., filed suit in
U.S. District Court against Thomas Root demanding the return of
$334,000 plus $250,000 in damages.
   Root, a communications lawyer, is accused of failing to represent
investors he was hired to speak for before the Federal
Communications Commission. The suit alleges Root took in an extra
$100,000 through double billing.
   Root is recovering from his plunge into the waters off the
Bahamas last week and the mysterious gunshot wound which he says he
does not remember receiving.
   In its court papers filed this week, Sonrise says it paid Root
$1.9 million since March 1986 as an advance against legal fees and
expenses and to reimburse him for FCC filing and hearing fees.
   Sonrise, which assists investors inexperienced in broadcasting
but with an interest in operating new FM stations to apply for
construction permits, alleges Root failed to adequately represent
nine groups of investors seeking permits.
   Sonrise said that last August it paid Root $75,000 that he was to
give to applicants for an FM station in Omega, Ga. Sonrise charges
the applicants never got the money and Root converted the funds to
his own use.
   Last November, said Sonrise, it paid Root $40,000 to hold in an
escrow account to buy the construction permit of an FM station in
Galva, Ill. The agreement was never executed and Root converted the
money, the suit said.
   The suit also accused Root of billing Sonrise twice for the same
services from April 1987 through August 1988, with overpayments
amounting to $54,200.
   In another case, Root's escrow account also was paid $45,000
twice to buy a construction permit for an FM station in Olney, Texas.
</TEXT>
