<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0551EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-StealthBomber     07-20 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stealth Bomber,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Declassifies List of Contractors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The B-2 stealth bomber, once one of the
Pentagon's most closely-guarded secret weapons systems, is becoming
more public each day.
   The latest Pentagon step in its high-profile campaign to surmount
congressional opposition to the expensive bomber is the
declassification of a list of 156 contractors in 26 states and the
District of Columbia involved in the program.
   ``The U.S. Air Force's B-2 program is supported nationwide by
tens of thousands of men and women at prime contractor Northrop
Corp., key subcontractors Boeing, LTV, General Electric and Hughes,
and other suppliers and subcontractors in 46 states,'' Northrop said
in a five-page memorandum received Wednesday.
   The memo, which includes the recently-declassified list of
contractors, was sent to members of Congress this week.
   The B-2 program has been shrouded in secrecy for nearly 10 years,
but as opposition to the expensive aircraft has grown in Congress,
the Air Force has been more forthcoming with information.
   Last week, Air Force Secretary Donald Rice and Chief of Staff
Larry Welch briefed members of the House Armed Services Committee in
an open session that included a color-slide presentation on the
plane.
   On Monday, the aircraft took off on its maiden two-hour test
flight with a huge bank of television cameras trained on it as it
flew over the Mojave Desert.
   Asked about the change in public access to the bomber at the test
flight, Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said Tuesday, ``It's a
wonderful country, isn't it?''
   The publicity campaign contrasts sharply with another weapon, the
super-secret F-117A stealth fighter, which remains under wraps.
``I'd urge you not to mix different planes and different missions,''
Williams said.
   Despite the successful flight, congressional opposition remains
to the radar-evading aircraft that at $530 million a copy is the
most expensive in history.
   The Pentagon hopes to buy 132 planes at a cost of about $70
billion.
   One Republican, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, said of the Northrop
memo, ``The company has now fallen back to selling the B-2 as a jobs
program. But I doubt Congress will be blinded by the smoke screen
that Northrop is trying to throw over us.''
   In fiscal 1990, the Defense Department has proposed spending $4.7
billion for the B-2, but last month the House Armed Services panel
cut $800 million from the budget. Money for the B-2 is expected to
be the most controversial item next week when the House and Senate
consider the defense bill.
</TEXT>
