<FIRST>r a PM-HollywoodSecurity     07-20 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hollywood Security,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actress Murder and Studio Shooting Highlight Hollywood Dangers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Actress Slain, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The murder of actress Rebecca Schaeffer and the
fiery assault on Lorimar Studios this week dramatize the increased
perils of living in the glare of Hollywood's bright lights.
   Entertainers have long employed security, if only to fend off the
paparazzi. But a string of recent incidents, including threats and
attacks involving actors such as Michael J. Fox and Michael Landon,
have prompted some stars to take greater safety measures.
   Gavin de Becker, Hollywood's leading security consultant, said
the killing of Miss Schaeffer bore similarities to the knife attack
seven years ago of his client, ``Raging Bull'' actress Theresa
Saldana.
   ``This was not Victoria Principal or Madonna,'' de Becker said
Wednesday. ``This was somebody with a far smaller audience. There is
a dynamic that says, `Whitney Houston is for everyone, but you're
for me.''
   ``There are more kooks in the world,'' said Ron Wells, business
manager of the American Federation of Guards here, a union
overseeing the 300 guards who protect studio gates.
   Robert John Bardo, 19, of Tucson, Ariz., was an obsessive fan of
Miss Schaeffer, police said Wednesday as Bardo was charged with
murder in the shooting death of the 21-year-old co-star of the
1986-88 CBS sitcom, ``My Sister Sam.''
   Investigators looking into another violent attack on Tuesday
believe Edward Phillips Jr., 43, of Corydon, Ind., was angered by a
business dispute with ``Dallas'' star Ken Kercheval over a popcorn
company.
   Phillips crashed a truck through the gate at Lorimar where
``Dallas'' is filmed, fired a burst of shotgun blasts, set his
vehicle afire and then killed himself.
   De Becker said he is in constant demand because of an exponential
growth in the volume of fan nuisance letters in recent years. He has
expanded into providing security for celebrity weddings and handled
last year's nuptials between Fox and actress Tracy Pollan.
   In an unusual departure, Eddie Murphy has set up a separate
security post at the offices of his new production company, even
though it sits on the Paramount Studios lot, itself protected by a
squadron of guards.
   When Murphy appears publicly, he is surrounded by a squadron of
guards and friends.
   Record producer Phil Spector is legendary for not making a move
without a security guard present, even though few people would
recognize him. Prince rarely appears without bodyguard accompaniment.
   Elizabeth Taylor and other stars have installed elaborate
security systems around their homes, often including cameras and
fence enclosures. Local tabloid reporters single out Olivia Newton
John, Sylvester Stallone and Johnny Carson for having the most
sophisticated protection.
   But despite the security, few celebrities may be completely
beyond the public's reach.
   ``The access is there if somebody wants to get to a celebrity,''
said Barry Levine, West Coast bureau chief for the tabloid Star,
itself an expert at gate-crashing. ``The stars can have security
guards and security systems more sensitive than a bank's, but people
can still buy a star map for $2 and haunt these people.
   ``There really seems to be a rash of these things. We seem to do
more stories about obsessed fans than anything else.''
   This week, 26-year-old Tina Marie-Ledbetter pleaded innocent in
Los Angeles Superior Court to sending thousands of threatening
letters and rabbit droppings to Fox, star of the former hit series,
``Family Ties.'' She was ordered to remain without bail at the Sybil
Brand Institute for Women.
   Two guards were shot and killed at Universal Studios last
December by a man who demanded to see Landon, star of ``Highway to
Heaven.'' Nathan Trupp, 44, of New Mexico, has pleaded innocent to
the charges.
   A deranged fan of Miss Saldana may be released early next year
after serving half of a 12-year sentence for a knife attack against
the actress. Arthur Jackson, a 53-year-old Scottish drifter,
attacked the actress in 1982, stabbing her 10 times with a kitchen
knife.
   ``I'm trying not to allow it to bring back bad memories for me,''
Miss Saldana said Wednesday of Miss Schaeffer's murder. ``I really
had a hard time with it this morning.''
   In true Hollywood fashion, celebrity stalking has been in the
news so much in recent years that the practice has sparked two
movies: 1981's ``The Fan,'' starring Lauren Bacall and 1982's ``The
Seduction,'' featuring Morgan Fairchild.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
