<DOCNO> AP890720-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StudioShooting     07-20 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Studio Shooting,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Failed Business Deal Apparently Provoked Movie Set Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who drove a truck through a
studio gate, set it afire and then committed suicide had claimed he
was the victim of a ``rotten, stinking deal'' involving ``Dallas''
star Ken Kercheval.
   Edward Phillips Jr., 43, of Corydon, Ind., was voted out of his
management position at Old Capital Popcorn in April 1988 by his then
wife, Linda, and Kercheval, who had bought the company from the
couple.
   Phillips fired 12-gauge shotgun blasts at the outside walls of a
sound stage where ``Dallas'' is filmed before shooting himself in
the chest on Tuesday.
   An article detailing the Corydon-based popcorn maker's financial
woes, published in April by The Courier-Journal of Louisville, Ky.,
was among items Phillips handed to a studio guard at the beginning
of his rampage, police said Wednesday.
   Phillips, a former farm-implement dealer, purchased Old Capital
Popcorn with his ex-wife in 1983.
   Kercheval liked the popcorn so much he invested $998,800 in the
company in 1985, acquiring a one-third interest. In April 1988, he
bought out the remainder of the company.
   In a statement issued through his publicist, Kercheval said he
was ``shocked and astonished'' by the suicide.
   The 54-year-old actor said that after he bought the company,
Phillips ``on several occasions exhibited irrational behavior that
frightened my family and associates.''
   Kercheval plays oil tycoon Cliff Barnes on the CBS series, which
is produced by Lorimar-Telepictures Corp.
   Late Tuesday afternoon, Phillips drove an 18-foot truck to a gate
at the Lorimar lot 10 miles east of downtown Los Angeles. With the
newspaper article and truck rental papers, he handed a security
guard two canisters of methyl bromide gas, telling him, ``You have
five minutes to live,'' police said.
   Methyl bromide is a caustic gas used to make popcorn, police Lt.
Bill Burck said.
   Phillips then drove through the gate, set the truck afire near a
sound stage and fired five blasts from a shotgun into nearby stage
walls as he yelled for people to stay away.
   Within minutes, police surrounded the gunman and Phillips shot
himself as they closed in. A bomb squad was called to the scene
after firefighters spotted what later proved to be a dummy hand
grenade inside the charred remains of the truck.
   Phillips was quoted in The Courier-Journal article as saying he
was devastated last year when he lost control of the popcorn firm
and his wife sued for divorce. Afterward, he said he admitted
himself briefly to an Ohio hospital for treatment of depression.
   Although the partnership seemed promising after Kercheval took
his first stake in 1985, Phillips and Kercheval clashed often over
corporate strategies and marketing decisions.
   Three years later, Linda Phillips and Kercheval voted against
renewing Phillips' management contract.
   A variety of disputes prompted numerous lawsuits in the case,
which left Phillips deeply embittered, the newspaper quoted Phillips
as saying, ``It was a rotten, stinking deal.''
   Linda Phillips declined to comment on the matter. ``It's just too
much right now,'' she was quoted as saying in today's Los Angeles
Times.
</TEXT>
