<FIRST>r w PM-DC-10History 1stLd-Writethru a0498 07-20 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 History, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC-10 Has Troubled History</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to restores AP Logo; SUBS 4th graf, `Wednesday's
crash ...' to give latest figure for the number aboard.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crash of a DC-10 in Iowa comes just as
McDonnell Douglas prepares to deliver the last of the workhorse
airliners plagued by some of history's worst air disasters.
   The wide-bodied, three-engine aircraft used by 51 world airlines
and built by McDonnell Douglas has had cargo door problems, been
accused of design flaws and was once grounded for more than a month
by the Federal Aviation Administration.
   The DC-10s have been the workhorse of many airlines, carrying
from 250 to 380 passengers, depending upon how their interior is
configured.
   A DC-10 was involved in history's worst U.S. air disaster that
killed 273 people in Chicago in 1979 and in one of the worst
single-plane disasters in the world, the 1974 crash of a Turkish
Airliner in Paris that killed 346 people.
   Wednesday's crash of United Airlines Flight 232 on its way from
Denver to Chicago during an emergency landing attempt in Iowa had
the potential of eclipsing the 1979 crash, but more than half the
293 people aboard survived after the plane cartwheeled into the
ground in a ball of flames.
   The pilot had radioed ``complete hydraulic failure'' prior to the
crash landing, FAA officials in Washington said.
   Failure of the hydraulics system, which is the main means of
controlling wing flaps and other mechanisms that guide the aircraft,
also has figured in other DC-10 crashes, although the primary cause
has varied.
   The Turkish Airlines crash was blamed on faulty cargo door
design, which was later altered after nonfatal incidents of doors
popping off other DC-10s in the United States and Canada. The loss
of the door led to decompression that buckled the floor which, in
turn, severed hydraulic lines essential to taking off, steering and
landing an airliner.
   Floors in wide-bodied jets were strengthened and hydraulic lines
rerouted after the incidents.
   In the Chicago American Airlines crash, hydraulic lines along the
wings were severed when one of the plane's engines came loose and
somersaulted over the wing.
   The FAA grounded all U.S. DC-10s but allowed them to fly 37 days
later. The National Transportation Board determined erroneous
maintenance procedures by American Airlines caused the engine
supports to crack. The board also said some systems in the plane
were vulnerable to damage.
   Jim Reed, spokesman for McDonnell Douglas in St. Louis, said 445
DC-10s have been built since 1969, including military models dubbed
KC-10s.
   Plagued by financial losses following the Chicago crash and heavy
competition from other wide-body airliners, the company's Douglas
Aircraft unit announced in 1983 it was ending production of the
model, except for military tanker versions that were on order.
   Two passenger planes remained unsold, and the last one of those
is to be delivered to Nigeria Airlines in a few weeks, Reed said.
   In 1980, a retired American Airlines pilot, Fred G. Johnson, told
a news conference he had refused to fly the DC-10 during his last
six months as a captain because it was unsafe.
   He said although the plane has several hydraulic systems, they
are interconnected through pumps so that failure of one system
jeopardizes the others.
   McDonnell Douglas officials have consistently defended the
aircraft as safe, blaming bad publicity for a decline in orders.
   The big tri-jets also have been involved in several crashes that
were blamed on pilot error or problems not related to design or
maintenance.
   In addition to the Chicago crash, two other DC-10s crashed in
1979. An Air New Zealand model hit the rocky slopes of a volcano at
the edge of Antarctica, killing all 257 people aboard. And 74 people
died when the pilot of a Western Airlines DC-10 landed on a Mexico
City runway that was closed for repairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
