<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest     07-20 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Can't Stop Mob Violence in Resort Region, Soviet Reports Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities evacuated 1,500 tourists and banned new
visitors from the Black Sea region of Abkhazia, where troops have
been unable to halt a bloody feud between rival ethnic groups,
Soviet media said today.
   Armed bands of Georgians and Abkhazians continued to roam the
roads in the resort area 870 miles south of Moscow, Tass said.
   Authorities declared a state of emergency and imposed a curfew in
the region on Tuesday and by today had confiscated more than 2,500
firearms, Radio Moscow said.
   But the report said ``attacks on citizens, policemen, and army
servicemen'' continued Wednesday night in the Abkhazian capital of
Sukhumi.
   Soviet news reports said Interior Ministry troops and police were
confiscating weapons from rioters, but Komsomolskaya Pravda, the
Communist Youth League newspaper, reported today that Sukhumi police
had to return some firearms to fear-stricken residents.
   The paper said police were forced to ``give way to the demands of
people tortured by fear and rumors, who surrounded the district
Interior Ministry building and demanded the return of their hunting
weapons for self-defense.''
   The violence has claimed at least 18 lives since it began
Saturday in Abkhazia, a 3,320-mile autonomous region in the southern
Soviet republic of Georgia. Komsomolskaya Pravda reported today that
339 people have been injured.
   Georgians outnumber Abkhazians 240,000 to 90,000 in the region
and both sides claim discrimination by the other. Many Abkhazians
demand that it be designated a 16th Soviet republic.
   Authorities banned visitors to the region, where millions of
tourists vacation every year, Tass said today. It said that 1,500
people were flown out in a 24-hour period ending today.
   The violence has halted road and rail transportation.
   More than 120 people have died in ethnic unrest in the past month
in the Soviet Union's southern republics of Georgia, Azerbaijan,
Kazakhstan, and Uzbekistan.
   In Abkhazia, armed rioters traveling in cars have attacked troops
and citizens for the purpose of seizing weapons, Tass said. Rioters
have attacked a hydroelectric dam and shot up two trains.
   With strikes widespread in Sukhumi, food supplies have been
interrupted and long bread lines form each morning, Komsomolskaya
Pravda said.
   Rules for citizens under the state of emergency forbid large
street gatherings, ban the use of private cars and require all
firearms to be surrendered to authorities.
   The order also includes an 11 p.m.-to-6 a.m. curfew.
</TEXT>
