<FIRST>r w PM-InfantMortality     07-20 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Infant Mortality,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C.'s Infant Mortality Rate More Than Double National Average</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RETRANSMITTING to fix category code.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The infant mortality rate in the nation's
capital jumped to more than twice the national average last year,
largely due to an increase in drug abuse among pregnant women, city
officials say.
   The District of Columbia saw 23.2 infant deaths per 1,000 births
in 1988, the highest level since 1980 and more than double the
national average of 9.9 deaths per 1,000 births, the city reported
Wednesday. The new statistics represented a substantial increase
over the 1987 rate of 19.6 deaths per 1,000 births.
   ``It's as if ... we've been hit by a hurricane that government
can't control,'' said Patricia A. Tompkins, chief of the Office of
Maternal and Child Health. ``There's a tremendous amount of drug
abuse among women of childbearing age.''
   Tomkins said the city expected an increase, but not one so
dramatic. ``It was kind of a shock,'' she said.
   The district's rise in infant mortality followed several years of
modest success in curbing what has long been identified as one of
the district's biggest health problems. Until 1988, the infant
mortality rate had been relatively stable for four years, and had
declined slightly in 1987.
   D.C. Mayor Marion Barry has made infant mortality a major part of
its health care agenda. But the city's efforts have been overwhelmed
by the crack cocaine epidemic, which has swamped hospitals with the
babies of drug addicts. Women who use drugs often give birth to
infants with low birth weights who have an increased likelihood of
dying before they reach their first birthdays.
</TEXT>
