<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-20 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Defense Minister Promises U.S. Jet Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney is praising South
Korea's decision to purchase U.S. fighter jets but indicates the
sensitive topic of co-production of the sophisticated fighters
hasn't been resolved.
   Cheney met with reporters Wednesday after completing the annual
series of talks with his South Korean counterpart, Lee Sang Hoon.
   ``I would like to get the best deal that we can,'' Cheney said
when asked about the issue.
   The subject of co-production, eagerly sought by the South
Koreans, has raised concern among some lawmakers on Capitol Hill
about the risks of transferring sensitive technology to a nation
eager to build its own aviation industry.
   Lee told reporters South Korea intends to purchase U.S. fighters
but has not yet decided which type.
   Asked about a possible co-production plan, Cheney said he had
advised his counterpart to purchase U.S.-produced fighters.
   He added, however, that it is in the United States' interest to
see that the Republic of Korea has necessary equipment to upgrade
its air defenses and that the two sides ``have been discussing the
best method'' by which that can be accomplished.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Economists Call for More Investment in Programs that Aid People</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New taxes are needed to pay for programs to
improve education, public health and technology, economists told a
congressional panel.
   Nobel Prize-winning economist James Tobin said lawmakers intent
on debating the federal deficit are ignoring the basic need for
investment in people.
   Tobin joined 326 other economists in signing a statement
Wednesday saying that failure to increase investment in such things
as education, public health, transportation and technology ``will
have a crippling effect on America's future competitiveness.''
   The increased investment must be paid for through cuts in
military and agriculture subsidy spending, as well as with revenue
from new taxes, according to the statement by the Economic Policy
Institute, a Washington-based think tank.
   ``We need sooner or later, preferably sooner, to break the
political taboo on raising federal revenues,'' Tobin said.
   Princeton University economist Alan S. Blinder, also testifying
Wednesday before the Congressional Joint Economic Committee, said
the government's ``unending obsession'' with the deficit will
adversely affect future productivity and standards of living.
   Blinder said the government must invest more in such things as
programs to aid disadvantaged children and to improve roads, bridges
and sewer facilities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Cheney Worried About Computer Exports to Soviets</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney says he's
concerned that the administration's decision to allow the sale of
personal computers to Soviet bloc nations gives them computers
``with military applications.''
   Cheney commented on the issue Wednesday in an effort to clarify a
Washington Post story that said he had been ``persuaded'' by
Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher to support the decision.
   ``I do not support that decision,'' Cheney said, appearing
clearly irritated.
   The secretary said he opposed the move because it would give the
Soviets ``significant capabilities they do not now possess.''
   Cheney's comments revealed the fierce debate waged inside
President Bush's Cabinet over the decision, which marks a major
shift in policy from the previous administration.
   Conservative members of that administration had sought to retain
tight control of high-tech exports to the Soviets. But this
administration's shift appears to have been influenced by the more
open attitude between the superpowers fostered by Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
