<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Sharon 3rdLd-Writethru a0482 07-20 0886</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Sharon, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0482,0911</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Hawk's Influence Grows With Frustrations Over Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To CORRECT title of columnist, ADD reaction of Shamir spokesman
to report he considering firing Sharon, SUB 13 grafs for 13-22 pvs, `Suddenly
Sharon ... to you.''' Picks up 23rd pvs, `Despite his ...' EDITS thereafter
to trim. ^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capitalizing on Israeli frustration over the
Palestinian uprising, Ariel Sharon has moved into a strong position
in the right-wing Likud bloc and challenged Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir.
   Six years ago Sharon was disgraced and forced to resign as
defense minister for failing to prevent the massacre of more than
800 Palestinians by Lebanese Christians who were allowed into
Israeli-encircled refugee camps in Beirut.
   But Sharon, 61, has fought his way out of the political
wilderness, assuring Israelis he knows how to crush the 19-month
Palestinian uprising, which has claimed 570 Arab and 37 Israeli
lives.
   Speaking in the Israeli-annexed Golan Heights this week, Sharon
suggested one way to improve the situation was to ``liquidate'' PLO
chief Yasser Arafat and other PLO officials.
   The comment was criticized by the U.S. State Department as
unhelpful to peace efforts. But at home, his tough talk is
increasingly welcomed by Israelis frustrated by the violence.
   ``We are at a historic crossroads and in the absence of a
national consensus about which road to take, the extremists gain the
upper hand,'' said Yehoshua Saguy, a Likud member of Parliament.
   ``If the situation continues getting worse, the people will grow
more extremist and feel they are in a time of national emergency. In
emergency conditions there is no room for realpolitik,'' said Saguy,
a former head of military intelligence who like Sharon was forced to
resign after the 1982 massacre.
   Sharon, minister of trade and industry in the coalition Cabinet,
demonstrated his power at a party convention earlier this month in
which he forced Shamir to tack hard-line conditions onto his peace
initiative.
   Sharon's restraints angered Palestinians and drew expressions of
concern from U.S. officials, worried that Shamir's ability to
compromise had been curtailed.
   The conditions included a demand that the uprising be halted
before Shamir's plan for Palestinian elections in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip is implemented and a stipulation that Jewish
settlements would continue to be built in the territories.
   The move almost triggered the breakup of the 8-month-old
coalition with Vice Premier Shimon Peres of the Labor Party
threatening to quit unless the conditions were abandoned.
   Sharon, the most charismatic and controversial figure in Likud,
has made no secret of the fact that he wants the party leadership.
Some analysts are now viewing him as a serious contender for the
first time.
   ``Suddenly Sharon looks strong and Shamir weak,'' said Nahum
Barnea, a political columnist for the Yediot Ahronot daily and
former editor of the left-wing Koteret Rashit magazine.
   ``There's no doubt that he (Sharon) is now dictating the party's
policy.''
   Sharon's comeback has generated tension between the two men.
Their dispute broke into the open today, with two major Israeli
newspapers _ Yediot Ahronot and Haaretz _ reporting that Shamir was
considering firing Sharon.
   Shamir's spokesman Yossi Ahimeir declined direct comment on the
reports.
   He suggested the premier was seeking to avoid splits in his party
and, at the same time, deter internal threats to his peace plan.
   ``The prime minister is concerned about the unity of the Likud.
He has a high tolerance threshold and tries to see things in their
broadest sense,'' Ahimeir said. ``He intends to continue advancing
the peace process. Sharon is only one of 11 (Likud) ministers.''
   According to the two newpapers, Sharon complained at a meeting
Wednesday of Likud leaders meeting that Shamir had not advised him
about the latest contacts between ministers and Palestinians.
   ``I cannot tell you anything, you leak everything you get your
hands on,'' Shamir replied, and also accused Sharon of ``sowing bad
blood and hatred among us.''
   ``I can only laugh at your words,'' Sharon was quoted as saying,
to which Shamir reportedly responded:
   ``He who laughs last laughs best and I don't want to speak to
you.''
   ``No personal attacks or threats to fire me will keep me from
demanding an end to the murder of Jews in the land of Israel,''
Sharon said afterward in a fiery interview on army radio.
   He accused the government of devoting too little time to
discussing the uprising, and world pressure on Israel to speak to
the PLO.
   ``In the U.S. Senate there is a tough ongoing debate on this
subject, and there they aren't being murdered ever day. And here
just anything goes?,'' Sharon said.
   Despite his irascible style, Sharon has strong public confidence.
   A poll of 1,206 Israelis conducted in May by the independent
Modiin Ezrachi Agency showed 44.4 percent had more confidence in
Sharon's ability to quell the uprising than in any other leader.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin of Labor won only 25.4 percent
support in the poll.
   ``I wouldn't necessarily use tougher measures, only different
ones,'' Sharon told a reporter recently.
   Although he declined to go into detail, Sharon pointed to his
record as a guerrilla fighter. He formed Israel's first commando
squad, known as Unit 101, and led the force on raids into Jordan in
the 1950s.
</TEXT>
