<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-US     07-20 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-US,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Aide Confirms Bush Letter, Claims It Was Supportive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
today confirmed that the premier received a letter from President
Bush condemning Jewish settlement building in the occupied lands as
an obstacle to peace.
   The spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir, also said that Shamir had sent a
written response rejecting Bush's contention and saying he believed
that the settlements should have nothing to do with peace efforts.
   But Ahimeir denied a report that Bush had urged Israel, in the
letter of last month, to abandon hopes of a ``greater Israel.''
   The report, carried by National Public Radio from Washington on
Tuesday, said Bush urged Israel to halt settlement building in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip. Israel radio also carried the report.
   NPR also quoted Bush as reiterating a remark Secretary of State
James A. Baker III made to pro-Israeli lobbyists on May 22 that
Israel give up ideas of annexing the disputed territories.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Robert Hall declined direct
comment on Bush's letter, ``that all sounds like U.S. policy.''
   Ahimeir, interviewed by telephone, confirmed that Bush had
written Shamir at the end of June.
   He declined to quote directly from Bush's letter, but described
its contents as ``friendly, most positive,'' and supportive of
Israel's peace initiative.
   In the letter ``he said nothing on the subject of a greater land
of Israel,'' Ahimeir said. ``He made no mention of it. The letter,
which we received about a month ago is friendly and supports the
Israeli peace initiative and the government's peace efforts.''
   Bush, however, did reiterate longstanding U.S. objections to
Israel's construction of Jewish towns and villages in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, Ahimeir said.
   Since seizing the disputed lands in the 1967 Middle East War,
Israel has built more than 130 of these enclaves, which are home to
about 70,000 Israelis. U.S. officials maintain the settlements run
counter to the U.S.-backed formula for Israel to give up occupied
land in exchange for peace.
   Bush's letter said these ``settlements are an obstacle to the
peace process,'' Ahimeir summarized it as saying.
   Paraphrasing Shamir's response, Ahimeir said, ``Shamir totally
rejects this view, and so he replied. He (Shamir) believes that
settlements have nothing whatsoever to do with his peace
initiative.''
</TEXT>
