<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FilmPreservation     07-20 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Film Preservation,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Film Board Closes Meeting to Curb Confusion About Hollywood's Greatest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel instructed by Congress to name
Hollywood's 25 greatest movies went behind closed doors to debate
the merits of films such as ``The Grapes of Wrath'' and ``Citizen
Kane.''
   Wednesday's meeting was closed to the public over the protests of
reporters from The New York Times, the Los Angeles Times and Daily
Variety, an observer said.
   Erich Schwartz, an attorney for the librarian of Congress charged
with overseeing the selections, said the meeting was conducted
secretly to dispel public confusion about the panel's work and to
promote ``spirited discussion.''
   ``There was nothing Machiavellian in the decision to close the
meeting,'' said Schwartz.
   ``My personal feeling is that they didn't want to hurt any
filmmaker's feelings while discussing the merits of one picture over
another,'' said Jane Galbraith, a film reviewer and reporter for
Daily Variety. ``They didn't want to be associated with critical
comments about people that they work with.''
   The meeting had been billed as a public discussion of
recommendations the board would make to the librarian of Congress
for the first 25 films to be protected under the National Film
Preservation Act of 1988.
   The act, drafted in response to outcries about the practice of
coloring old black-and-white movies, stipulates that a panel of
experts select 25 titles each year for a national film register.
   Selected films can still be colored, but the act requires that
they're labelled as having been altered without the participation of
the original makers of the film.
   The National Film Preservation Board, composed of representatives
of 13 film groups, began meeting in a public session at the
University of California, Los Angeles.
   Chairwoman Fay Kanin, a representative of the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences, moved to close the meeting to the public
after almost 1{ hours.
   Schwartz said the board had already satisfied requirements under
the act to hold two public meetings and was under no legal
obligation to continue meeting in public session.
   Instead of reaching agreement on a list Wednesday, Schwartz said
each board member would compose his or her own personal list and
submit it to the librarian of Congress, James Billington. Then
Billington will make the final decision, announcing the choices in
September, he said.
   The move to a secret session was especially perplexing as board
members had discussed the nominations publicly prior to the meeting.
   In preliminary polling, 57 movies were nominated by at least two
of 13 members of the preservation board. The leader was ``The Grapes
of Wrath'' with eight votes. ``Casablanca'' and ``It's a Wonderful
Life'' each drew seven votes; ``The Best Years of Our Lives,'`
``Citizen Kane'' and ``On the Waterfront'' all received six votes.
   ``They just made this decision at their luncheon today, and they
didn't tell anybody about it,'' said Mary Tokita, a spokeswoman for
the UCLA College of Fine Arts who had volunteered to handle
publicity for the board.
</TEXT>
