<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Gangsters     07-20 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Gangsters,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Huge Crime Syndicate Holds Quiet Ceremony For New Boss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police claimed a victory today as the huge
Yamaguchi-gumi organized crime syndicate abandoned plans for an
elaborate inauguration for its new boss, opting instead for a quiet
gathering at its headquarters.
   ``Our pressure and hard work paid off,'' said a police official
in Kobe, a port city in western Japan where the 21,000-member gang
is based.
   He said police around the country had requested hotels and large
banquet halls not to accept reservations from the gang, which, with
no where else to go, finally had to hold the ceremony in a large
room on the second floor of its headquarters building.
   The official, who requested anonymity, said about 300 police
officers surrounded the building, located on a hill in an expensive
residential area, as 105 gangsters attended the two-hour fete.
   He said there were no arrests.
   When new boss Yoshinori Watanabe's predecessor, Masahisa
Takenaka, was inauguarated in Naruto on the southern island of
Shikoku in July 1984, about 1,000 police were mobilized.
   More than 300 gangsters, many dressed in black suits or kimono,
attended, although no incidents were reported.
   In 1985, Takenaka was killed in a leadership dispute that divided
the gang into two rival camps. More than two dozen deaths and 315
shootings made the ensuing conflict the bloodiest ever in Japan's
underworld.
   During today's ceremony, Watanabe is believed to have received
three ``treasures'' symbolic of his post, a tradition mocking the
three sacred treasures that have been passed down from emperor to
emperor for centuries.
   ``We don't expect anything to change under Watanabe,'' the
officer said. ``And we will keep up our pressure on the gang.''
   Watanabe, 48, heads the powerful Yama-ken gang, based in Kobe.
The gang is the largest within the Yamaguchi-gumi, and claims a
membership of 3,000.
   Police estimate there are nearly 90,000 gangsters, or yakuza, in
Japan and say nearly half are associated with the three biggest
syndicates _ the Yamaguchi-gumi, Sumiyoshi Rengo and the Inagawa-kai.
   Leaders of the Inagawa-kai, based in the Tokyo area, attended
today's ceremony, demonstrating their close relationship with the
Yamaguchi-gumi.
   Watanabe is the fifth boss of the gang, which was founded by
Harukichi Yamaguchi in 1915. When the gang was founded, it had only
50 members.
   Underworld syndicates often keep a high profile by posting signs
outside their offices, and the Yamaguchi-gumi headquarters is a
well-known Kobe landmark.
   Syndicates are involved in extortion, illicit gambling and the
drug and sex trades. They also commonly operate in construction,
real estate, money laundering and entertainment.
   Their activities are mainly limited to Japan, but they are known
to buy guns and drugs from the Philippines, Thailand and Taiwan for
sale here.
   Police estimate the total underworld income at $15 billion
annually.
   Gang members have complex ``family'' relations cemented by
rituals, often patterned on Japan's indigenous Shinto religion,
where rice wine is sipped to seal vows of fidelity.
   Watanabe on May 18 completed his wine-sipping ceremony with the
gang's top leaders. Later that month, he was convicted of assault
and given a 10-month suspended sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
