<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Airports     07-20 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Airports,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives of Crash Victims Grieve in Airports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In airports in Chicago and Denver, people grieved over the United
DC-10 crash. In a Philadelphia airport, some who grieved before came
to console.
   Flight 232, headed to Philadelphia from Denver via Chicago
crashed with 293 aboard Wednesday while attempting an emergency
landing in Sioux City, Iowa. More than half survived.
   Moments after hearing about the crash, four people who lost
relatives in one of the world's worst airline disasters rushed to
Philadelphia International Airport to offer consolation.
   Stan Maslowski and his wife, Norma, both of Haddonfield, N.J.,
lost their 30-year-old daughter, Diane, when a terrorist's bomb blew
up Pan Am Flight 103 on Dec. 21, killing 259 aboard and 11 people in
Lockerbie, Scotland, where the wreckage fell. Two others joined the
couple at the Philadelphia airport.
   ``The purpose of our visit is to comfort the families, to support
those people who wonder if they're family members are alive,''
Maslowski said.
   On Wednesday, though, their message reached no relatives of those
aboard the United flight. Maslowski said United officials told him
no one waiting for passengers had reported to the airport.
   ``It makes it all dredged up again,'' said Norma Maslowski of
their mission. ``It's horrible.''
   Maslowski said the relatives of the Pan Am victims have formed a
network of more than 400 people who are prepared to rush to airports
to console anyone waiting for a plane that had crashed.
   In Denver, United employees escorted 25 to 30 visibly shaken
relatives past ranks of reporters and television cameras. The media
were not allowed into the VIP area.
   United officials at Chicago's O'Hare Airport opened a lounge for
families of those aboard the flight.
   One woman entered crying, her fingertips at her mouth. Two men
leaving refused to speak with a reporter, one swearing as he brushed
by.
   Outside the room, 20 police officers and O'Hare security guards
stood by the entrance.
   Some at the Denver and Chicago airports had news to celebrate.
   Rabbi Avrohom Brownstein and his wife burst out of the VIP room
in Denver where relatives of passengers on the plane had gathered.
They had just heard their 9-year-old son, Yisroel, had survived with
a fractured arm and minor burns.
   ``He's OK. He always wanted to have a broken arm anyway. We just
talked to him on the phone and he's OK,'' Brownstein said.
   United officials in Chicago told Arthur and Christine Bulmann of
New Lenox, Ill., that his sister, Susan Randa, and her young son,
David, of Boulder, Colo., had only minor scratches from the crash.
   ``I think it's a miracle,'' Christine Bulmann said.
</TEXT>
