<DOCNO> AP890720-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Koreas     07-20 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Koreas,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Asks South to Grant Student Safe Re-entry to South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea demanded today that South
Korea not arrest a Seoul college student who violated a ban on
visits to the communist north and now wants to return home,
officials said today.
   North Korea insisted that South Korean Prime Minister Kang
Young-hoon give a public assurance that 20-year-old Im Su-kyong may
return home as a free citizen through the border village of
Panmunjom, officials said.
   ``If she is arrested and persecuted, North-South relations will
be further aggravated, creating a grave obstacle in the road to
peaceful unification,'' the message from North Korea said.
   South Korea said the message was relayed in a telephone call to
South Korean Unification Minister Lee Hong-koo.
   It was not immediately known whether South Korea would allow Miss
Im to cross the border. There have been few mutually acceptable
crossings between the enemy nations since they were divided at the
end of World War II.
   Park Jyun-kyu, chairman of South Korea's governing Democratic
Justice Party, has warned that any North Korean attempt to send the
student back to Seoul through Panmunjom ``will raise havoc on the
present military status quo at the demarcation line.''
   The Demilitarized Zone runs through the middle of the truce
village.
   Also today, North Korean Red Cross chief Son Song-pil sent a
telephone message to his South Korean counterpart requesting
``immediate steps to guarantee personal safety for Miss Im.''
   The Seoul government has announced that Miss Im, a radical
student leader attending Seoul's Hankuk University of Foreign
Studies, would be arrested when she returned from the north and
charged with violating national security law.
   She defied the government's ban on unauthorized travel to North
Korea and traveled by air via Tokyo and East Germany to attend the
July 1-8 World Festival for Youth and Students in the North's
capital of Pyongyang.
   At a news conference in Pyongyang, she said she wanted to return
home through the border to symbolize a unified Korea and planned to
do so on July 27, the anniversary of the cease-fire that ended the
1950-53 Korean War.
   That is also the last day of a planned July 20-27 peace march
aimed at drawing national and international support for unification
of the peninsula.
   Organizers said in Washington on July 6 that the march would
include about 100 foreigners and would be held simultaneously in
both countries, with the two groups meeting at the border in
Panmunjom.
   South Korea regards the march as a pro-communist vehicle to stir
up unrest and tightened immigration proceedures at all ports of
entry to block foreigners who might try to participate. South Korea
prohibits foreigners from engaging in political activity.
   Riot police were deployed today at Mount Halla on the southern
island of Cheju where the march was scheduled to begin, according to
Yonhap, the South Korean news agency. Only journalists and tourists
showed up, the agency said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
