<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0718EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StolenRembrandt     07-20 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stolen Rembrandt,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missing Amsterdam Rembrandt Found in New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Rembrandt drawing stolen 10 years ago from a
Dutch museum is on its way back to Amsterdam today after being
identified by an art expert at Christie's auction house.
   The unsigned artwork came to the auction house from a European
dealer, Christie's spokeswoman Starr Collins said Wednesday. The
drawing was consigned to the dealer by a client who bought it for an
undisclosed sum several years ago as a ``good anonymous drawing,''
she said.
   The auction house routinely tries to attribute all the unsigned
works it receives for auction. Beverly Jacoby, who heads Christie's
Old Masters department, got this one on June 16.
   ``I knew right away it had a very good shot at being a
Rembrandt,'' she said. ``I felt the drawing on stylistic grounds was
very Rembrandtesque and also very high quality.''
   Research quickly confirmed her hunch.
   ``After my initial elation that it was a Rembrandt, I read
through the catalog entry, to the bottom line, where it said,
`Current ownership, Amsterdam Rembrandt House.' That sent alarm
bells ringing and I called our counsel before I did anything else,''
said Jacoby.
   ``We contacted them to inquire and they informed us the drawing
was stolen 10 years ago. I think they were very surprised and very
pleased.''
   The Rembrandt, removed from its original frame, was mounted on
two pieces of glass with tape around the edges.
   The 3-by-5 inch, double-sided drawing is in pen and ink on
handmade paper. One side depicts a child, believed to be Rembrandt's
son, Rombartus; the other a sleeping woman, thought to be his wife,
Saskia.
   ``A drawing of such personal and biographical interest has added
appeal'' and could have fetched more than $100,000 at auction, said
Jacoby.
   The drawing, which was stolen in May 1979, has been handed over
to U.S. Customs and is on its way to the Amsterdam museum, said Ms.
Collins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0502 07-20 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>Devastating Shelling in Beirut</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with Syrians taking direct hit,
higher casualty toll, Hoss appeal to Arab leaders. Picks up 7th pvs, ```May
someone ...' EDITS thereafter to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howitzer shells and rockets rained on
Beirut's Moslem and Christian sectors today in one of the fiercest
overnight duels between Syrian and Christian army gunners in 18
weeks of fighting.
   Police said four people were killed and 49 wounded.
   The shells hit residential buildings on both sides of Beirut's
dividing Green Line, starting hundreds of fires and covering the
city with a blanket of rubble and glass shards.
   Streets were full of cars reduced to smoldering piles of metal.
   Tongues of flame shot up in the sky and smoke billowed from
blasted buildings. Fire brigades were unable to combat blazes due to
a shortage of water caused by a power failure.
   Ambulances, their sirens wailing, sped through the streets to
evacuate the latest casualties, which raised the overall toll to 424
killed and 1,741 wounded since the current round of fighting broke
out March 8.
   Several Syrian artillery positions in West Beirut's seafront Ein
Mreisseh boulevard took direct hits and a police spokesman said many
Syrian soldiers were killed or wounded.
   ``We don't have a breakdown because the Syrian command does not
report its losses to us,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be named
under standing regulations.
   At least eight Syrian army trucks loaded with rocket ammunition
and gasoline were gutted, according to a Lebanese eyewitness.
   One 155mm howitzer shell crashed at a road intersection across
the street from the Italian Embassy in west Beirut's Wardieh
district, wrecking a cluster of chic boutiques and the city's most
fashionable florist, Florelle.
   The barrage, according to police, reached an intensity of about
30 shells per minute at times. Police said at least 700 buildings
and shops were hit in the deadly barrage, which also inflicted
damage on more than 5,000 cars.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem Cabinet
vying for power with the Christian Cabinet, pleaded with the leaders
of Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria to speed up efforts aimed at
resolving Lebanon's crisis.
   In a cable, Hoss said: ``Beirut and its surroundings witnessed a
horrible night of barbaric random shelling.
   ``On behalf of the innocent people of Lebanon, its children,
women and elderly I plead with you to speed up your humanitarian
mission,'' he said.
   The three heads of state were assigned by an Arab summit in May
to find a settlement. Their cease-fire calls have been ignored by
the warring factions.
   ``May someone call the fire brigade. We want an ambulance too,''
a woman screamed from the 11-story Kaaki building in west Beirut's
Zokak Blatt district as fire raged in the top three floors.
   ``Telephone lines are down,'' a man shouted back from a nearby
building. ``Have faith in God, we're coming to help you.''
   The 10th-floor apartment of Fawzi Rida in Kaaki building took two
direct hits from 107mm rockets early today.
   Rida, 37, a Shiite Moslem, said, ``The explosions shattered the
walls and pushed the furniture out of the apartment.''
   ``I stretched a hand to open the door, but there was no door
left,'' he said, his eyes brimming with tears. ``We've nothing left
except the night dresses we are wearing.''
   Residents throughout the city rushed to basements shortly after
the shelling duel broke out late Wednesday night.
   ``There is no district in Beirut and the surrounding mountains
that wasn't targeted by the shelling,'' said a police spokesman, who
cannot be named in line with standing regulations.
   The current round of fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war
began this spring two days after Christian army commander Gen.
Michel Aoun blockaded illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias
south of Beirut.
   Aoun took the measure to salvage about $100 million in lost
customs dues annually. The Syrians and their allies retaliated by
blockading the 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of Beirut.
   A spokesman for Aoun's command, speaking on condition of
anonymity, accused the Syrians of starting the latest barrage by
shelling the coastline north of Beirut to prevent three
vegetable-laden ships from docking at Christian ports.
   The Syrians have been shelling the Christian-controlled coast
north of Beirut almost daily for more than a month to prevent Aoun
from receiving war material from Iraq.
   Iraq, Syria's main Arab rival, has declared support to Aoun's
``war of liberation'' against the 40,000 Syrian troops deployed in
predominantly Moslem Lebanese provinces under a 1976 peacekeeping
mandate from the Arab League.
   Aoun and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of failing to
achieve their mandate by siding with Moslems against Christians in
Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
