<FIRST>r a PM-TaxResisters     07-20 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Resisters,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Bid Food, Blood, Toilet Seats For Home of Tax Resisters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government acquired the home of a
pair of tax resisters after the only bidders at an auction were
protesters whose offers ranged from toilet seats to food for the
poor.
   More than 300 people, many carrying banners and placards
denouncing military spending, gathered outside the Internal Revenue
Service office here Wednesday for the auction of the home of Randall
Kehler and his wife, Betsy Corner.
   The couple have not paid federal taxes in 12 years to protest the
federal government's military spending. Kehler is a founder of the
Nuclear Freeze campaign and its first national chairman.
   One group of protesters offered $21,414 worth of food and donated
services to the poor. Their canned goods were heaped on a truck next
to the IRS office.
   Bill Deters of Montague Center offered 10 toilet seats, which he
asserted would meet the $5,100 minimum bid if priced according to
U.S. Defense Department procurement standards. Other bids included a
guided tour of Nicaragua for Secretary of State James Baker.
   All 90 offers were rejected because they did not constitute legal
tender, said Robert Ruttenberg, an IRS spokesman. The government
acquired the home in the northwest Massachusetts town of Colrain for
the minimum bid of $5,100.
   The couple has six months to get their home back by paying
$27,000 in taxes, Ruttenberg said.
   But Kehler said they would not pay. He also promised that he, his
wife and their 9-year-old daughter would not comply with an eviction
order.
   Kehler said he and his wife have filed returns and donated the
money owed to local charities and peace groups. They have continued
to pay state and local taxes, he said.
   Ruttenberg said the number of tax resisters protesting military
spending has dropped to about 5,000 from about 22,000 in the early
1980s.
</TEXT>
