<FIRST>u i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru a0429 07-20 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0429,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Opposition Leader Arrested In Burma</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with arrest of opposition leader. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities put Burma's top opposition
leader, Aung San Suu Kyi, under house arrest today after a day of
unrest in that country's capital, according to a Western embassy
report.
   The arrest came after police beat protesters Wednesday during a
holiday marking national independence. State radio said 44 other
people were reported arrested during the protests.
   Troops of the military government of Gen. Saw Maung surrounded
Ms. Suu Kyi's house in a suburb of the capital, Rangoon, and kept
her there, said a source who spoke on condition of anonymity. He got
his information from a report of a Western embassy in Rangoon that
he would not identify further.
   ``She tried to surrender herself to the military, but they
refused and they forced her back inside,'' said the source.
   He said a diplomat and Tin Oo, co-leader of Ms. Suu Kyi's
National League for Democracy, went to see her, but they were turned
away.
   Other details were not immediately available. Operators said
telephone and telex lines to Rangoon from Bangkok were out of order
today.
   The source said the reason for the arrest of Ms. Suu Kyi, the
daughter of a celebrated independence leader, was unclear.
   He said the government may have used the violence during
Wednesday's Martyrs Day ceremonies as a pretext to move against her.
   He said her arrest may also be linked to those of three members
of her party. Authorities accused the three of bombing a government
oil refinery earlier this month in an attack that killed three
people.
   Ms. Suu Kyi is the most vocal critic of the authoritarian
government that has ruled under martial law since army commander Saw
Maung seized power in a coup in September and killed hundreds of
people to crush a nationwide campaign for democracy.
   Saw Maung has pledged to hold a general election by early next
year, and Western diplomats in Rangoon say authorities have been
increasingly concerned by Ms. Suu Kyi's growing popularity.
   ``Aung San Suu Kyi has been looking for a confrontation. Now it's
happened,'' the source in Bangkok said.
   Ms. Suu Kyi, 44, had vowed to lead thousands of people on a march
Wednesday to mark the day her father, Aung San, and other Burmese
independence leaders were assassinated in 1947. She canceled the
rally, however, to avoid bloodshed as troops flooded the streets of
the capital and erected barricades.
   The soldiers ``blocked off all the roads and prepared literally a
killing field for the people,'' said Ms. Suu Kyi in a telephone
interview from Bangkok Wednesday before her reported arrest.
   Witnesses said troops scattered hundreds of student demonstrators
who defied martial law. State-run radio reported 44 arrests.
   Ms. Suu Kyi said soldiers used sticks to beat some of the 3,000
student protesters in the capital's Swegondine district.
   A Western diplomat, also reached by telephone, said he saw
soldiers chase a group of students down a side street, drag some of
them out and hit them with sticks before putting 15 to 20 of them
into a truck.
   State radio said Wednesday night more than 1,400 people gathered
at seven areas of the city despite martial law. It said they
chanted, carried anti-government banners and distributed protest
literature while marching.
   A text of that broadcast was seen in Bangkok today.
   A heavily-guarded ceremony sponsored by the government was held
at the Martyrs Mausoleum without incident Wednesday morning, though
most opposition parties boycotted it.
   Also Wednesday, Briton David Storey, chief correspondent in
Bangkok for the Reuters news agency, said authorities expelled him
from the country.
</TEXT>
