<HEAD>Storm Batters China, Kills 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 8th, ``The typhoon...'' to UPDATE casualty figures
from Philippines. Pickup 9th, ``Gordon's raging...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Gordon left at least 17 people dead and
more than 100 injured when it slammed into southern China, cutting
communication lines and washing away roads and crops, the official
China Daily reported today.
   The paper said 13 people were missing and that damages totaled
about $27 million. The storm hit on Wednesday.
   Eight of the dead and 80 of the injured were in Yangjiang, one of
the hardest hit areas in coastal Guangdong province, the paper said.
   About 250 fishing boats capsized, 22 bridges collapsed and 156
miles of highway were washed away, the report said.
   Eight other people died in Zhaoqing in central Guangdong, and one
person was killed in the Zhuhai Special Economic Zone, near Macao,
where most of the coastal dikes were destroyed and 4,200 acres of
sugar cane fields, rice paddies and fish ponds were flooded, the
paper said.
   Thousands of people in the provincial capital of Canton were
stranded and telecommunications were knocked out, it said.
   The nationally televised evening news on Wednesday showed footage
of waves crashing over sea walls, flooded streets and buildings with
only rooftops visible.
   The typhoon first hit the Philippines early Sunday with winds of
up to 116 mph, killing 32 people, injuring 43 and leaving almost
186,000 people homeless on the islands. It caused at least $30
million in damage, according to the Office of Civil Defense.
   Gordon's raging winds hit Hong Kong on Tuesday, killing one
person before moving on to Guangdong province.
   It was downgraded to a tropical storm Wednesday morning, the
State Meteorological Bureau said.
</TEXT>
