<FIRST>r w PM-Teachers-Gangs     07-20 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teachers-Gangs,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teacher Union Leaders Express Concern About Growing Teen Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly three-quarters of teacher union leaders
say they are increasingly concerned about teen-age violence and
gang-related activities, the American Federation of Teachers
reported today.
   More than 80 percent of those surveyed by the AFT said easy
access to drugs was among the factors ``very responsible'' for the
problem. Some 65 percent cited easy access to guns.
   Drug trafficking, lack of parental supervision and lack of
employment opportunities were also identified as major factors.
   The top five solutions favored by the teachers were improved
support systems for families, improved community organizations, more
money for education and recreation facilities for teen-agers, more
stringent gun control laws and mandatory school-site security
personnel.
   Fewer than half of those surveyed favored installing metal
detectors in schools, with many citing the enormous cost of such a
move.
   Sandra Feldman, president of the AFT affiliate in New York City,
said school violence is still the exception rather than the rule.
But she said 82 percent of survey respondents said teen-age violence
is a bigger problem now than it used to be, and ``if that's not a
warning, I don't know what is.''
   The 710,000-member AFT represents education personnel in most of
the nation's urban areas. For its survey it questioned
representatives of its 50 largest locals, the 43 presidents of AFT
state units, and the union's 38-member executive council.
</TEXT>
