<FIRST>r a PM-CollegeDeseg 1stLd-Writethru a0529 07-20 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-College Deseg, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0529,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sweeping Reforms to Promote Desegregation at Louisiana Colleges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `Currently, one ...,' to CORRECT that all three
boards answer to the state Board of Regents, not Board of Trustees. Also
subs 7th graf, `The Southern ...,' to CORRECT that board meets July 29,
not today.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three federal judges have ordered Louisiana to
replace four governing boards with one in a package of sweeping
reforms to desegregate the state's 17 public colleges and
universities.
   ``The present scheme for governing education in Louisiana _ three
operating boards and one coordinating board _ has perpetuated
illegal segregation in Louisiana's higher education,'' the judges
said Wednesday.
   The ruling came in a lawsuit filed 15 years ago by the U.S.
Justice Department. It closely followed recommendations made in May
by Paul Verkuil, president of the College of William &amp; Mary, who was
appointed by the judges to conduct hearings and write a
desegregation plan.
   The five-year plan would create of a single board to govern
higher education, restrict admissions at some universities, limit
degree programs most can offer and establish a community college
system.
   Currently, one board governs the Louisiana State University
system, another governs the mostly black Southern University system
and a third governs the others. All three boards answer to the State
Board of Regents for Higher Education.
   The court gave the state 30 days to replace the four governing
boards with a new 17-member board. The governor will appoint the
members, pending Senate confirmation. The court declined to set a
ratio of white-to-black members.
   The Southern University board of supervisors will meet July 29 in
Baton Rouge to discuss an appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court, which
could delay the plan's implementation.
   The plan was recommended by Gov. Buddy Roemer when he took office
in 1988.
   ``The state has won. The people have won. I believe we have Buddy
Roemer and three judges to thank,'' said John Kennedy, Roemer's
lawyer in the case.
   The order would designate Louisiana State University in Baton
Rouge as the unified system's flagship university, with the greatest
number of graduate and research programs.
   It also calls for creation of an intermediate level of
institutions _ which includes Southern _ offering significant
doctoral and other graduate programs, and for gradually merging the
LSU law school and the Southern University law school, both in Baton
Rouge.
   The state's remaining four-year colleges would be designated
comprehensive universities with limited graduate or research
missions and less-selective or open admissions.
   The order was written by 5th U.S. Circuit Court Judge John M.
Wisdom, U.S. District Judge Charles Schwartz and District Judge
Veronica Wicker.
   Reaction to the order varied.
   ``I would think that the (merger of) Southern law school is a
real big problem for the board and for the black community. It's a
matter that needs to be modified,'' said state Sen. William
Jefferson, a black New Orleans lawyer who represents the Southern
University system.
   Kennedy said the plan has great potential to desegregate. ``I
think a single system and a selective admissions policy in some
schools to move students around will help desegregate.''
   John McKeithen, who left the LSU Board last year and was the
first governor to champion desegregation, was skeptical.
   ``I don't think it's going to work. For the life of me, I don't
know any way to make a white go to Grambling or a black go to
Louisiana Tech,'' McKeithen said, referring to two state colleges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
