<FIRST>r a PM-Khashoggi 1stLd-Writethru a0444 07-20 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khashoggi, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Financier Adnan Khashoggi Ordered Jailed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lede to fix spelling of extradited. Also subs 4th graf,
`The former ...,' to CORRECT description of suit.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi financier Adnan Khashoggi landed in a U.S.
jail after being extradited from Switzerland and pleading innocent
to charges of helping Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos plunder $100
million from the Philippines.
   U.S. District Judge Charles Keenan said at Wednesday's hearing
that he ``wouldn't dream of setting bail'' until Khashoggi's worth
is verified.
   Once among the world's richest men, Khashoggi was said to be the
middleman in the Iran-Contra deal.
   The former fugitive, handcuffed and wearing a green walking suit,
did not talk with reporters before leaving Kennedy International
Airport with FBI agents. But in a statement released by his lawyer,
Khashoggi said he intends to contest the charges and is confident
that ``my innocence will be clearly established.''
   Khashoggi's attorney, Robert Morvillo, had asked that bail be set
no higher than the $5 million bond granted Mrs. Marcos.
   Khashoggi's assets have dwindled recently as various holdings
have been sold. ``I read in the newspapers, like everyone else, that
he's a very rich man, but I don't know that,'' the judge said.
   ``I think your honor can assume that he's an enormously wealthy
man,'' Morvillo said.
   Instead of jail, Morvillo suggested that Khashoggi be put under
house arrest at his luxury apartment on Fifth Avenue. He said
Khashoggi could pay for private security guards deputized by the
court to watch him.
   Keenan laughed at the idea but said he would keep in mind
Morvillo's arguments in favor of bail.
   U.S. Assistant Attorney Charles LaBella opposed bail and house
arrest, saying he had learned that creditors were about to foreclose
on the apartment.
   In October, a federal grand jury in New York indicted Khashoggi,
the Marcoses, five other people and the California Overseas Bank in
Los Angeles.
   The Marcoses were charged with stealing millions from the
Philippines to buy real estate and art in New York. Khashoggi
allegedly posed as the owner of some of the assets as a cover.
   Khashoggi, 53, had been jailed in Switzerland since his April 18
arrest at a luxury hotel in Bern. But Swiss officials denied
extradition for racketeering and conspiracy charges because they're
not recognized under Swiss law. He was arraigned Wednesday on mail
fraud and obstruction of justice.
   He faces up to five years in jail and a $250,000 fine.
   Khashoggi, who once traveled the globe in his private yacht and
plane, spent the last three months in a 30-square-foot prison cell
fighting extradition.
   He is said to have been a major financier and middleman of the
Iran-Contra affair, in which proceeds of secret U.S. arms sales to
Iran were channeled to rebels fighting Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government. He has acknowledged a role in the deal and
said he lost $10 million on it.
   Khashoggi also has been named in several kickback scandals, and
has had financial problems that led one of his companies to file for
protection under bankruptcy law. His arrest in Switzerland marked
the first time that he was ever jailed.
   A U.S. diplomatic note asking that Khashoggi be arrested cited
four buildings in Manhattan and a collection of paintings that
disappeared from a Manila museum, Swiss authorities said.
   Khashoggi's lawyers two weeks ago announced they planned to
appeal the extradition. But the Swiss Justice Ministry statement
said Khashoggi changed his mind at a recent hearing. His lawyers
gave no explanation for the change of heart.
</TEXT>
