<HEAD>Jamiat Rebel Group Blames Rival Faction for Massacre</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to ADD Hekmatyar denial and CORRECT spelling
of Gulbaddin. Pickup 4th graf, `Hekmatyar heads...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for Afghanistan's
Jamiat-e-Islami guerrilla faction alleged today that the leader of a
rival faction ordered the massacre last week of 30 Jamiat rebels.
   Mohammad Shaoib said Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, leader of the
Hezb-e-Islami rebel group, should be tried under Islamic law for his
alleged role in the slayings in northern Afghanistan.
   Hekmatyar denied the allegation and said in a statement
distributed by the rebel-controlled Afghan News Agency, ``We not
only discourage but hate such a strife or feud among the mujahedeen,
and I strongly condemn those persons who committed this heinous
offence against their own Afghan brethren.''
   Hekmatyar heads one of two Hezb-e-Islami rebel groups
headquartered in the Pakistani border city of Peshawar. His
hard-line fundamentalist group is at odds with Shaoib's faction,
which also is based in Pakistan.
   Shaoib said the 30 guerrillas, seven of whom were key Jamiat
commanders, were returning July 9 from a military strategy meeting
with Jamiat's key commander, Ahmad Shah Masoud, in the northern
province of Takhar.
   They were ambushed by Hezb-e-Islami commander Said Jamal, and
five were killed immediately and 25 were later executed, Shaoib
alleged.
   Sixteen ``mutilated'' bodies were returned to Jamiat forces in
northern Afghanistan, said Shaoib.
   ``All those who were involved should be tried...Hekmatyar gave
the order so he is involved,'' Shaoib said in a news release.
   Guerrilla sources said the killings are part of a bloody power
struggle that has been going on between the two guerrilla groups in
northern Afghanistan since the civil war began 11 years ago.
   The Moslem insurgents are fighting to oust the Soviet-backed
government in Kabul and set up an Islamic republic. Until February,
Soviet troops were helping the Afghan government troops. They
withdrew under a U.N.-mediated accord.
   Scores of rebels have been killed in clashes between the
guerrilla groups, according to rebel sources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
