<FIRST>u w PM-Gingrich 1stLd-Writethru a0478 07-20 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0478,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Puts Off Decision to Investigate House GOP Whip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with comments on Gingrich, Savage; picks up
at pvs 4th graf, ``The committee''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House ethics committee said
today the panel was not ready to decide whether to launch an
investigation of Republican Whip Newt Gingrich.
   Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said the committee was taking no
action ``on anything on the calendar today,'' but added ``there was
a strong likelihood'' the panel could meet next week.
   The panel's first step in an investigation of Gingrich, R-Ga.,
who engineered a controversial book deal, would be to order a
preliminary inquiry.
   The committee's ranking Republican, Rep. John T. Myers of
Indiana, said before the panel's closed-door meeting, ``I don't
think there will be a decision on any of the issues before the
August recess,'' which begins in about two weeks.
   Dixon, who said the committee has three or four items on its
agenda, also said he has received a letter from the State Department
concerning Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill.
   On Wednesday, three House members asked the committee to
investigate an accusation that Savage sexually assaulted a Peace
Corps volunteer while on an official trip to Zaire. Dixon said the
State Department letter was ``an assertion of what they believe to
be the facts.''
   Gingrich filed the complaint that led to the investigation of
former House Speaker Jim Wright, who resigned in June after the
committee charged him with 69 rules violations.
   The committee was also considering whether to hire an outside
lawyer for the Gingrich probe as it did in the former speaker's case.
   Chicago attorney Richard J. Phelan, who handled the Wright case,
said this week he has discussed with the panel the possibility of
performing a similar role if an investigation of Gingrich is
approved.
   A complaint by Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark. filed last April
alleged that Gingrich, the second-ranking House Republican, may have
violated campaign finance laws and House rules on outside income and
receipt of gifts.
   The complaint focused on a partnership in which 21 investors put
up $5,000 each to promote ``Window of Opportunity'' _ a book
authored by Gingrich, his wife and a third writer.
   The ethics committee also received in June a request from House
Republicans for an investigation of Rep. Donald ``Buz'' Lukens,
R-Ohio. He is appealing his conviction on a charge of contributing
to the unruliness and delinquency of a minor.
   After a Franklin County, Ohio, jury found Lukens had sex with a
16-year-old girl in his Columbus apartment, he was sentenced June 30
to 180 days in jail and a $1,000 fine for the misdemeanor
conviction. He is free on bond and continues to perform his
congressional duties.
   
   The committee _ officially the Committee on Standards of Official
Conduct _ this week has a new member in Rep. Fred Grandy, R-Iowa,
replacing Rep. Hank Brown, R-Colo., who resigned from the panel.
   ``Newt Gingrich is one of my friends,'' Grandy told reporters.
``The fact that he's a Republican leader adds a little bit of
political heat to it. He gets no more or no less justice than any
other member of Congress.''
</TEXT>
