<FIRST>r a PM-DeltaCrash     07-20 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Delta Crash,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta Says Pilots at Fault in Texas Crash That Killed 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines took responsibility for the crash
of a Boeing 727, saying crew error led to the tragedy that killed 14
people at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport last summer.
   ``The flight crew failed to set the aircraft's flaps and slats in
the proper takeoff configuration as required by established Delta
practices and procedures,'' the airline said in a statement from its
Atlanta headquarters Wednesday.
   Flight 1141, carrying 108 people, rolled from side to side and
got no more than 30 feet off the runway before crashing Aug. 31 on
takeoff in a grassy field near the runway.
   The airline said Wednesday that the members of the flight crew
``are no longer flying with Delta.''
   The crew members were fired Tuesday after being called to the
Delta chief pilot's office in Dallas, said Capt. Jim Gray, spokesman
for the Air Line Pilots Association.
   Larry Davis, the pilot, and Steven Judd, the flight engineer, had
no comment Wednesday on Delta's announcement, said women answering
telephones at their Dallas-area homes. No phone listing was found
for co-pilot Carey Wilson Kirkland Jr.
   Delta spokesman Jim Lundy said the airline's investigation was
conducted separately from a National Transportation Safety Board
probe of the crash. He said Delta expects the NTSB to release its
conclusions in late summer or early fall.
   In NTSB hearings in November, the three crew members admitted
certain technical violations of Delta regulations had occurred as
they prepared for takeoff, but said they made all necessary
pre-flight preparations.
   Attorneys for crash victims said they were glad Delta accepted
blame for the crash but added that doesn't mean their clients' legal
action is finished.
   ``It will certainly expedite the cases,'' said Windle Turley, a
Dallas lawyer representing at least eight passengers who were aboard
Delta Flight 1141. ``If a case was going to take 18 months maybe now
it will be done in a year.''
</TEXT>
