<FIRST>r a PM-CannibalismDig     07-20 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cannibalism Dig,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archaeologists Unearth Remains of At Least Four Bodies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archaeologists trying to piece together a
story of cannibalism by a gold prospecting party in 1874 have found
the remains of four bodies in a mass grave.
   ``The working hypothesis today _ tomorrow I may change my mind _
is that we have a minimum of four individuals represented,'' Walter
Birkby, physical anthropology curator at Arizona State Museum in
Tucson, said at the excavation site.
   He is one of a team examining the expedition, whose organizer and
sole survivor, Alferd Packer, admitted eating his five colleagues
but said he killed only one of them, and in self-defense.
   Analysis of the bones for evidence of cannibalism will take some
time in a laboratory after the excavation is completed.
   Found with the bones were quantities of burlap and a green
suspender clip holding remnants of brown cloth, two hard rubber
buttons and two badly corroded metal buttons, the scientists said.
   Birkby said scientists decided that four bodies were represented
based on duplicate bones discovered and the arrangement of some
bones that were uncovered, such as arm bones arranged adjacent to a
shoulder bone.
   ``The cloth is most remarkable,'' archaeologist Jim Ayres said.
``It could help us put a date on things.''
   Birkby said Wednesday's findings suggest the bodies of the men
were wrapped in burlap and buried in a mass grave.
   Packer, who formed a gold-hunting party of five other men, said
the group became stranded on a snow-packed mountain ridge two miles
south of Lake City. He claimed Shannon Bell, a member of the party,
killed the other four gold-seekers, and that he was forced to kill
Bell in self-defense. Packer also admitted to consuming the remains
of the five men in order to survive.
   He was convicted of manslaughter and sentenced to serve 40 years
in prison.
   George Washington University law professor James Starrs organized
the archaeologists' search for the truth about what occurred.
</TEXT>
