<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan     07-20 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Dead in Ethnic-Related Shooting In Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HYDERABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorcyclists firing guns roared
through this southern city and killed six people in an attack
spurred by ethnic tensions, police said today.
   The violence occurred Wednesday night, and the city was under
curfew today. Residents were told they would be shot if caught
violating the curfew.
   Troops in jeeps with mounted machine guns were patrolling the
streets warning people to remain inside, witnesses said.
   The shooting occurred in an area of the city dominated by
immigrants who arrived from India after Pakistan and India were
partitioned in 1947, police said. They said 20 people were injured.
   The immigrants, who call themselves Mohajirs, want to be
recognized as a fifth ethnic group in Pakistan.
   Hyderbad is 95 miles north of the port city of Karachi, which
also has been hit with ethnic violence.
   Most of the clashes have involved Mohajirs; Pathans, the ethnic
majority in Pakistan's Northwest Frontier province; and Sind
Nationalists, who want greater autonomy for the southern Sind
province.
   Most of the clashes have occurred in Karachi and Hyderabad, the
two largest cities in Sind.
