<HEAD>Thousands Of Students Clash With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of high school students who
support a teachers' union that has been banned by the government
clashed with riot police in the southern city of Kwangju today, news
reports said.
   Police fired tear gas to break up the protests by 5,000 students
who tried to march from a university campus to nearby streets,
shouting slogans for a teachers' union, the Yonhap News Agency said.
   About 600 students were briefly detained by police, it said.
   Yonhap reported there were some injuries, but police had no
figures. The news agency said some students threw rocks at police.
``We love teachers! Don't punish them!'' students shouted, according
to Yonhap.
   Thousands of activist teachers are pushing to organize a labor
union in defiance of a government ban. The govenrment is threatening
to punish all teachers affiliated with the union.
   Union leaders claimed a membership of 30,000, but the Education
Ministry said only 5,000 of the nation's 300,000 middle and high
school teachers are affiliated with it.
   Also today, 2,000 street vendors, hurling rocks and wielding
sticks, fought police for several hours in Seoul, protesting a
government ban on their business in downtown areas.
   Seoul city authorities have recently removed all street vendors
as part of their effort to clean up the streets.
   Witnesses said several people were injured in the protests, which
lasted for several hours.
