<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill-Records     07-20 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill-Records,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Employee Sues Exxon, Charges Slander, Wrongful Firing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Exxon computer operator who
destroyed records on the Exxon Valdez oil spill has sued the
company, accusing it of wrongfully firing and slandering him.
   The lawsuit was filed Wednesday in state district court in
Houston on behalf of Kenneth A. Davis, his attorney David Berg said
in a telephone interview. The amount of damages sought by
Houston-based Exxon Co. USA was not specified.
   Berg said Davis will give Alaska officials a sworn statement
explaining how the computerized records were erased only if a judge
is present to protect his client from harassment by Exxon lawyers.
   Davis, 33, has acknowledged that on June 5-7, he and three other
employees recorded over computer files containing information on the
March 24 grounding of the Exxon Valdez.
   The lawsuit charges that Exxon fired Davis to make him a
scapegoat for the company's violation of court orders to perserve
documents on the tanker's spill of nearly 11 million gallons of
crude oil.
   The lawsuit says the destroyed records were the only complete
file Exxon had on the spill, and that there is no way to verify
whether the oil company has other copies.
   Exxon attorneys, in a memorandum filed Wednesday in Anchorage
Superior Court, say the erased files were backup copies that it was
not required to preserve.
   Davis says in the lawsuit that he erased the first tapes April 24
on the orders of supervisor Randall Parrott, even after Davis
indicated to Parrott that the tapes contained records from the day
of the spill.
   Davis was fired June 9 for insubordination. He says in the
lawsuit that he had received dozens of memos praising his work.
   Exxon's memorandum describes Davis as a disgruntled worker who,
after his firing, took unfounded allegations to a reporter.
   Exxon attorney Douglas Serdahely in Anchorage said late Wednesday
that he had not seen the lawsuit and could not comment on it.
   The crippled tanker has been moved to within seven to 10 miles of
San Clemente Island, about 60 miles southwest of San Diego, where it
is scheduled to undergo $25 million in repairs. Lawyers for Exxon
Shipping Co. and state agencies were negotiating over conditions for
allowing the leaky ship into California waters.
</TEXT>
