<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia     07-20 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Namibian Prisoners Released to Jubilant Crowd</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today freed 24 men described
as Namibia's last political prisoners, and hundreds of cheering
supporters escorted them back to their hometown in this South
African-ruled territory.
   Their group, the South-West African People's Organization or
SWAPO, said it had unearthed 27 bodies in a mass grave. SWAPO fought
the South Africans in a 23-year bush war, and it is now favored in
elections expected in November.
   Territorial authorities acknowledged burying 11 guerrillas but
dismissed the report of 27 bodies.
   The released prisoners were placed in a bus that took them back
to the Katatura black township on the edge of Windhoek. The bus was
surrounded by a crowd of up to 300 cheering, jogging supporters as
it crawled the two miles from Windhoek Central Prison to the
township.
   Territorial administrator Louis Pienaar announced Wednesday he
would free the 24 men whom he called the last political prisoners in
Namibia, also known as South-West Africa. However, he said eight
others held in connection with political violence would remain in
prison.
   Pienaar previously linked the release of political prisoners to
freedom for people he say SWAPO holds in Angolan, Zambian and
Tanzanian camps. Pienaar said he changed his mind when U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar assured him the United
Nations would seek the return to Namibia of all SWAPO detainees.
   Perez de Cuellar is in the territory for talks on a
U.N.-monitored independence process that South Africa approved in
December. The transition began in April.
   SWAPO has said it released all of its 201 detainees. But
relatives and the freed detainees themselves said nearly 2,000 more
detainees are in SWAPO camps.
   When the 24 prisoners held by authorities returned home today,
SWAPO's information secretary, Hidipo Hamutenya, announced on a
loudspeaker that on Saturday the group had dug up 27 bodies from a
mass grave where they were dumped last week by territorial police in
Ovamboland in northern Namibia.
   Hamutenya said U.N. forces were present during the unearthing. He
gave no further details.
   Senior U.N. officials could not be reached because they flew to
the north early today with Perez de Cuellar to inspect security
there.
   Gerhard Roux, a spokesman for Pienaar, questioned whether U.N.
officials were present at such an unearthing. He said they did not
mention it when de Cuellar met with Pienaar on Wednesday.
   Inspector Kerrie du Rand of the South-West African Police said
police had buried in the bush 11 bodies of SWAPO guerrillas on
Friday. He said the guerrillas were killed during battles in April
that nearly derailed the independence process.
   Du Rand said the bodies had been kept in a refrigerator at the
Oshakati morgue but had been unclaimed. He called the figure of 27
bodies ``blatant propaganda.''
</TEXT>
