<FIRST>u i PM-France-China     07-20 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-China,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exiles Report Arrest of Top Chinese Student Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese student Wang Dan, who headed a list of
dissidents wanted by Chinese authorities, has been arrested after
more than a month in hiding, prominent Chinese exiles said today.
   Wu'er Kaixi, who with Wang was among the best-known leaders of
the democracy movement suppressed last month, told a news conference
he had received confirmation of his colleague's arrest earlier in
the day.
   ``Wang Dan is one of the greatest fighters for freedom in China
today,'' Wang told a news conference, his voice cracking with
emotion.
   ``Recently the authorities have tried to dirty Wang Dan's image
by calling him a traitor. The contribution of Wang Dan, this
20-year-old student, will live on in the history of China.''
   In Beijing today, Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Li Jinhua refused
to comment on persistent reports there that Wang is under arrest.
   Wu'er and four other Chinese dissidents issued an appeal to
governments, the United Nations, human rights groups and individuals
around the world to pressure the Chinese government ``to put an end
to secret arrests, to torture, to secret executions.''
   The five also proposed that a representative assembly be called
to create a Chinese Democratic Front to unite Chinese ``without
distinction of parties, tendencies, groups, beliefs, professions or
regions to unite under the banner of liberty, democracy, legalism
and human rights.''
   Wu'ur was joined by businessman Wan Runnan, political scientist
Yan Jiaqi, journalist Liu Binyan and economist Su Shaozhi, the
former director of the Institute for Marxist-Leninist studies in
Beijing.
   Liu said he does not believe the current government in China can
last more than two years.
   ``I'm not saying that what will follow Li Peng will be a
democratic government, but it will be replaced by a more moderate
faction,'' he said. ``We cannot predict when a Gorbachev might
emerge in China, but it's a possibility,'' he said, referring to
Soviet President Mikhai S. Gorbachev.
   Wu'er said there was no organization in place to help wanted
leaders get out of China.
   ``Before June 4, we never would have imagined that the government
would be so cruel and barbarous, so we never had such an
organization,'' he said.
   He said he and others who escaped ``have the responsibility to
continue the work of all those who have been arrested and executed
and lost their lives.''
   Since the June 3-4 crackdown on pro-democracy protesters, at
least 12 people who participated in the protests have been executed.
   China's official Xinhua news agency has said nearly 100 soldiers
and police died and that thousands were injured, while about 100
civilians died and nearly 1,000 were injured in the crackdown.
Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources said the death
toll may have been as high as 3,000.
</TEXT>
