<SECOND>PM-Cyprus, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0568,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Cypriot Women Declare Victory in Protest Against Turks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with protesters declaring victory
and announcing end of protest. Pickup 2nd graf pvs, `Rauf Denktash...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek Cypriot women said today they will
end a demonstration that led to a clash with Turkish authorities
because they achieved their goal of protesting Turkish control of
northern Cyprus.
   The protest further inflamed sectarian passions between Moslems
Turks and Christian Greeks and threatened to wreck 11 months of
U.N.-sponsored talks on reuniting this Mediterranean island.
   ``We have achieved our purpose of emphasizing the Greek Cypriots'
right to return'' to their homes in the Turkish-held north, said
Athena Violari, one of the organizers. Organizers said their protest
would end later today.
   Many people now in the Greek-controlled sector fled the north
when Turkey invaded in 1974.
   Despite stifling summer heat, thousands of Greek Cypriot women
poured into narrow alleys of Nicosia's old quarter today, responding
to radio appeals to support about 1,000 woman protestors who clashed
with police Wednesday.
   Rauf Denktash, leader of the island's Turkish sector, threatened
to cut off talks on reunification because of the Greek Cyriot
protest. He was speaking to a rally while the 120,000 Turkish
Cypriots celebrated the 15th anniversary of the Turkish invasion
that led to their breakaway state.
   Akis Fantis, a spokesman for the Greek Cypriot government,
appealed for calm and warned of ``painful consequences'' if the
situation deteriorates.
   About 1,000 Greek Cypriot women and some male supporters pushed
across Nicosia's U.N.-policed buffer zone Wednesday night and
clashed at its edge with Turkish Cypriot forces.
   The women penetrated the boundary, called the Green Line, at dusk
after scuffling with the Canadian soldiers who patrol it and
knocking down barbed wire barricades at the Ayios Kassianos
neighborhood. They occupied a war-damaged elementary school and a
church.
   A few minutes later, Turkish riot police supported by dozens of
soldiers armed with rifles charged into the buffer zone.
   Four people were injured, Turkish authorities said.
   Organizers of the Greek Cypriot protest today demanded that
Turkish authorities free 100 women and 11 men, including Greek
Orthodox Bishop Chrysostomos of Kitium, who were arrested when
Turkish authorities moved in.
   Those arrested included Steve Weizman, a British reporter for
Reuters news agency; Katherine McElroy, another Reuters reporter who
holds dual Cypriot and American nationality; and Dutch radio
reporter Hetty Lubberding.
   Turkish Cypriot Radio Bayrak said the arrested protesters were
taken to courts in the Turkish sector of Nicosia today, but it gave
no other details.
   The thousands of women who joined the protest today, responding
to radio appeals for support, filled the narrow streets near the
buffer zone.
   Many of the women, some wearing factory workclothes, left their
jobs to join the protest. They were joined by scores of black-robed
Greek Orthodox priests singing Byzantine hymns.
</TEXT>
