<FIRST>r a PM-FlashFlood     07-20 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flash Flood,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flash Flood Sweeps Cars from Bridge, Killing One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARRENTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Floodwaters washed at least 10 vehicles off
a bridge into a creek that rose about 13 feet in 30 minutes early
this morning, killing at least one person, authorities said.
   The high water hampered divers who were searching downstream this
morning for another car that may have contained as many as three
people, said Fauquier County Sheriff's Lt. David Flohr.
   ``It's the age-old story: people forget about the tremendous
force of running water,'' said Chuck Thompson, director of county
emergency services.
   Thompson said the cars were swept off the bridge on U.S. 17
between Delaplane and U.S. 50 in northern Virginia just after
midnight. The bridge, normally 10 feet above Goose Creek, was under
2 to 3 feet of water at the height of the flooding, officers said.
   Two motorists were rescued by boat off the tops of their cars
while others made their way to shore. After the water receded,
rescuers found the body of a woman whose car had not been seen
leaving the bridge, Thompson said. She was identified as Tammy Woolf
Conneway of Bloommerry, W.Va., said sheriff's Maj. Warren Jenkins.
   ``We had no warning whatsoever. There was nothing from the
National Weather Service. It caught everyone by surprise,'' Thompson
said.
   John Billet, a weather service forecaster in Washington, said the
thunderstorm was a local one ``that popped up in the front range of
the mountain.'' The heaviest rain reported was 2 inches at Front
Royal, about 15 miles away in the Blue Ridge mountains.
</TEXT>
