<HEAD>Scientists Brew Semiconductors From Yeast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have discovered that a simple kind of
yeast creates excellent specimens of a new kind of matter _
semiconducting crystals so small they behave somewhat like
individual atoms or molecules.
   The yeast organisms produce the tiny crystals when exposed to
cadmium, a highly toxic metal, in a process that apparently
detoxifies the metal.
   Semiconducting crystals are the basis of chips that are used for
all kinds of electronic devices. Studying the tiny yeast-generated
crystals should help researchers understand how small transistors
can be shrunk before they begin to take on the quantum properties of
atoms and molecules, losing their normal semiconducting properties.
   A paper on the findings was published in the April 13 issue of
the journal Nature by physicists at AT&amp;T Bell Laboratories in Murray
Hill, N.J., and biochemists at the University of Utah Medical School
in Salt Lake City.
   It was not until the Utah researchers contacted the Bell Labs
scientists that the two groups realized the yeast had created the
first biological specimens of the kind of particles the physicists
were probing.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 24</NOTE>
