<FIRST>r w PM-Savage-Sex 1stLd-Writethru a0446 07-20 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Savage-Sex, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Seek Probe of Congressman Accused of Assault</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf, `The State,' to UPDATE with
comment from ethics committee chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., faces a House ethics
committee investigation into allegations he sexually assaulted a
Peace Corps volunteer while on an official trip to Africa.
   ``Obviously we believe people should be innocent until proven
guilty,'' said Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., one of three
Democrats who formally requested an investigation by the House
ethics committee. The panel must inquire when such a request is made.
   But the ``behavior is fairly shocking if it proves to be true,''
Schroeder said. ``There's just no excuse ... We cannot let power go
to people's heads.''
   The Peace Corps worker claims Savage, while on an official trip,
fondled her for more than two hours in the back of a
chauffeur-driven embassy car in Kinshasa, the capital of Zaire, on
March 19, according to several government officials.
   Savage denied the charge.
   ``I did nothing, that's what I did,'' the black congressman told
television reporters outside the Capitol. ``This lie was leaked by
the State Department for political reasons.''
   ``They tried to destroy Dr. Martin Luther King with a lie ... I'm
in very good company,'' Savage said.
   In calling for an ethics investigation, Schroeder was joined by
Democratic Reps. Barney Frank of Massachusetts and Matthew McHugh of
New York.
   ``We write to ask the ethics committee to inquire into the
assertion that our colleague from Illinois, Mr. Savage, behaved
improperly towards a federal employee while on a congressional
tour,'' said the letter sent to ethics committee chairman Rep.
Julian C. Dixon, D-Calif.
   The letter noted that the lawmakers had no independent knowledge
of the incident, but added: ``We believe that the accusation is
sufficiently serious to justify your looking into it.''
   The State Department has sent a separate confidential letter to
the committee noting the allegations, said Jill Gross of the
agency's inspector general's office.
   Outside the committee room today, Dixon said the State Department
material was ``an assertion of what they believed to be the facts.''
   The committee met privately for 90 minutes today, and Dixon said
afterward he had no announcements to make on the Savage case or any
other issues facing the panel.
   The incident allegedly occurred while Savage was on a visit to
Zaire and had dinner one night at the residence of U.S. Ambassador
William Harrop.
   Those attending the dinner included the Peace Corps volunteer,
who was scheduled to brief the congressman a few days later on
agency activities there, said a Peace Corps official who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
   After dinner, Savage insisted the woman ride alone with him in an
embassy limousine while the congressman, members of his staff and
others visited area bars, the official said.
   ``He tried to force me to have sex with him ... He kept touching
me, after I told him to stop, many times, loudly,'' she was quoted
as saying in Wednesday's editions of the Washington Post.
   Savage offered reporters a different version.
   ``We were in a caravan of four or five cars,'' he said. ``We made
four or five brief stops and got out of the car and got back in. If
there were any kind of abuse, then why would she keep getting back
into the same car?''
   The woman left her post in Zaire for six weeks of counseling and
medical treatment at a Washington hospital and is awaiting another
Peace Corps assignment, the agency official said.
   But the 28-year-old worker, whose name has not been disclosed,
had declined to file a formal complaint against Savage, believing it
would hurt the Peace Corps, the official said.
   Savage, 63, has encountered criticism before for absenteeism in
Congress and globe-trotting appearances for questionable causes,
accused by government agencies of failing to disclose sources of
funds and investigated for personnel practices.
   But he remains popular in his Chicago district, winning
re-election last November with 83 percent of the vote.
   Savage was first elected to Congress in 1980, and the Chicago
Sun-Times said that during his first year he participated in only 51
percent of the recorded votes.
   The following January, Savage showed up at a demonstration in
Lisbon, Portugal, leading 50,000 demonstrators against American
policy who were described as mainly Communist trade unionists.
</TEXT>
