<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Airbus     07-20 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Airbus,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Daily Scorns U.S. Compensation Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. offer to pay $30 million to
families of those killed when an Iranian jetliner was shot down by
the USS Vincennes demonstrated Washington's low regard for Iranian
lives, a Tehran newspaper said Thursday.
   The Kayhan International newspaper said the U.S. compensation
offer was ``an attempt to counter an Iranian lawsuit against
Washington at the World Court.''
   The State Department said Monday it would pay up to $250,000 for
each full-time wage earner and up to $100,000 for others killed when
the Iran Air jetliner was shot down July 3 last year.
   The U.S. offer followed the filing of claims in a Washington
court on behalf of more than 200 heirs seeking a total of $145.5
million in compensation for their dead relatives.
   Kayhan said that the U.S. offer of $100,000 for non-wage earners
was not ``even a respectable illegal kickback in Washington these
days.''
   ``Each life at $100,000 equals the price tag for four Oliver
North speeches, three speeches by Nancy Reagan, and two by Ronald
Reagan. That is cheap,'' the Islamic Republic News Agency quoted the
newspaper as saying.
   There were 250 Iranians and 40 citizens of other countries aboard
the Iran Air jet when it was shot down by the Vincennes. All 290
were killed.
   A U.S. military inquiry determined that radar operators aboard
the Vincennes, which had earlier clashed with Iranian gunboats, had
mistaken the jetliner for an F-14 fighter on an attack course.
   Kayhan said Washington's compensation offer was far lower than
what American families were paid by Iraq for 37 crewmen killed in an
Iraqi air attack on the U.S. frigate Stark in May 1987. Iraq said
the pilot mistook the Stark for an Iranian warship.
   Iraq paid about $740,000 to each of the slain men's families.
   The Stark settlement totaled about $27 million for 37 crewmen
killed in the attack, while the U.S. offer amounted to $30 million
for 290 lives, IRNA quoted Kayhan as saying.
</TEXT>
