<HEAD>Tons of Dead Fish Choke River; Bulgarian Battery Plant Blamed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDROUPOLIS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tons of dead fish choked the Evros
River on Thursday, and government officials blamed a battery factory
in Bulgaria.
   The river emanates from Bulgaria and serves as a frontier for
Greece and Turkey.
   An official of the Greek Fisheries Department in Evros province
accused the Bulgarian battery factory of dumping chemical waste into
the river, killing the fish.
   The factory lies near the Greek-Bulgarian border and was the
focus of attention last summer, when the same problem occured.
   Tons of rotting fish on the river banks are creating a health
hazard and farmers have stopped drawing water for irrigation.
   Environmentalists fear the polluted waters could create problems
in the Evros River delta, a breeding ground for tens of thousands of
migratory birds.
