<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Zimbabwe-Strike     07-20 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Zimbabwe-Strike,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zimbabwe Rail Strike Ends; Workers to Get New Offer From Gov't</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Railroad repairmen returned to work
Thursday, ending an eight day strike that crippled transport
service, officials said.
   About 2,000 repairmen reported for work and most others were
expected to resume normal working schedules by late Thursday, a
state railroad spokesman said.
   More than 200 train drivers, brakemen, conductors and station
staff who stopped work in sympathy with the repairmen also returned
to their posts, the spokesman said.
   The striking repairmen demanded a 20 percent wage increase
retroactive to July 1987 after rejecting a 10.7 percent pay increase
from the government.
   On Wednesday, transport minister Simbarashe Mumbengegwi met with
strikers at the biggest National Railways workshops in the western
city of Bulawayo, and he said the government was working out a new
offer. He declined to elaborate.
   Junior repairmen earn about $250 a month, rising to $700 in
higher grades.
   Strikers said their action halted three-fourths of Zimbabwe's
rail traffic, including freight services to the Indian Ocean ports
of neighboring Mozambique and South Africa.
</TEXT>
