<FIRST>u a PM-PTLTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0630 07-20 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PTL Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0630,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>David Taggart: Bakker Gave Him Authority to Use Ministry Credit Cards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs overline to reflect David Taggart testimony. Subs lede
to insert N.C. in dateline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former aide to PTL founder Jim Bakker
testified in court today that the evangelist gave him the authority
to take large cash advances and use ministry credit cards.
   David Taggart and his brother, James, are charged with evading
$525,000 in federal income taxes while associated with PTL.
   Under questioning by defense lawyer Ben Cotten, David Taggart
said that as a vice president of the ministry, he had direct
authority from Bakker to take large cash advances, sign PTL checks,
use PTL credit cards and authorize bonuses for PTL employees.
   Taggart said he gained the authority when Bakker and his wife,
Tammy, lured him back to the ministry after a brief absence he
attributed to exhaustion.
   The cash advances, Taggart said, were used primarily for trips by
the Bakkers on ministry business. He claimed that money used for
personal expenses was reimbursed, but said, ``I always have been lax
about documentation. It's never been a priority.''
   Taggart's testimony came a day after Bakker invoked his Fifth
Amendment right against self-incrimination in refusing to answer
questions by defense and prosecuting attorneys. Bakker's 10-minute
appearance in the federal courtroom was without the presence of the
jury.
   ``When his trial comes about, there will be no taking of the
Fifth Amendment and no refusal to answer any questions that the
government cares to ask and to go into the entire matter in depth,''
said Bakker attorney George T. Davis.
   Bakker and former top PTL aide Richard Dortch are scheduled to go
on trial for conspiracy and wire and mail fraud on Aug. 28.
   After Bakker refused to answer questions, Judge Robert Potter
released the witness, saying, ``This court will not force him to
testify.''
   Cotten said he is barred from mentioning to the jury that Bakker
ever appeared in court.
   James Taggart took the stand Wednesday and described his
association with Bakker.
   Both Taggarts were fired when Jerry Falwell took over at the
television ministry following Bakker's resignation in March 1987
following revelations of the Jessica Hahn sex-and-money scandal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
