<FIRST>u a PM-UnplannedLanding     07-20 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unplanned Landing,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Plane Makes Unscheduled Landing at O'Hare</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines DC-10 made an unscheduled
landing today at O'Hare International Airport after a bird was
sucked into an engine and the pilot shut it down, said the FAA and
the airline.
   United Flight 23 from New York's JFK Airport to San Francisco set
down without incident at 9:58 a.m., said Mort Edelstein, a spokesman
for the Federal Aviation Administration.
   ``Passengers left the airplane normally on the jet bridge
(walkway) and are being re-accommodated on another airplane,'' said
United spokesman Russell Mack, adding that none of the 265
passengers or 10 crew members was injured.
   The unscheduled landing came a day after United Flight 232, a
DC-10 en route from Denver to Chicago, crashed at Sioux City, Iowa.
The plane was carrying 293 people. At least 74 people were killed;
at least 176 people survived.
   In today's incident, a bird was sucked into the No. 1 engine,
which is on a wing, shortly after takeoff at 8:30 a.m. EDT, Mack
said. He said he didn't know why the pilot flew to O'Hare before
landing.
   Emergency crews waited on the runway until the landing was
complete, said Chicago Fire Department spokesman Tom Sheppard.
   The plane had been scheduled to fly non-stop and to land at 11:33
a.m. PDT in San Francisco, Mack said.
   In a third incident this week, a United Boeing 747 flying from
Los Angeles to Sydney, Australia, made an emergency landing in Fiji,
according to the Sydney Morning Herald. There were no injuries.
   The report quoted an unidentified United spokeswoman in Sydney as
saying the Boeing 747 later flew back to the United States after the
crew rested.
   Mack said the Fiji landing occurred two days ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
