<FIRST>u a PM-WanderingPlane 2ndLd-Writethru a0586 07-20 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0586,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Attorney Reviewing Case of Lawyer-Pilot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. attorney probe, brother's
comments. Picks up 2nd graf `Various pilots....'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. attorney in Miami has received
FBI files on lawyer-pilot Thomas Root and is looking into
contradictions in his account of his 800-mile autopilot flight, a
spokeswoman confirmed today.
   A source close to the investigation told The Associated Press
that it would probably examine filing of false information about a
flight and liability for expenses of search and rescue after Root
ditched in Bahamian waters.
   Diane Cossins, executive assistant to U.S. Attorney Dexter
Lehtinen, confirmed that the office is looking into the case, adding
``we will not discuss any matters concerning an ongoing
investigation.''
   She said, however, that the FBI had turned over material at
Lehtinen's request, including details of interrogation of Root by
FBI agents at the hospital.
   Todd Root said today that his brother has no explanation for
reports by pilots who intercepted the flight a week ago that they
saw Root's head move when he said he was flying unconscious. He said
Thomas Root would stay in the hospital for another week for testing.
   ``We hope the medical tests will finally end this mystery and put
this all to rest,'' he said, noting that the battery of tests might
include psychological testing.
   ``Various pilots reported that as he was intercepted from the
right his head would turn to the right and as he was intercepted
from the left, his head would move to the left,'' Andrew Alston, a
National Transportation Safety Board investigator, said Wednesday.
   He said the plane's sun visor was moved at least three times
during the flight, too.
   Still, Alston, who interviewed the 36-year-old Washington
communications attorney again Wednesday at Hollywood's Memorial
Hospital, refused to second-guess the pilot.
   ``He was there. You weren't. I wasn't,'' Alston said.
   Alston wouldn't say whether Root could face charges for
misleading NTSB investigators.
   FBI spokesman Paul Miller said his agency also is continuing to
investigate the case, adding:
   ``We anticipate that once all our facts are developed, we will
again discuss the matter with the U.S. attorney's office in Miami.''
   Results of Root's blood test for carbon monoxide were negative,
ruling out that explanation for his claimed loss of consciousness,
authorities said Wednesday. Results of drug and alcohol tests are
expected later this week.
   The pilot says he was on a routine business flight, passed out,
and must have been shot when his handgun accidentally went off
before he regained consciousness in Bahamian waters.
   Root, who remained in stable condition with a gunshot wound in
his stomach, maintains the .32-caliber Smith &amp; Wesson revolver he
kept in the plane's glove compartment must have discharged during
the crash.
   But Smith &amp; Wesson officials said the gun's safety features make
such accidental misfirings impossible. And police and doctors said
medical evidence indicates Root must have been shot several hours
before his small plane went down.
   Root's plane lies beneath several thousand feet of water off the
Bahamian island of Eleuthera. Miller said a decision on whether the
plane should be raised for evidence would probably be made in
Washington.
   Also Wednesday, Root was sued in federal court in Washington by a
Georgia company that accused him of breach of contract and
unlawfully converting money to his own use.
   Root is accused by Sonrise Management Services Inc. of Columbus,
Ga., of failing to perform work he had agreed to do in representing
investors before the Federal Communications Commission. It also
accused him of double billing Sonrise, resulting in overpayments of
nearly $100,000.
   Since March 1986, Sonrise has paid Root $1.9 million as an
advance against legal fees and expenses and to reimburse him for FCC
filing and hearing fees, the suit said.
   On July 3, a separate suit in federal court in Macon, Ga.,
accused Root of legal malpractice, breach of contract and fraud in
handling a $75,000 transaction for Dr. Kenneth Bazemore of Byron, Ga.
   Bazemore's suit contends Root sent the money _ meant as an
initial payment for two broadcast companies _ to Ralph Savage,
chairman of Sonrise, without permission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
