<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CaribouDeaths     07-20 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caribou Deaths,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mysterious Disease Killing Maine Caribou</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORONO, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mysterious disease is taking a heavy toll
on a herd of caribou calves that were to be let loose in the Maine
wilds.
   Twelve of 17 calves born this spring within a herd living in pens
at the University of Maine in Orono have died, seven from a
diarrhea-like illness biologists are not able to identify.
   Of the other five that died, one was stillborn and the others
fell victim to infection, low birth weight and other problems of
unknown origin.
   In addition, two adult caribou in the Orono pens died of
brainworm parasite. Maine Caribou Project leader Mark McCollough
said biologists are taking precautions to protect the rest of the
herd from the parasite, which is passed to susceptible animals
through infected snails and slugs. The parasite infests much of
Maine's deer herd.
   Of the 14 caribou already released in northern Maine's Baxter
state wilderness park this spring, nine remain alive. One died after
being attacked by a coyote, another died of the brainworm parasite,
and three others died of stress and reaction to a drug.
   One doe that was released roamed across the border to Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
