<FIRST>r w AM-SilentMarch     07-20 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Silent March,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP Slates Silent Civil Rights March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NAACP called on civil rights leaders
Thursday to join a silent march to protest what they described as
``illogical, irrational and unexplainable'' Supreme Court decisions.
   ``We cannot stand by and let four men and one woman in black
robes halt our long-delayed march to freedom, any more than we
allowed people in white robes,'' to do so, said Benjamin L. Hooks,
executive director of the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People.
   Hooks called on ``thought leaders'' of the minority community in
the United States to gather in Washington on Aug. 26 for a silent
march to protest the recent court decisions.
   ``It is illogical, irrational and unexplainable,'' he said.
   In particular, Hooks cited recent decisions overturning a
Richmond, Va., plan that set aside some city contracts for minority
businesses, permitting a reverse discrimination lawsuit by white
firefighters in Birmingham, Ala. and weakening protection for people
seeking to prove racial discrimination in jobs and contracts.
   ``This present Supreme Court is more dangerous to the legitimate
hopes and aspirations of black people in this nation than ... any
George Wallace proclaiming `segregation forever' or any Ross Barnett
standing in the schoolhouse door saying `they shall not pass,'''
Hooks told a news conference.
   Hooks, a former Memphis, Tenn., judge, said he still respects the
institution of the Supreme Court, but termed the recent rulings
``berserk'' and ``tragic.''
   Hooks explained that a decision to hold a silent march recalled
1917, when several thousand blacks marched silently in the streets
of New York to protect recent race riots in Waco, Memphis and St.
Louis. Participants in the upcoming march will be asked to dress the
same as they did then: men in black, women in white.
   The plan is not for a massive march and there is no desire to
disrupt city life on Aug. 26, said Hooks.
   ``We are not trying to mobilize large numbers, we are trying to
mobilize the leaders,'' said Hooks. ``Frankly, if we have 1,000 to
2,000 people I'll be happy, provided they represent the scope and
depth of the people.
   He said that organization of the effort is just beginning that
that while he is inviting ``all people of conscience'' to
participate, he has not yet contacted other groups about joining the
effort.
   Other organizations such as the Urban League, National Council of
Negro Women, Leadership Conference on Civil Rights and League of
United Latin American Citizens had no immediate reaction to Hooks
plan.
</TEXT>
