<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs     07-20 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>55,000 Drug Addicts To Be Sent To Labor Camps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 55,000 Iranian drug addicts will be
prosecuted and sent to labor camps next week upon expiration of a
six-month grace period for them to kick their habit, it was reported
Thursday.
   The move was the second stage of an anti-narcotics crackdown
launched in December to stamp out rampant drug addiction.
   Law enforcement agencies will round up the addicts who have
failed to overcome their addiction to send them to the labor camps
to kick the habit, the Islamic Republic News Agency said in a report
monitored in Cyprus.
   More than 80 percent of the addicts in Iran have been identified,
according to an official of the Islamic Revolutionary Committees,
which have taken over from police.
   Guards will be stationed in most cities and along major highways
starting July 23 for a 10-day period to identify and arrest addicts,
he noted.
   The anti-narcotics campaign has concentrated so far on arresting
drug pushers and traffickers. Almost 800 alleged drug smugglers,
including men, women and a few non-Iranians, have been hanged since
December.
