<HEAD>Investigators Look for Additional Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf, `Meanwhile, Alamance ...,' with 2 grafs with
sheriff refusing to confirm reports. Picks up 5th graf, `One possible ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN P. TEATER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of using arsenic to kill her
former husband and a boyfriend and trying to poison her current
husband is under investigation in other deaths, investigators said.
   Blanche Taylor Moore, 56, proclaimed her innocence through her
attorney Wednesday after making her first court appearance on the
charges.
   ``Mrs. Moore personally, while traumatized and upset over being
arrested and denied bond, is determined to rally and present her
side of all this,'' her attorney, Mitchell McEntire, said outside
court. ``She maintains her innocence.''
   Two sources close to the investigation, who asked that their
names not be used, told the Winston-Salem Journal that ``a good
friend'' of Mrs. Moore's _ a woman _ may have died of arsenic
poisoning.
   When asked about that information, Alamance County Sheriff
Richard L. Frye refused to confirm details of any cases, saying only
that investigators were being asked to review several deaths.
   ``People are calling us and giving us information,'' he said.
``The Burlington police have some (information) that they are
checking out. Anything that we come up with will be entirely up to
the chief medical examiner and the attorney as to where we go from
here.''
   One possible subject of the investigation is Mabel Parsons, a
grocery store co-worker of Mrs. Moore whose death was blamed on
cancer, WGHP-TV reported.
   A judge has ordered the exumation of the body of her father,
Parker D. Kiser Sr., to determine whether his 1966 death was caused
by arsenic poisoning.
   At the hearing Wednesday, Alamance County Superior Court Judge
Spencer Ennis scheduled a probable cause hearing for Aug. 1.
   Mrs. Moore is being held without bond on the murder charges.
   The charges:
   _First-degree murder in the 1973 death of her first husband,
James Taylor, filed by the Burlington Police Department.
   _First-degree murder in the 1986 death of Raymond Reid, a former
boyfriend, in a warrant issued by the Forsyth County Sheriff's
Department.
   _Assault with a deadly weapon with intent to kill in the arsenic
poisoning of her current husband, the Rev. Dwight Moore, who is
being treated at North Carolina Memorial Hospital in Chapel Hill,
filed by the Alamance County Sheriff's Department.
   Authorities from several jurisdictions who conducted a two-month
probe have refused to suggest a motive.
</TEXT>
