<DOCNO> AP890720-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     07-20 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Accuses U.S. Congress of Slander, Interference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China accused the U.S. Congress on Thursday of
slander and gross interference in the latest round of recriminations
prompted by Beijing's crackdown on pro-democracy protests.
   In Paris, prominent Chinese exiles appealed for more pressure
from governments and individuals on China's leaders to halt secret
arrests and executions of dissidents.
   China's Foreign Ministry accused U.S. lawmakers of ``pursuing
power politics,'' the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   ``The U.S. Congress has grossly interfered in China's internal
affairs time and again, seriously hurting the feelings of the
Chinese people,'' Xinhua quoted a ministry official as telling U.S.
Ambassador James Lilley.
   At issue were separate amendments approved by the Senate and
House of Representatives that provide sanctions against China.
President Bush already has halted military sales and high-level
contacts, but the amendments would also stop U.S. funds from
supporting trade with China and suspend satellite exports and
nuclear cooperation.
   The two houses have yet to reconcile the differences in their
bills.
   In a separate protest, a Chinese legislative committee said the
amendments ``willfully distorted the facts'' about the army's June
3-4 attack in Beijing on the student-led protesters for a freer
society.
   The Foreign Affairs Committee of the National People's Congress
accused U.S. legislators of having unspecified ``ulterior motives,''
and warned that efforts to pressure China, ``like lifting a rock
only to drop it on one's own feet ... will ultimately hurt the
interests of the United States itself.''
   China has strongly objected to all foreign criticism of the army
attack and subsequent arrests and executions. But the United States,
viewed by many of the protesters as a model of democracy, has been
most heavily attacked in a blitz of broadcast and newspaper
commentaries.
   China has protested the U.S. Embassy giving refuge to dissidents
Fang Lizhi and his wife, Li Shuxian, while the United States has
protested an attack by Chinese soldiers on foreign diplomats.
   U.S.-China relations have been strained before over trade, Taiwan
and China's policy in Tibet, but never since ties were restored in
1979 have emotions on both sides run so high.
   ``There are some people, a small group of people, who think the
United States is a bad influence and want to see (the influence)
limited,'' said a U.S. diplomat on condition of anonymity. But he
said he did not expect the quarrel to lead to a break in ties.
   Ms. Li, meanwhile, said Chinese soldiers were ``acting according
to their orders and ... Performing their normal tasks'' in searching
foreign diplomats' cars at checkpoints in Beijing and sometimes
sticking guns in their faces.
   Military checkpoints go up around Beijing after midnight, and
several diplomats have reported soldiers searched their cars in
apparent violation of diplomatic immunity.
   She also defended the government's seizure of foreign newspapers
and magazines at stores and hotels in Beijing last week.
   ``We do not refuse all foreign books and magazines and
newspapers,'' she said, although she could not name any not banned.
``But we do not allow those foreign magazines and newspapers whose
content interferes in China's internal affairs ... to spread
unchecked on Chinese soil. This is quite natural.''
   In Paris, student leader Wu'er Kaixi and four other men who have
fled China called on ``all people in the world blessed with a moral
conscience to come to our aid and help us put an end immediately to
these atrocious acts of repression.''
   They said a confidential report in China reported more than
120,000 arrests in the suppression of the democracy movement since
early June, and more than 100 secret executions in Beijing.
   Wu'er said they had received confirmation earlier in the day that
top student leader Wang Dan had been captured after more than a
month in hiding.
</TEXT>
