<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People     07-20 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People ,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul singer James Brown may have hurt his
chances for parole by having almost $40,600 in checks and cash in
his prison cell, a state spokesman said.
   Brown, 56, is serving a six-year sentence for aggravated assault
and failing to stop for police. He was moved Wednesday from
minimum-security State Park Correctional Facility to Stevenson
Correctional Institution, a medium-security prison, for violating a
rule limiting prisoners to possessing $50.
   ``That could affect the length of time he'll serve on his
sentence,'' said South Carolina Corrections Department spokesman
Francis Archibald.
   The rule is intended to prevent inmates from bribing their way
out, or commissioning new crimes.
   ``Everyone knows the rules when they come in,'' Archibald said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jonathan Edwards, who sang the hit
protest song ``Sunshine'' in 1972, prefers tunes about family life
these days.
   ``The Natural Thing,'' his current album, includes odes to
fidelity such as ``Where Did We Go Right,'' ``Fewer Threads Than
These'' and ``It's Easy to Write a Love Song.''
   ``It has proud-of-our-family, proud-of-our-love kind of theme,''
he said before a recent Nashville performance.
   ``Actually, `Sunshine' was the only flat political song I ever
did,'' Edwards said. ``It was written about authority figures,
(former president) Nixon and my father all rolled into one.''
   ``I've done some other things that attempt to make a social
comment and so forth. But I think my strength is in the love
ballad.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sidewalk preacher who doesn't like Rob Lowe
filming a movie at his apartment building should ``go to Carmel or
pull his window blinds,'' a judge said.
   Superior Court Judge Kurt Lewin made the comment, which referred
to a quiet California resort town, on Wednesday when he rejected
John Medford's request for a restraining order against the filming
of ``Bad Influence.''
   Moviemaker Trans World Entertainment has a valid contract with
the building's board of governors for the filming, the judge ruled.
   Medford, a worship leader at a local Southern Baptist church who
preaches weekly on downtown sidewalks, objected because of an
Atlanta mother's accusation that Lowe persuaded her teen-age
daughter to have sex with a woman while he videotaped it.
   ``It's tacky, disgusting and wrong as can be,'' said Medford, 47.
But he went on to predict, ``God's will will be worked out.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nan Wood Graham, the model for the
dour-faced farm woman in the painting ``American Gothic,''
celebrated her 90th birthday by singing turn-of-the-century songs
and posing for a few photos.
   About 30 friends and relatives gathered Wednesday at a
convalescent hospital to celebrate with the sister of painter Grant
Wood. Graham and the family dentist posed in 1930 for ``American
Gothic,'' portraying a farmer and his spinster daughter enduring
harsh rural life.
   ``The painting has become my entire life,'' she said. ``It has
gotten me invitations to places I would never have seen.''
   The sister said Wood received only $300 for the painting in a
contest sponsored by the Art Institute of Chicago and never made
another dollar from it after that.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald Wallace, brother of former Gov.
George Wallace, goes to trial Sept. 5 on charges he filed false
federal income tax returns.
   Wallace, 68, pleaded innocent Wednesday before U.S. District
Judge Myron Thompson. Wallace, who often was embroiled in
controversy during his brother's time in office, refused to talk to
reporters after the hearing.
   If convicted, the maximum possible sentence is three years in
prison and a $100,000 fine on each count. He could also be required
to pay back taxes and interest.
   He is charged with failing to report more than $30,000 in income
in 1984 and $135,000 in 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Candice Bergen considered her
ventriloquist father's dummy, Charlie McCarthy, a rival when she was
growing up in Beverly Hills.
   But you wouldn't know it from her Manhattan apartment, where she
lives with her husband, French film director Louis Malle, and their
3-year-old daughter. It is filled with mementos of Edgar Bergen's
dummy _ including enamel pins with movable mouths.
   ``When I was born, the papers called me his sister,'' Bergen, 43
and star of TV's ``Murphy Brown,'' told Parade magazine in an
interview to be published Sunday. ``And I guess there were times, as
I was growing up, when I did feel as if he were my brother.''
   ``In a public sense, he was sort of my nemesis, because when I
was on my father's show, I wasn't allowed the laughs. Mostly, the
laughs belonged to Charlie.''
