<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-US     07-20 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-US,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Consular Officer Denied Access to Detained American</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Consular officer said she was
denied access Thursday to a detained American photographer for the
fifth day since arriving in Kabul to oversee his release.
   The government announced July 1 it will free Tony O'Brien without
trial, but did not say when. O'Brien was arrested June 8 for being
in company of Moslem guerrillas.
   ``I do not know when they will let him out. There is no
indication,'' said Renny Smith, a consular officer from the U.S.
Embassy in New Delhi, India.
   The government Sunday demanded a formal letter from the U.S.
State Department, requesting O'Brien's release and authorizing Ms.
Smith to take him home. The letter arrived Wednesday, Ms. Smith said.
   ``I have been visiting various ministries and offices here since
I arrived on Sunday, but I do not have a clue to what is going on,''
she said.
   O'Brien, 43, of Santa Fe, N.M., entered the country without a
visa and was arrested by security forces at a guerrilla hideout in
Kabul. He has not been charged.
   He has been covering the war from the Pakistani frontier city of
Peshawar.
   O'Brien was on assignment for Time-Life Inc. when he crossed into
Afghanistan with the guerrillas known as mujahedeen, or Islamic holy
warriors.
   The guerrillas, backed by the United States and based in
neighboring Pakistan, have been fighting to overthrow the Marxist
government for 11 years.
   The United States and other Western nations closed their
embassies in Kabul shortly before Soviet troops withdrew from
Afghanistan in February.
</TEXT>
