<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolClosed     07-20 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Closed,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Close School to Investigate Ooze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUDAHY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials closed an elementary school so
workers can excavate the playground, which on warm days oozes a
highly acidic black substance that contains chemicals that may cause
cancer.
   Park Avenue Elementary was built 21 years ago at the site of an
unauthorized landfill.
   Parents of its 1,100 students were informed by letters taken home
by their children Wednesday that the school will be closed next
week, said Los Angeles Unified School District spokeswomnes.
   Park Avenue is a year-round school. For now, children will use
two schools that are closed for the summer; another transfer may be
nan Diana
Munatoecessary in September, officials said.
   Superintendent Leonard Britton said the school will be shut while
workers excavate the playground to determine what is underneath.
Black ooze has seeped through the school's asphalt playground since
it opened, but the asphalt simply was repaved, according to former
students.
   A private study issued in December said some chemicals in the
substance were carcinogenic _ capable of causing cancer. The report,
by Thorne Environmental Inc. of Anaheim, said the substance would
present a danger only if it was eaten, rubbed on the body or set
afire and its vapors inhaled.
   Cudahy is about seven miles southeast of downtown Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
