<FIRST>r w AM-US-Burma     07-20 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Burma,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>United States Casts Doubt On Burma's Intention To Hold Free Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Thursday the arrests
of opposition activists in Burma ``cast serious doubts'' on the
government's stated intention to hold free elections next year.
   The State Department called on the Burmese authorities to release
all political prisoners and allow the opposition to campaign in
preparation for the balloting.
   It confirmed reports from Rangoon that authorities had placed
Burma's top opposition leader, Aung San Suu Kyi, under house arrest
and detained at least 42 protesters Wednesday. Troops prevented
access to the home of Ms. Suu Kyi of the National League for
Democracy, a vocal opponent of the government and the daughter of a
celebrated independence leader.
   Saw Maung pledged to hold general elections by early next year,
and Western diplomats in Rangoon say authorities have been
increasingly concerned by Ms. Suu Kyi's growing popularity.
   Relations between the United States and Burma have been strained
since army commander Saw Maung seized power in a coup in September
and killed hundreds of people to crush a nationwide campaign for
democracy.
   The United States responded by suspending some 12 million dollars
in aid, meant mostly for development projects and to help fight
narcotics growing and trafficking.
   ``The United States government is deeply disturbed by this series
of actions taken against Burma's largest political party, which cast
serious doubts on the Burmese government's repeated promises to hold
free and fair elections by may of 1990,'' the statement said.
   It urged authorities to allow ``freedom of movement and
expression and to release other political priosners. We also hope
the Burmese government will permit the political activity essential
for the holding of democratic elections.''
</TEXT>
