<FIRST>r w AM-Deficit     07-20 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deficit,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBO Offers Tough Choices to Meet Federal Deficit Targets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Greenspan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meeting deficit reduction targets in fiscal
1991 without a tax increase or a cutback in Social Security benefits
would require a 10 percent across-the-board cut in federal spending,
the Congressional Budget Office said Tuesday.
   The $74 billion to $88 billion in spending cuts needed to meet
the fiscal 1991 defict tartget of $64 billion without raising taxes
would likely force the economy into a recession unless the Federal
Reserve Board further loosens its reins on inflation substantially,
the House Budget Committee was told.
   ``The central bank would have to permit faster money growth and a
substantial decline in interest rates to ... offset the direct
depressing effect of actions taken to reduce the deficit,'' CBO
Director Robert D. Reischauer told the panel.
   Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan told the House Banking Committee that
he is willing to push interest rates lower to avoid a recession, but
warned it is ``a difficult balancing act.''
   ``Some day, some event will end the extraordinary sting of
economic advances that has prevailed since late 1982,'' he said.
   Reischauer put the chances of the economy slipping into a
recession during the next nine months ``in the 15 percent to 40
percent range.''
   ``Retail sales have been disappointing in recent months ... (but)
the weakness is at least partly offset by continued growth in
personal income,'' he said. ``The stock market, which has always
fallen before in previous recessions, continues to rise. And the
recent decline in interest rates is likely eventually to help
housing and spending on durable goods.''
   But, like the Fed, the CBO is forecasting a more modest 2.4
percent rate of economic growth this year, slowing to 2 percent in
1990. The administration has predicted the economy will grow by 2.7
percent this year and 2.6 percent next after adjustments for
inflation.
   The congressional forecasters also think inflation, interest
rates and unemployment for all of this year and 1990 will higher
than what the administration has forecast, but only slightly.
   With the economy slowing, it also predicts that civilian
unemployment will rise from its current 5.3 percent to average 5.5
percent in 1990.
   The House committee's chairman, Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., said
the CBO's economic growth projections have consistently been less
optimistic ``and more accurate'' that those of the administration.
   ``Despite the soft landing projected by both CBO and the
administration,'' Panetta said, it will be impossible to meet
1991-93 deficit reductions targets of $64 billion, $28 billion and
zero without a tax increase or cuts in ``non-means-tested
entitlements'' such as Social Security.
   Reischauer said the CBO has reduced its estimate for the deficit
for the current fiscal year that ends on Sept. 30 from $159 billion
forecast last February to $150 billion.
   ``Although the 1989 deficit is almost certain to exceed the
Balanced Budget Act target of $136 billion, it may not exceed the
target by much more than $10 billion allowed in the law,'' he said.
   Although the congressional auditors have not yet incorporated
their economic projections into budget estimates, Reischauer said
the deficit outlook for 1990 is unlikely to change substantially
from CBO's forecast of $116.8 billion to $140.1 billion.
   The difference in those figues is whether Congress includes the
immediate $50 billion cost of the savings and loan bailout in the
deficit as Democrats want or finances it through 30-year private
bonds as advocated by President Bush.
   Bush's S&amp;L bailout plan would actually reduce the deficit by $3
billion next year because the money collected through the bonds
would count as revenues to the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0433 07-20 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says US Would Be Loser in Barring of Contacts with PLO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 7 grafs on Bush letter, edits for transition.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today the United States and
Israel would be the big losers if the Senate seeks to bar U.S.
contacts with officials of the Palestine Liberation Organization
linked to terrorist attacks on Americans.
   In a letter to Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine,
Bush said adoption of such a ban ``would interfere significantly
with, if not destroy'' U.S. ability to promote peace in the Middle
East.
   After six months of talks between U.S. Ambassador Robert
Pelletreau and PLO officials in Tunisia, the discussions are at a
``promising diplomatic juncture,'' Bush wrote. ``This is not the
time to take away from the executive a key tool of our diplomacy.''
   Pelletreau is the designated U.S. contact with the PLO in the
talks, designed to encourage eventual discussions between Israel and
Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza strip.
   Mitchell signaled that he would seek to kill the move, pressed by
Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and offer instead compromise language that
would give the administration greater flexibility to continue the
current talks.
   Helms insisted that Bush be required to certify that the United
States was not dealing with PLO officials who were in any way
connected with terrorist acts against Americans. The compromise,
expected to be voted on later in the day, would prohibit the
contacts only if the president knows and advises Congress that the
officials ``directly participated'' in terrorism.
   Bush said the Helms language would ``significantly and possibly
decisively'' undermine the Tunis talks and the peace process. ``The
big losers would be Israel and ourselves. I am sure that you and
your colleagues would not want to assume such a responsibility,'' he
said.
   But Helms and other senators held out for requiring the president
to make a certification to Congress, which the White House
considered an infringement on its authority.
   Bush and his two principal foreign policy advisers, Secretary of
State James A. Baker III and National Security Adviser Brent
Scowcroft, had worked throughout the day on Wednesday to kill the
amendment by Helms and Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., barring talks
with any PLO official ever linked to the death, injury or kidnapping
of Americans.
   Baker, appearing on the MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour, said the Helms
amendment would ``terminate the dialogue that's been established
between United States and the PLO.''
   ``We think it's important ... that we maintain this dialogue if
we're going to make progress toward peace in the Middle East,''
Baker added.
   Congressional sources said Sens. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, and
Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, also were among the holdouts.
   Bush, who invited Democratic and Republican leaders of Congress
to the White House on Wednesday for a report on his just-completed
trip to Europe, used the occasion to lobby against the amendment.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., said Bush told the lawmakers that ``if
you pass this amendment and shut down any negotiations with anybody
that's ever even breathed on the PLO ... that's a step backward, not
a step forward.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush told the
lawmakers ``that at this point in the peace process, fragile as it
may be, that these kinds of limitations would not be helpful.''
   The United States opened talks with the PLO in December after
Arafat publicly renounced terrorism and accepted Israel's right to
exist. Pelletreau has met periodically with PLO officials without
evidence of headway toward settling the Arab-Israeli dispute.
   After it was disclosed he had held two unannounced meetings with
Saleh Khalaf, the security chief of the PLO and Arafat's principal
deputy, supporters of Israel led by Helms and Kerry developed their
legislation to limit the contacts.
   Khalaf, also known as Abu Iyad, was the founder and leader of
Black September, which carried out a massacre of Israeli athletes at
the Olympic Games in Munich in 1972. He was also a suspect in the
murder of Cleo A. Noel Jr., the U.S. ambassador to the Sudan in 1973.
   The proposed compromise has the effect of barring talks with
organizers, such as Khalaf, or the actual perpetrators of terrorism,
but not limiting talks with officials whose direct involvement was
not clear.
   The lawmakers voiced praise for Bush's performance on his 10-day,
four-nation trip to Europe, and gave an early signal of strong
support for his promise of $125 million to spur free enterprise in
Poland and Hungary.
</TEXT>
