<FIRST>r i AM-Guatemala     07-20 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Knocks TV Station off Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb knocked a TV station off the air and
a guard was shot to death after the station ignored warnings not to
broadcast news about the anniversary of the Sandinista revolution in
Nicaragua, employees and police said Thursday.
   The attack on a tower of the privately owned Televisiete
Channel-7 occurred Wednesday night at Cerro Alux, on a mountain 16
miles outside the capital.
   A Televisiete official who spoke on condition of anonymity said
station employees had been threatened for several days and were
warned Wednesday not to broadcast news about the celebration of the
10th anniversary of the revolution that brought the leftist
Sandinistas to power in neighboring Nicaragua.
   The station covered the Sandinista ceremonies and broadcast an
interview with Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega on Wednesday.
   A news release by the fire department described the damage to the
tower and adjacent broadcasting equipment as extensive. The
Televisiete official said Channel-7 may be off the air for as much
as a month.
   Police identified the dead guard as Roberto Perez Paniagua, 62,
and said he had worked as a night watchman for the station for 24
years.
   The National Police said explosives experts searched the Yurrita
Church in the southern part of the capital Wednesday night after the
parish priest received an anonymous call saying there was a bomb
inside. No bomb was found.
   Earlier Wednesday, the fire department said experts found and
deactivated a homemade bomb containing four sticks of dynamite at
the entrance of the Guatemalan Army Bank after evacuating 350 people
who worked in the building.
   Rightist terrorist groups have been active against leftist
guerrillas who have been fighting for power in Guatemala for more
than four decades.
</TEXT>
