<FIRST>r a AM-ArsenicPoisoning     07-20 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arsenic Poisoning,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Going `One Body at a Time' In Arsenic Poisoning Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators are going ``one body at a
time'' as they review other deaths for possible ties to a woman
accused of fatally poisoning two men and making a third man ill, the
sheriff said Thursday.
   Blanche Taylor Moore, 56, was arrested Tuesday and charged with
assault in the poisoning of her current husband and with murder in
connection with the deaths of her first husband and a boyfriend.
Also this week, a judge gave permission for police to exhume the
body of Mrs. Moore's father, but no charges have been filed in that
case.
   Through her lawyer, she has denied all charges. She remains
jailed pending a bond hearing.
   ``We don't know where it's going to go to,'' said Alamance County
Sheriff Richard L. Frye. ``We can only take it one step at a time,
one body at a time. It's a long process to exhume anyone, so we can
only take so much at one time.''
   Meanwhile, the Winston-Salem Journal quoted unidentified sources
as saying that a good friend of Mrs. Moore's, a woman, may have died
of arsenic poisoning. Television station WGHP in High Point said one
death that may be investigated is that of a co-worker who was
believed to have died of cancer.
   But Frye declined to provide details of his investigation or what
deaths are being looked into.
   ``We confirmed we do have some names that we're checking into and
we will not release the names and we will not release whether it's
male or female,'' he said.
   ``People are calling us and giving us information,'' he said.
``The Burlington police have some (information) that they are
checking out. Anything that we come up with will be entirely up to
the chief medical examiner and the attorney as to where we go from
here.''
   Mrs. Moore was charged in Alamance County with assault with a
deadly weapon with intent to kill in the arsenic poisoning of her
husband, the Rev. Dwight Moore. He fell ill on their honeymoon this
spring and is still hospitalized.
   After doctors said Moore was suffering from arsenic poisoning,
authorities decided to exhume the bodies of Mrs. Moore's first
husband, James N. Taylor, who died in 1973, and a boyfriend, Raymond
Reid, who died in 1986. Tests on those bodied led to the murder
charges.
   Also this week, a judge ordered the exumation of the body of her
father, Parker D. Kiser Sr., to determine whether his 1966 death was
caused by arsenic poisoning. The body has not yet been exhumed.
</TEXT>
