<FIRST>u a PM-DC-10Crash 7thLd-Writethru a0673 07-20 1266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash, 7th Ld - Writethru, a0673,1299</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC-10 Wreckage Searched; Airline Says 186 Survived Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with airline saying survivors number
186. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `It's tragic...' SUBS 12th graf, `CNN reported...',
to delete now-outdated reference.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserColor SCX6,DC2,DC3; LaserPhotos SCX1,2,3,4,5,7, CX17, DX1; LaserGraphics
NY57</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA JORDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators and rescue crews conducted
an ``inch-by-inch'' sweep today of the cornfield where a United
DC-10 crashed, cartwheeling in a ball of flame and splitting apart.
At least 74 people were killed.
   The airline said 186 of the 293 people aboard survived after the
plane, crippled by a loss of hydraulic power, crashed during an
emergency landing. Earlier, the number of survivors had been put at
176.
   ``We feel pretty confident about that number,'' Russell Mack, a
United spokesman, said at an afternoon briefing, but he added that
the airline had not quite completed a list of passengers.
   The plane hit the Sioux Gateway Airport runway Wednesday and
cartwheeled in a ball of fire into the field. But many survivors
walked away from the crash.
   Today, rescuers looked through the wreckage for victims. If there
were 74 dead and 186 survivors, that would leave 33 people
unaccounted-for.
   ``It's tragic what happened, but amazing and delightful that so
many survived,'' Rachel Halterman, National Transportation Safety
Board spokeswoman, said today from the agency's makeshift command
center in the Sioux City Convention Center.
   ``Even the investigators can't say why so many people survived,''
she added, ``and there hasn't been time for speculation.''
   ``The idea is to form teams and start pulling together the clues.
It will be an inch-by-inch thing,'' Ms. Halterman said. ``The flight
recorder will be going back to Washington sometime today and we'll
start interviewing the crew and the survivors, eyewitnesses and
everybody we can who has first-hand knowledge of the accident. We're
also collecting maintenance records on the plane.''
   National Guardsmen began working at daybreak, collecting pieces
of the wreckage which were strewn over an area the length of three
football fields. Ambulances and refrigerated trailers for the
storage of remains were parked along the runway where the plane hit
before skidding into a field.
   ``We swept the area four times last night for survivors. If they
were fatalities, they just covered them up and went on,'' said an
official of the Woodbury County Civil Defense and Disaster Agency
who asked not to be identified. ``Today, we've started removing
bodies ... and everything else.''
   A flight attendant who survived the crash by crawling out of an
opening in the burning wreckage was quoted by her parents as saying
``the Lord opened up that hole'' to allow her to escape.
   CNN reported that emergency officials believed most of the
missing were in the fuselage and were fairly confident that anyone
still in the wreckage was dead.
   The 15-year-old jumbo jet experienced ``complete hydraulic
failure'' before the crash, Federal Aviation Administration
spokesman Fred Farrar said. Parts of the plane were found 50 miles
away.
   Flight attendant Virginia Jane Murray, 35, phoned her parents in
Chester, S.C., to say she was all right.
   ``She said she was tumbling,'' said her father, Don Murray. ``The
walls were coming in. She said a hole opened up and the sunlight
came in and she climbed out the hole. She said she knew the Lord
opened up that hole.''
   Murray said he did not know the extent of his daughter's injuries
except that she was not burned.
   ``I thought I was going to die,'' said 8-year-old Ben Radtke of
Prairie View, Ill., who was carried out of the fractured fuselage by
a passenger. The boy, shaking but unhurt, clutched a United Airlines
button and a pair of plastic pilot's wings as he spoke.
   Flight 232, from Denver to Philadelphia via Chicago, carried 11
crew members and 282 passengers, including three infants, said
United spokesman Lawrence Nagin. The plane has a capacity of 287
passengers.
   Most of the survivors were sitting in the middle of the plane, in
rows 9 to 19, said Dr. David Greco, director of the emergency
department and helicopter services for the Marian Health Center,
where many of the injured were taken.
   ``There was nothing left of the rear half of the aircraft. First
class was devastated,'' Greco said. Except for the midsection, ``the
rest of the aircraft was in tiny little debris.''
   The Seattle-based cockpit crew was being treated for injuries at
a hospital, Nagin said. He identified the crew as Capt. A.C. Haynes,
a 33-year United veteran; First Officer W.R. Records; and Second
Officer D.J. Dvorak.
   Hydraulic systems provide power steering that allows pilots to
manipulate the wing and tail controls of the jumbo jet. Without it,
aviation officials say the plane would be uncontrollable.
   The tail engine failed, and this may have caused a hydraulic
failure, said Bob Raynesford, another FAA spokesman. The plane's
three independent hydraulic systems are routed to the tail section.
   The crash left a swath of charred runway and strewed bits of
people's lives over the wide expanse: two sets of golf clubs, a
wallet photo of a brunette in her prom dress, a Reebok tennis shoe,
a purple hairdryer, one black high-heeled shoe and a collection of
Marilyn Monroe photographs.
   Four people near Alta, 55 miles east of Sioux City, discovered a
piece of the plane, 6 to 7 feet high and 6 feet long, in a corn
field.
   Four miles away, Allen and Phil Jahde found three pieces of the
plane scattered in their cornfield. Phil Jahde said one piece was a
6-foot-long metal band, engraved ENG 2.
   The plane may have experienced problems earlier Wednesday. Ruth
Dinsmore, of Mount Laurel, N.J., said she took the same DC-10 from
Philadelphia to Denver in the morning. The plane made the return
trip later.
   She said the plane began to leave the terminal at Philadelphia
International Airport shortly after 10 a.m., when ``everything sort
of shut off.'' The plane taxied back to the terminal, where it sat
about 15 minutes for repairs.
   However, Roland Herwig, a spokesman for the FAA center in
Oklahoma City, said it is ``complete hearsay at this point'' that
the plane had had problems earlier Wednesday.
   Herwig said nobody official has said there was a problem. ``We
don't even know if it was the same airplane,'' he said.
   United spokeswoman Kim Thomas in Chicago said she could not
confirm that the DC-10 had difficulty earlier in the day and read
this statement:
   ``I've been advised that maintenance records are what is called
`material,' which means they are part of the NTSB and FAA
investigations. Because of that, the information is not being
released.''
   The plane was flying southwest as it approached the airport, and
its wings rocked as it descended until the craft pitched violently
to its right, causing the right wing to hit the ground and sending
the plane into a cartwheel. The plane nose and fuselage ended upside
down.
   Survivor Mark Michaelson of Denver said during the last 30
minutes of the flight the attendants drilled the passengers on
emergency procedures and instructed them to put their heads between
their knees.
   After the crash, passenger Cliff Marshall of Columbus, Ohio, said
people were ``sitting there upside down and it began to fill up with
smoke.''
   ``Then God opened a hole in the basement and I pushed a little
girl out,'' he said. ``I grabbed another, kept pulling them out
until they didn't come no more.''
   Marshall said he thought he helped a half-dozen out. Then he ran.
   Several others walked away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
