<FIRST>u i AM-Burma     07-20 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Puts Opposition Leader Under House Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's military government put the main
opposition leader under house arrest Thursday and soldiers sealed
off her home in a Rangoon suburb, according to diplomatic reports
from the Burmese capital.
   Hundreds of students had defied martial law with anti-government
protests Wednesday even though the opposition leader, Aung San Suu
Kyi, canceled a planned rally to avoid clashes with the large number
of soldiers in the streets. Burma's official radio reported 44
arrests.
   A source in Bangkok, citing a report from a Western embassy in
the Burmese capital, said Ms. Suu Kyi's ``compound was surrounded by
troops'' and ``she tried to surrender herself to the military, but
they refused and they forced her back inside.''
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a diplomat
and Tin Oo, co-leader of Ms. Suu Kyi's National League for
Democracy, were turned away when they tried to see her.
   No other details were available. Telephone and telex lines to
Rangoon from Bangkok and other Asian cities were out of order
Thursday.
   In Washington, the State Department confirmed Ms. Suu Kyi, 44,
was under house arrest and that soldiers were blocking access to her
home. It said the arrest of opposition activists ``cast serious
doubts'' on the government's stated intention of holding free
elections next year.
   Rangoon radio did not mention Ms. Suu Kyi on Thursday, but said
diplomats were being summoned to a meeting Friday with the
government's Information Committee.
   It announced an amnesty for people tried on or before Sept. 18,
1988. Gen. Saw Maung, the army commander, seized power on that day
and his soldiers killed hundreds of people demonstrating peacefully
for democracy.
   Saw Maung signed the amnesty order, which commutes death
sentences to life imprisonment, reduces life terms to 10 years and
cuts other sentences by one-third.
   Prisoners with two years or less to serve will be released and
criminal cases still being heard will be closed, with the exceptions
of those involving high treason or violation of martial law, the
order said.
   The Bangkok source said the reason for Ms. Suu Kyi's arrest was
not clear, but the government may have used violence during
Wednesday's Martyrs Day ceremonies as a pretext to move against her.
   He said her arrest also might be linked to those of three members
of her party accused of bombing a government oil refinery earlier
this month. Three people were killed.
   Ms. Suu Kyi, whose father was an independence leader, is the
military government's most vocal critic. Western diplomats say the
authorities have been concerned about the growing popularity that
attracts thousands of people to her rallies.
   ``Aung San Suu Kyi has been looking for a confrontation,'' the
source in Bangkok said. ``Now it's happened.''
   Ms. Suu Kyi had planned to lead thousands in a march Wednesday,
the anniversary of the day her father, Aung San, and other Burmese
independence leaders were assassinated in 1947. Burma became
independent of Britain in January 1948.
   On Wednesday, Ms. Suu Kyi said she canceled the march because
soldiers ``blocked off all the roads and prepared literally a
killing field for the people.''
   In a telephone interview from Rangoon, she also said soldiers had
beaten some of about 3,000 students in the capital's Swegondine
district.
   A Western diplomat, also reached by telephone, said he saw
soldiers pursue students down a side street, drag some out and hit
them with clubs, then put 15 or 20 into a truck.
</TEXT>
