<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 2047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SovietReunion     07-20 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Reunion,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Concentration Camp Survivor to Reunite With American Liberators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dick Fitzsimmons doesn't how he'll react
when he sees Vladimir Kutz of the Soviet Union for the first time
in more than 44 years.
   But he knows the reunion Tuesday with the man he knew as a
skinny teen-ager he helped save from a Nazi concentration camp will
be a happy one.
   ``I never expected to see him again, and when I do, I probably
won't be able to say a word,'' Fitzsimmons said. ``It all just
doesn't seem real.''
   Fitzsimmons was an 18-year-old American infantryman serving in
Germany when he met Kutz, 17, doing slave labor at a Nazi work camp
at the end of World War II in March 1945.
   Kutz is scheduled to fly to the United States from his Moscow
home to Dover, N.H., for the reunion with Fitzsimmons, 63, a
retired electrician in Rutland, Vt., and William Riska of
Connecticut. In August, Kutz is to meet two other men from the old
4th Infantry Division, Robert Nystrom of Harrisburg, Pa., and
Patrick Mealy of California.
   The five will have plenty to talk about because it's likely none
of them them would have lived to see the end of the war if they had
never met. The young prisoner returned the favor of his freedom by
warning the Americans of a German ambush.
   The Americans were ready and ``fought right through them,''
Fitzsimmons remembers.
   The reunion was arranged by John Barr, vice president of the
national Veterans for Peace organization and a member of its Dover
chapter. On a January 1988 trip to the Soviet Union, he was met at
the airport by Kurtz's son, Yuri, who read about his visit in a
newspaper.
   The young Kurtz retold his father's story of being saved by men
of the 4th Division, and provided a few names and hometowns written
on a scrap of paper his father had saved since the war.
   Barr and members of his organization managed to track down the
four old soldiers, who got choked up remembering ``Willie.''
   Vladimir became ``Willie'' to the Americans, ``because we
couldn't pronounce his first name and didn't have time to learn,''
Fitzsimmons said.
   Fitzsimmons has vivid memories of his Soviet friend.
   ``He was a kind of small, rawboned kid,'' he said. ``They didn't
feed him very well.''
   After the ambush, Willie tagged along and was adopted by the
division.
   ``We dressed him and fed him and put him to work as a
machine-gunner for two months,'' Fitzsimmons recalled.
   Though he spoke no English and no Americans spoke his native
Ukrainian, the men were able to communicate in sign language,
Fitzsimmons said.
   When it was time for him to go home, Willie went in style,
Fitzsimmons said.
   ``Some men commandeered a German staff car and we taught Willie
how to drive it,'' he said. ``We gave him the car and sent him on
his way toward Moscow.''
   Barr said this is Willie's first visit to the United States and
that it will coincide with a reunion of 4th Division veterans in
Cherry Hill, N.J. in August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0149 </DOCNO>
