<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     07-20 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Free 24 Political Prisoners; U.N. Chief Visits Namibia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Territorial officials Thursday freed 24
guerrillas described as the last political prisoners in Namibia,
and the U.N. secretary-general said the plan for the territory's
independence is on schedule.
   The freed guerrillas of the South-West African People's
Organization sang a tribal ballad as they emerged from the prison
in Windhoek and were escorted home by nearly 200 supporters, who
cheered and jogged with them nearly two miles in a freezing wind.
   Eight jailed SWAPO members, including some responsible for
bombings that killed more than 30 people, have not been designated
political prisoners and remain jailed.
   The U.N. leader, Javier Perez de Cuellar, visited northern
Namibia's Ongwediva refugee camp, home to hundreds of people who
have been repatriated by the United Nations. About 1,200 people
live in tents in the dry, dusty camp.
   Perez de Cuellar also visited a voter registration station and
met with U.N. officials and human rights workers. More than 5,000
U.N. military and civilian personnel are in Namibia to monitor a
yearlong transition to independence after 74 years of South African
rule.
   Several thousand people, many dressed in the red, green and blue
colors of SWAPO, circled Perez de Cuellar when he arrived at the
camp, a U.N. flag fluttering on the hood of his Mercedes-Benz.
   Some held placards claiming harassment by Namibian policemen who
served on a disbanded paramilitary unit known as Koevoet.
   Perez de Cuellar indicated he was pleased with the progress of
the independence plan, which took effect April 1 and includes
elections in November.
   But when asked if he was satisfied with the security situation
in northern Namibia, he said, ``No, I'm not... We have to fight
against intimidation and partiality.''
   After 23 years of war between SWAPO and South African
authorities, local residents are deeply suspicious of Namibian
police, who remain responsible for law enforcement during the
transition to independence.
   Most people in northern Namibia support SWAPO.
   No fighting has been reported in northern Namibia since April,
but territorial officials claim 1,900 SWAPO guerrillas are in
southernmost Angola, near the Namibian border, in violation of a
regional peace accord.
   Police in northern Namibia said Thursday that officers uncovered
an arms cache that included a Soviet-made ground-to-air missile,
grenades, and assault rifles.
   SWAPO denies its fighters are near the border but has not said
why thousands of guerrillas remain in Angola when they are allowed
to return to Namibia as civilians.
   SWAPO also has said it released all 201 detainees that it held.
But relatives, and the freed detainees, have said there were nearly
2,000 prisoners in SWAPO camps.
   In Washington, the assistant secretary of state for African,
Herman J. Cohen, suggested Thursday that former President Jimmy
Carter might go privately to Namibia to observe the November
election.
   Cohen noted that Carter observed the election last May in
Panama. He was testifying before the subcommittee on Africa of the
Foreign Affairs Committee in the House of Representatives.
Afterward, he told reporters he had not asked Carter about going to
Namibia.
</TEXT>
