<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan-Children 1stLd-Writethru a0671 07-20 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Children, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0671,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>War's Children Taken To Europe For Treatment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with children arriving in Frankfurt; CORRECTS spelling
of Friedensdorf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atiqullah, 7, was caught in a cross
fire and his wounds became infected. He would have died like
countless others, but foreign volunteers found him and took him
away for treatment in Europe.
   Tens of thousands of children are among the estimated 1.3
million victims of the civil war that has ravaged Afghanistan for
11 years.
   Fighting has disrupted access to much of the mountainous nation.
Moslem guerrillas control most of the countryside and the communist
government's army has the cities.
   The United Nations says fewer than 30 percent of Afghanistan's
10 million people have access to medical treatment and three of 10
children die before their fifth birthday, the highest infant
mortality rate in the world.
   At least one in 10 Afghan children suffers from disease or
injuries related to the war.
   Atiqullah's wounds could have been treated after he was shot
seven months ago, but they remained open and became infected
because of a shortage of surgeons and antibiotics in the
deteriorating health-care system.
   Ultimately, however, Atiqullah was among the lucky ones. On
Monday, he boarded an airplane for the first time in his life to
begin a journey that may see him fully recovered and back home in a
year.
   He was one of 20 children who arrived in Frankfurt on Thursday
for advanced medical treatment arranged by a West German volunteer
organization.
   ``If he is left here, he is going to die in four weeks,'' said
Dr. Eberhard Thoma of Friedensdorf (Peace Village) International.
``He is in a devastating state.''
   ``What we see (in Kabul) makes us sick,'' said Ronald
Gegenfurtner, president of Friedensdorf International. ``Imagine
what is happening in the countryside.
   ``We are shocked to see the large number of innocent Afghan
children who are suffering from a war aided by so-called civilized
countries and superpowers.''
   The Kabul government is sponsored by the Soviet Union and the
United States supports the Moslem guerrillas who have fought it
since a communist coup in April 1978.
   Friedensdorf International came to Afghanistan in December and
has helped treat at least 88 children wounded in the war. About 25
of them have returned home.
   Wolfgang Martens, a Friedensdorf spokesman in West Germany, said
the latest group flew out of Kabul on Monday during rocket attacks.
   Three girls and 17 boys aged 5-12 were in the group. Thoma said
at least seven had bone marrow infections and ``to get them cured,
we will have to operate several times.''
   ``There is no way you can perform these operations in Kabul,''
he said. ``The hospitals here just don't have the facilities.
   ``In some hospitals, they don't have bandages. They use ordinary
cloth, sometimes torn from the garments of victims, to tie up
wounds.''
   Gegenfurtner said members of Friedensdorf International would
return in three months to pick up another group of children.
</TEXT>
