<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strike 1stLd-Writethru a0711 07-20 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0711,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Coal Strike Spreads To Five More Areas But Eases in Another</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with fifth walkout; picks up 9th pvs, `Official
news...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROKOPYEVSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal miners walked off their jobs
in five more regions, but the Siberian strikers who started the
Soviet Union's worst labor unrest in decades were told Thursday to
return to work by dawn Friday.
   ``We have agreed to interrupt the strike, not to end it,'' said
Vyacheslav G. Akulov, a strike committee member in Prokopyevsk in
Siberia's Kuznetsk Coal Basin.
   The strike committee asked the estimated 150,000 strikers in the
region to return to the pits at dawn Friday after a government and
Communist Party commission agreed to give them greater control over
their industry, Akulov said. The commission also agreed to improve
the miners' food, housing and working conditions.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has said the concessions granted
the miners in the Kuznetsk region will apply to all miners
nationwide. State-run TV repeated that promise Thursday night in an
apparent effort to end the country's worst labor unrest since the
1920s.
   Some Siberian miners have already returned to work. Tass said
nine out of 11 mining centers were operating, and Prokopyevsk's
central Victory Square was empty Thursday night after nearly two
weeks of rallies and demonstrations by thousands of strikers.
   But the strike spread in other areas as miners raised demands
similar to those of the Kuznetsk strikers, who began the walkout 10
days ago.
   Miners in the northern town of Vorkuta, the Don River city of
Rostov and the Ukrainian industrial center of Dnepropetrovsk,
walked out Wednesday with demands similar to those of the strike
instigators in Kuznetsk, Tass reported. Dnepropetrovsk is in the
Donetsk coal basin, the nation's leading coal region.
   On Thursday, more than 16,000 miners in Soviet Central Asia's
Karaganda region, the country's third-largest coal field, refused
to go down into the pits and were massing by the thousands for
rallies, Tass and the government newspaper Izvestia reported.
   Miners at three shafts in Chervonograd in the western Ukraine
joined the walkout Thursday night, said Anatoly M. Dotsenko, a
spokesman for the Ukrainian Helsinki Watch Group.
   Official news reports did not say how many miners were on strike
nationwide. The coal industry employs more than 1 million workers.
   Vorkuta workers striking at nine of the city's 13 mines asked
the Kremlin for an ``urgent resolution of the sharp economic and
social problems of the coal sector, and also specific problems of
workers of the far north,'' Tass said.
   Miners in Rostov demanded extra pay for evening and night
shifts, longer vacations and an increase in the price of coal to
world market prices, the news agency reported.
   Workers striking at 11 mines in Dnepropetrovsk made 24 demands
similar to those of the Kuznetsk miners, reports said.
   Karaganda strikers said they walked out to protest incomplete
news accounts of miners' demands in the Kuznetsk strikes, according
to Tass.
   The government compromised on most of the 39 demands made by the
Kuznetsk miners, who walked off the job July 11. One of the biggest
demands was for economic independence.
   Akulov said that starting Jan. 1, the Kuznetzk coal basin will
become economically autonomous.
   ``The Coal Mining Ministry will continue to run the mines, but
the miners will have a much greater say setting production levels
and allocating the profits,'' said Akulov, one of two
representatives on the regional strike committee from the town of
Anzhero-Sudzhensk, the northern-most coal settlement in Kuznetsk.
   Television quoted Coal Minister Mikhail I. Shchadov as saying
all Soviet coal operations would become economically independent.
   Akulov, whose weathered, gaunt face is typical of the miners in
the region, said the Kuznetsk miners would hold the government to
its word.
   ``If the government doesn't keep its promises, we will go back
on strike. That's in the agreement,'' he said.
   He and other strike leaders described the settlement
negotiations as ``open and very constructive.''
   ``Our politics have gotten freer under perestroika,'' said
Akulov, referring to Gorbachev's economic reform program. ``But our
living conditions have not improved.''
   Another strike committee member, Alexander S. Kukaletov, said
housing conditions remain poor and there were severe shortages of
sugar, other foods and consumer goods.
   Prokopyevsk's small wooden huts cling to the rolling hills and
expansive birch forests of Siberia. Some houses, most of which are
heated by coal-burning stoves during the long winter, sit next to
piles of slag and other mine debris.
   The youth newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda said the government has
promised to send extra meat, butter, sugar, tea, leather footwear,
furniture and cars to relieve shortages in the region.
</TEXT>
