<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-WorldCourt-US     07-20 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Court-US,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Loses World Court Case Over Plant Closure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Court on Thursday said
the United States has no right to compensation from the Italian
government for Italy's seizure of an American-owned plant 21 years
ago.
   The five-judge panel ruled 4-1 that Italy did not breach the
1948 Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation, as alleged by
Washington, when it seized the Elettronica Sicula, or ELSI, plant
in Palermo in 1968. It also voted 4-1 to deny compensation to the
United States.
   Stephen M. Schwebel, the court's only U.S. judge, opposed the
decision.
   ELSI was a cathode-ray tube factory wholly owned by Raytheon
Corp., a major defense contractor, and by another American company,
Machlett Laboratories Inc.
   Italy contended the mayor of Palermo seized the company to
safeguard the jobs of about 900 factory workers after the owners
announced plans to liquidate the firm.
   According to the U.S. complaint, the company was then sold to a
subsidiary of a conglomerate owned by the Italian government ``at a
price far less than market value,'' and Raytheon was never
compensated.
   No specific compensation amounts were demanded in court, but
U.S. sources have claimed privately that American damages in the
case were more than $6 million.
   The court, officially known as the International Court of
Justice, is the legal arm of the United Nations. It has no
enforcement powers and depends on voluntary adherence to its
decisions.
   In court, the United States complained that a ruling on the case
by an Italian court was delayed 16 months after the seizure until
ELSI was sold.
   The judges said ELSI was on a ``course to bankruptcy'' even
before it was seized.
   ``What really deprived Raytheon and Machlett as shareholders of
their right to dispose of ELSI's ... property was not the
requisition but the precarious financial state of ELSI ultimately
leading inescapably to bankruptcy,'' they said.
   Voting in favor were the court's Argentinian president, Jose
Maria Ruda, as well as judges Roberto Ago of Italy, Shigeru Oda of
Japan and Sir Robert Jennings of Britain.
   Schwebel said in a separate document attached to the ruling that
ELSI's seizure was an ``unreasonable and capricious'' measure that
``deprived Raytheon of its right to control and manage and, hence,
liquidate ELSI.''
   The ELSI case was filed in February 1987 after years of
diplomatic bargaining failed to resolve the issue.
   In 1986, the World Court denounced U.S.-sponsored military
action against Nicaragua and U.S. support for the anti-Sandinista
forces known as Contras.
   Earlier that year, in an apparent anticipation of the adverse
decision, Washington withdrew its recognition of the unlimited
jurisdiction of the court but said it would continue to accept
jurisdiction in some cases, such as the one involving Elettronica
Sicula.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
