<FIRST>r a AM-PTLTrial     07-20 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PTL Trial,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taggart Says He Was Lax About PTL Money Documentation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker's former personal aide
testified Thursday in his federal tax evasion trial he didn't have
any way to prove that cash advances he took while at the PTL
ministry were for business use.
   David Taggart said under cross-examination by prosecutor David
Brown that proper record keeping would have helped determine
whether sums of money he drew from PTL accounts were taxable or not.
   Taggart, 32, and his brother, James, are charged with evading
$525,000 in income taxes after taking nearly $1.2 million in PTL
money for their own use during a four-year period beginning in 1984.
   Under questioning by defense lawyer Ben Cotten, Taggart said
that as a vice president of the ministry, he had direct authority
from Bakker to take large cash advances, sign PTL checks, use PTL
credit cards and authorize bonuses for PTL employees.
   Taggart said he left PTL in early 1983 because of exhaustion and
job burnout. He said Bakker and his wife, Tammy, called him
numerous times with generous offers to entice him to return.
   ``He told me `David, you've killed yourself for the ministry for
$25,000 a year (as assistant music director from 1978 to 1980 and
from 1980 to 1983 as Bakker's personal assistant). Now the ministry
is in a different position and I'm willing to pay you $100,000 a
year,'' Taggart said.
   Taggart said he recalled telling Bakker, ``I want access to the
same resources that you have. But I also want to control my money.
I don't want a house or a car to be given to me.''
   Taggart said that on his return, he had authority to take large
cash advances, which he said were used primarily for trips by the
Bakkers on ministry business. He said he needed large amounts of
cash on hand at all times.
   ``Many times on a trip I would advance Tammy Bakker some cash
and she would reimburse it,'' he said. That was true of dozens of
other members of the Bakkers' entourage, he said.
   Taggart's brother James testified Wednesday that as PTL's
interior designer he was an artist who left the business dealings
to his brother.
   ``I always have been lax about documentation. It's never been a
priority,'' David Taggart said.
   Taggart's testimony came a day after Bakker invoked the Fifth
Amendment in refusing to answer questions in the trial. His
10-minute appearance was with the jury not present.
   Bakker and former top PTL aide Richard Dortch are scheduled to
go on trial Aug. 28 on conspiracy and wire and mail fraud charges.
</TEXT>
