<FIRST>r w AM-Newspapers-JOA     07-20 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspapers-JOA,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Holds Hearing on Joint Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE ANN ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation allowing rival newspapers to
publish under a Joint Operating Agreement fails to save daily
newspapers and should be repealed, the editor of a Michigan weekly
told a House panel Thursday.
   ``It has encouraged concentration of newspaper ownership,
peculiar competitive practices and lessened the vigor and quality
of newspapering,'' Michigan editor W. Edward Wendover told the
Judiciary Committee panel.
   However, Jerry Friedheim, president of the American Newspaper
Publishers Association, testified that the act ``helped the
marketplace evolve and prosper.''
   Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, called the hearing 19 years after
Congress approved the Newspaper Preservation Act, which allows
newspapers in the same city to merge business operations when one
of the papers is in danger of failing. Newsgathering operations
remain separate.
   ``In 1970, the act was hailed as a necessary means of preventing
daily newspapers from falling victim to fierce market forces,''
Brooks said. ``Yet, since passage of the act, some estimate that
over 200 papers have ceased operation.''
   Wendover, editor and publisher of the weekly The Community Crier
in Plymouth-Canton, Mich., testified on behalf of Michigan Citizens
for an Independent Press. That group, made up of 1,400 readers,
advertisers and employees of The Detroit News and Detroit Free
Press, filed a lawsuit in August to block a JOA between the two
papers.
   Gannett Co. Inc., which owns The News, and Knight-Ridder Inc.,
owner of the Free Press, say the JOA is needed to allow the Free
Press to survive.
   The U.S. Supreme Court will hear arguments on the case this
fall. There are 18 active JOAs in the United States.
   ``The principle of a free press cannot be maintained when the
biggest newspaper chains enjoy unregulated monopoly status,''
Wendover said, calling on Congress to repeal the act.
   Harsh criticism came from Bruce B. Brugmann, editor and
publisher of the 70,000 circulation weekly San Francisco Bay
Guardian. Brugmann also testified against the act when it was being
considered in 1969.
   ``Never have so many given so much to so few for no good reason
at all,'' Brugmann said, charging that the only people to benefit
from JOAs are publishers.
   The JOA between the two San Francisco dailies, the Examiner and
the Chronicle, Brugmann said, has led to less competitive
journalism.
   Also critical of the act was Louis Mleczko, a reporter for The
Detroit News and president of Local 22 of The Newspaper Guild of
Detroit. Mleczko, who is opposed to the proposed Detroit JOA, said
Congress should repeal the act and force giant chains to compete.
   ``Newspapers are more than just businesses, only concerned with
the bottom line. They are a public trust,'' Mleczko said. ``The
Robber Barons live. It's time for Congress to break up the trusts
again.''
   Brooks said his Economic and Commercial Law Subcommittee would
study the testimony and decide whether further hearings are needed.
</TEXT>
