<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--HistoricFlight     07-20 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Historic Flight,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Duplicates First Cross-Channel Flight by Bleriot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALAIS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian pilot flying a homemade replica
of the Bleriot 11 that made the first air crossing of the English
Channel 80 years ago duplicated the event Wednesday.
   Zanardo Juan Carlo took off from Calais airport at 5:25 p.m. in
the plane that took him 2,500 hours of work to build. Fifty minutes
later, he landed at the airport at Manston in southern England.
   The 48-year-old aviation enthusiast duplicated the journey of
french aviation pioneer Louis Bleriot, who made the same trip on
July 25, 1909.
   The latter-day version was accompanied across the Channel by six
other planes: four Pipers and two Tiger Moths.
   The flight was organized by a group of Italian amateur aviation
buffs.
