<SECOND>AM-Meat Packer,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meat Packer Agrees to Sell or Close Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chicago meat packer, convicted last year on
two counts of bribery, has signed an agreement with the Agriculture
Department to sell or close two companies, officials said Thursday.
   Walter S. Mander, owner of Lincoln Meat Co. Inc., and Lincoln
Provision Inc., was convicted in 1988 of bribing a federal meat
grader. The department then moved to withdraw federal inspection
from both companies.
   Officials said that after one day of hearings before an
administrative law judge, Mander on July 12 signed an order
agreeing to divest himself of the two companies _ Lincoln Meat
within 90 days, and Lincoln Provision within one year.
   Assistant Secretary Jo Ann Smith said the consent order signed
by Mander was with the department's Food Safety and Inspection
Service, and the Agricultural Marketing Service.
   The order provides for withdrawal of federal inspection and
grading services if Mander fails to sell or close the plants. Such
withdrawal effectively bars a company from selling meat across
state lines.
