<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2132EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-StateIncomes     07-20 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Incomes,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nevada's Income Growth Paces the Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nevada's income growth, driven by the state's
tourism and mining industries, outpaced other states during the
year ending last March, while income growth in Wyoming trailed the
rest of the country, the government reported Thursday.
   The Commerce Department said said that non-farm incomes rose 9.4
percent nationally in the 12 months ending March 30. But the
national average masked disparities among states and regions of the
country.
   Nevada paced the country with a non-farm income increase of 15
percent, the department said.
   Nevada's income growth was fueld by the hotel and resort
construction demands of its tourism industry and a healthy mining
industry, according to department analyst Rudolph E. DePass.
   Nevada was followed by Florida whose non-farm income was up 12.1
percent; California, up 10.7 percent; Vermont, up 10.5 percent, and
Virginia, up 10.5 percent.
   With inflation rising at an annual rate of 5.9 percent, the
figures showed those states stayed well ahead of the increase in
prices.
   Other states did not fare so well.
   Last-ranked Wyoming saw non-farm income growth rise only 5.7
percent, pulled down by declining construction and services
industry, DePass said.
   Other states at the bottom-end of the rankings were West
Virginia, up 6.3 percent; North Dakota, up 6.4 percent; Oklahoma,
up 6.9 percent, and Alaska, up 7.2 percent.
   By region, the Far West led the nation with an overall income
growth of 10.5 percent, followed by the Southeast, 9.9 percent; and
New England, 9.6 percent.
   Other regions and their income growth rates were: Great Lakes, 9
percent; Mideast, 8.9 percent; Plains, 8.8 percent; Southwest, 8.6
percent, and Rocky Mountains, 8.2 percent.
   DePass said differences in non-farm income growth between
coastal and interior regions continued to grow smaller from the
first quarter of 1988 to the first quarter of 1989, although
coastal growth continued to outpace the inland areas.
   The Commerce Department focuses on changes in non-farm income as
a better indication of a region's prosperity because of the often
erratic nature of farm incomes.
</TEXT>
