<FIRST>r w AM-MassacreAmendment     07-20 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Massacre Amendment,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Wants Report on Implications of China Massacre for Hong Kong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate wants the State Department to
consider the implications of the June massacre of Chinese
pro-democracy demonstrators on the switch of Hong Kong to China's
control in 1997.
   An amendment offered by Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., and approved
Wednesday night by the Senate in work on the $4.6 billion State
Department authorization bill, calls for a report on the
implications of the massacre and for the agency to cooperate with
allies to ensure Hong Kong's political stability.
   ``Beijing must realize that one of the costs of the massacre may
be changes in the conditions under which China regains sovereignty
over Hong Kong. The British have already signaled to China that
they intend to accelerate the process of democratization in Hong
Kong,'' Bradley said.
   ``This amendment shows our support for the efforts of the United
Kingdom, and underscores the importance we and our allies place on
the continued political and economic well-being of the people of
Hong Kong in 1997,'' Bradley added.
</TEXT>
