<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     07-20 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thailand Pushes for Cambodia Truce after Vietnam Praise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan and
other top officials tried to rally support Thursday for their
proposal to declare a truce in the Cambodia war.
   They were reacting to Vietnam's praise of the idea Wednesday.
Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach of Vietnam said he agreed with the
proposal by Chatichai this year for a truce before Vietnam's
pullout.
   Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia in December 1978 and installed
the current government, has said it will pull its 60,000 to 70,000
forces out by Sept. 30. It said it will do so even without a
settlement.
   However, Thach said on official Radio Hanoi: ``The Cambodian
issue cannot be solved peacefully without a cease-fire.
   ``Therefore, Vietnam fully supports the Thai prime minister's
proposal that the Cambodian parties sign a cease-fire agreement in
Bangkok, and considers this as part of a political solution to the
Cambodian issue,'' he said. The broadcast was monitored in Bangkok.
   Asked for his reaction Thursday, Chatichai said he had not yet
received the report. But he added that ``if the four Cambodian
parties agree, it would be great.''
   The Cambodian government has been battling a coalition of three
guerrilla groups, including the communist Khmer Rouge. The
communist group ruled Cambodia for almost four years, killing
hundreds of thousands, until they were driven out by the Vietnamese.
   Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila of Thailand told reporters the
truce issue should be raised at an international conference on
Cambodia starting Sunday in Paris.
   He said a truce could be signed there, but he added that he
thinks it will be impossible to get the Cambodian factions to agree
on it.
   Cambodian government leader Hun Sen and Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
chief of the three-party guerrilla coalition, in May agreed in
principle to a cease-fire. But the Khmer Rouge, the largest and
most hard-line guerrilla force, rejected a truce unless Vietnamese
forces first withdraw under international supervision.
   Another Radio Hanoi broadcast Thursday said Hun Sen stopped in
Hanoi the day before en route to the Paris talks and conferred with
Prime Minister Do Muoi and Thach.
   The radio said the two sides agreed that the basis for a
solution lay in what they said was the consensus reached at two
rounds of talks in Indonesia the past year _ the withdrawal of
Vietnamese troops and ``elimination'' of the Khmer Rouge.
   Sihanouk has demanded a government joining the Hun Sen
administration and all three guerrilla groups, but Hun Sen has
rejected Khmer Rouge participation because he says it would ignite
more war.
   Hun Sen apparently plans no major concessions. The official
Cambodian news agency SPK said he told a Australian official
visiting Phnom Penh Monday that he was prepared for more fighting
if need be.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
