<FIRST>r w AM-BirthControlBill     07-20 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Birth Control Bill,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Bill Would Fund Birth Control/Fertility Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congresswomen, saying they want to reclaim
the ``middle ground'' in the abortion debate, Thursday introduced a
bill to fund birth control and fertility research.
   Reps. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., and Olympia Snowe, R-Maine,
said they are trying to broaden the abortion-rights base and seize
control of the debate from abortion foes by attracting people from
both sides of the issue as well as the undecided.
   ``This is a comfort zone for people who don't want to line up
for or against abortion,'' Schroeder said.
   ``We're not going to sidetrack the debate on abortion,'' Snow
said, but the congresswomen want to broaden it to address the
conditions that lead to the need for abortion.
   The Supreme Court's ruling earlier this month giving the states
broader authority to limit women's rights to terminate their
pregnancies has thrown the abortion debate into the state
legislatures and governors' offices. Abortion-rights advocates and
opponents have been bracing to steer the issue in their states.
   ``We've got to start reclaiming that middle ground'' to broaden
the pro-choice base and reach out to people who may be
uncomfortable in either camp on abortion but who support the need
for better contraception, Schroeder said.
   With more than 3 million unintended pregnancies in the United
States each year, more attention has to be focused on preventing
pregnancies, they said. Additionally, one out of six U.S. couples
is infertile or cannot conceive within one year of deciding to have
a child, they said.
   ``Clearly, we need to encourage birth control and fertility
research,'' Schroeder said.
   Currently, the federal government is spending about $9 million
annually on contraceptive research, she said.
   The bill would fund three birth control research centers and two
fertility research centers that would do clinical research and
development as well as develop education programs and distribute
medical information.
   The centers would receive $20 million in fiscal year 1990, the
same amount in 1991, $12 million in fiscal 1992, $12.5 million in
fiscal 1993 and $13 million for fiscal 1994.
   The bill would also authorize a loan repayment program for
graduate students or health professionals who conduct birth control
or fertility research.
</TEXT>
