<FIRST>r a AM-PrivateRoad     07-20 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Private Road,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia Approves Private Toll Highway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's transportation board on Thursday
approved plans for a private toll highway that the builder said
would be the first in the country in 30 years.
   The Commonwealth Transportation Board voted unanimously to
approve the Toll Road Corp. of Virginia's proposal to build a
15-mile, $155 million extension of the Dulles Toll Road in
traffic-clogged northern Virginia.
   The vote came after intense negotiations between the state and
the corporation, which is headed by Ralph L. Stanley, former chief
of the federal Urban Mass Transportation Administration.
   ``We've got a lot to be proud of,'' said Byron E. Waldman,
northern Virginia's representative on the board. ``We're willing to
look at creative and new ways to meet our state's needs.''
   The company still must seek approval from the State Corporation
Commission, which will regulate the amount of tolls. The company
has said tolls would start at $1.50.
   Stanley said he hopes the SCC will act as soon as possible and
construction can begin by December. He said the highway should be
finished by the end of 1991, about 15 months ahead of when the
state could complete the project.
   ``We couldn't be more pleased, particularly with a unanimous
vote,'' Stanley said.
   ``I don't minimize the historic nature of it,'' he said. ``I
think it's a whole new era of funding for not just highway projects
but infrastructure through the state.''
   Bill Woodwell, a representative of the Toll Road Corp., said
land for the project is largely being donated by developers and
other landowners on the assumption the road will increase the value
of land near it. The company is still negotiating with some small
individual owners, and may have to buy some parcels.
   The land donations are one of the main reasons the company will
be able to build the road so much faster than the state, Woodwell
said.
   Stanley said the road would be the first private toll highway
built in the country in more than 30 years.
   ``There are, I would say, at least 30 states I know who are
going to be very interested in what happened here today,'' he said.
   The Virginia General Assembly passed legislation in 1988
allowing private companies to fund and build roads in the state.
   Stanley said he could foresee more private funding of roads,
bridges and wastewater treatment plants, particularly in small
communities.
   State transportation officials acknowledged that the private
company could build the road faster and at a lower initial cost,
but they said it would cost far more in the long run because the
company must pay higher interest rates than the state. That would
increase tolls, they said.
   Ray D. Pethtel, the board's commissioner, said the public's
overwhelming support for the private road outweighed such concerns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
