<FIRST>r a AM-RussianArrivals     07-20 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Russian Arrivals,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Russian Students' Arrival Surprises University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unexpected visit by a group of Soviet students
and professors sent University of Houston officials scrambling to
line up social and educational events.
   ``Yes, we are embarrassed. We certainly don't make a habit of
treating international visitors this way,'' said Willie Munson, the
university's student life director.
   The six members of the Soviet group from Leningrad State
University arrived Tuesday at Houston's Intercontinental Airport
eager to start their ``exchange program.'' But nobody expected them.
   After waiting a few hours at the airport, the group was picked
up by officials from the university's housing department.
   ``We are so pleased to have somebody meet us and feed us. The
people are very pleasant,'' said Elena Krasnova, 31, a teacher at
the Leningrad university.
   Ali Annan, a former students' association president in Houston,
had corresponded with Leningrad administrators for two years. In
May, he wrote a letter suggesting that the summer would be an ideal
time to visit.
   The Soviets received that letter last week, obtained their visas
and caught the first available plane. They also say they mailed a
letter to Annan telling them about their trip, but he has yet to
receive it.
   ``I was shocked,'' said Annan, a May graduate. ``The worst few
moments of my life were then. I ... asked myself if I could be
dreaming.''
   University officials said they are making the best of the
situation.
   ``They're a very nice group of people, very bright,'' interim
school President George Magner said. ``It's their first trip
outside of Russia. We intend to give them a very pleasant and
productive visit.''
   The impromptu plans for the Soviets include trips to the Johnson
Space Center, Astroworld and the port city of Galveston. The group
is scheduled to go sailing and spend time on a ranch, as well as
visit university laboratories and classes.
</TEXT>
