<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0724 07-20 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0724,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civilians Flee Beirut During Sectarian Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more casualties and quotes.
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christians and Syrians fought artillery
battles Thursday that rained 30 shells a minute on the city and
sent thousands of residents fleeing in panic. Police said 13 people
were killed and 88 wounded.
   ``Someone call the fire brigade! We want an ambulance too!'' a
woman screamed from the 11-story Kaaki building in west Beirut,
whose top three floors were burning.
   ``Telephone lines are down!'' a man answered from a nearby
building. ``Have faith in God! We're coming to help you!''
   Two 107mm rockets hit Fawzi Rida's apartment on the 10th floor
before dawn. ``I stretched a hand to open the door, but there was
no door,'' he said. ``We have nothing left but the night clothes we
are wearing.''
   Police said 433 people have been killed and 1,780 wounded in the
18 weeks of artillery warfare between Gen. Michel Aoun's Christian
army units and an alliance of Syrian soldiers and Moslem militias.
Thursday's shelling was some of the heaviest in the long battle.
   Tongues of flame shot into the sky over Beirut. Blasted
buildings burned out of control. A police spokesman said damage in
Moslem west Beirut was much worse than in the Christian eastern
sector.
   He reported a heavy flow of civilians from both sides of the
city toward safer areas in south Lebanon, the Bekaa valley in the
east and the mountains northeast of Beirut.
   ``Thousands of cars packed with families headed south from west
Beirut,'' the spokesman said.
   The evacuees used a lull in shelling at midday Thursday to leave
the city, ``carrying whatever personal effects and household items
they could save,'' he said.
   Associated Press photo editor Zouheir Saade said shells fell
near his fifth-floor apartment in west Beirut's seaside Raouche
district.
   ``Our building doesn't have a bomb shelter,'' he said. ``The
only precautionary measure I could take was to distribute my four
sons each in a different room. I thought that was the only possible
way to keep some of them alive in case the apartment was hit.''
   Firefighters were hampered because a power blackout caused a
water shortage. A source at the fire department said two fire
engines used sea water to extinguish some fires overnight.
   The police spokesman said several Syrian soldiers were killed
when Aoun's artillery pounded their bases and artillery
emplacements in west Beirut, but police said they had no precise
information because the Syrians do not report their losses to
Lebanese authorities.
   An estimated 40,000 Syrian soldiers are in Lebanon under an Arab
League peacekeeping mandate granted in 1976, a year after Lebanon's
sectarian civil war began. Aoun calls them an army of occupation
and has vowed to drive them out.
   The police spokesman said Samir Geagea's right-wing Lebanese
Forces, the main Christian militia, joined Christian army forces in
shelling west Beirut.
   ``Aoun's gunners targeted mainly Syrian positions,'' he said.
``Geagea's men rocketed residential areas in west Beirut.''
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads a Moslem government
vying for power with the Aoun's Christian Cabinet, pleaded with
leaders of Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria to speed up Arab
League efforts for a cease-fire.
   A spokesman for Aoun's command claimed the Syrians started the
battle by shelling the Christian-held coast north of Beirut to
prevent three ships loaded with food from landing. The Syrians
bombard the coast regularly to keep supply ships away from
Christian ports.
</TEXT>
