<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2220EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Wolves     07-20 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wolves,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parks Chief Opposes Wolf Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of the National Park Service said
Thursday he opposes legislation being considered by the House that
would speed the return of wolves to the Yellowstone Park area.
   James Ridenour, newly appointed parks director, called a bill
introduced by Rep. Wayne Owens, D-Utah, ``clearly premature.''
   Sponsors believe the administration is moving too slowly to
restore the only indigenous species still missing from the
Yellowstone area.
   But the measure has other members growling.
   Rep. Ron Marlenee, R-Mont., called the bill ``blatantly
anti-sportsman'' because wolves kill elk sought by hunters.
   ``This is a meddlesome bill ... an effort to extend the borders
of Yellowstone,'' Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, told fellow members of
the national parks subcommittee of the House Interior Committee.
   Young called wolf proponents ``romantic'' and said they should
see the wolf for what it is, ``without any doubt, second to man in
his ability as a predator against the clove-footed animal.''
   Rep. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, said livestock owners will kill the
wolves in defense of their animals ``and I would support that.''
   Ridenour said the park service goal is to return the area to its
natural state as far as possible. He said the Interior Department,
of which the park service is a part, is conducting studies to
determine:
   _If the wolf population can be controlled once it is returned.
   _The effects of the wolves on prey within the park and big game
hunting outside it.
   _The effect on grizzly bears.
   He said the studies would probably be finished by early in the
next fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1, and no environmental impact
statement should be prepared before then.
   Owens' bill calls for an environmental impact statement and
action by the interior secretary after the statement is complete.
   Ridenour said the wording of the bill would make it difficult
for the secretary to make any decision other than returning the
wolves to the park.
   Ridenour urged the subcommittee chairman, Rep. Bruce Vento,
D-Minn., to ``let the scientists do their studies; let the wildlife
advocates, ranchers, park visitors, state and local officials, and
members of Congress comment on the findings; and then let us make a
policy which is driven by our stewardship responsibility.''
   Vento asked, ``Can you give me assurances that there will be no
attempt to short circuit'' the process? He said the administration
already has delayed planned re-introduction of wolves by two years.
   Ridenour said he was trying to avoid a ``headlong rush'' and
said he had an open mind on the subject.
   Dr. David Mech, a world-renowned wolf expert with the Fish and
Wildlife Service, told the subcommittee each wolf eats the
equivalent of three adult elk cows a year, which should not
endanger the population of about 35,000 elk in the Yellowstone area.
   Mech said the elk that died last year of bad weather would have
been the likely prey of wolves.
   If 10 breeding pairs of wolves were established in Yellowstone,
about 500 could be living there by the turn of the century. He said
enough prey, including animals other than elk, exists in the region
to support the wolves without disrupting the ecosystem.
   While admitting that wolves sometimes venture out of the forest
to prey on domestic livestock, he said it was unusual.
</TEXT>
