<FIRST>r w AM-USSIowa-Report 345   07-20 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USS Iowa-Report, 345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Report On Iowa Blast Could Take Weeks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hartwig Letters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy's report on its investigation into
the explosion aboard the battleship Iowa is expected to take
several more weeks to complete, Navy sources said Thursday.
   A board of inquiry has drafted a report into the April 19
incident, which killed 47 sailors.
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said the report is in Norfolk,
Va., on the desk of Vice Adm. Joseph S. Donnell III, the commander
of the Naval Surface Forces.
   He disputed a report that discord within the Navy has held it
up, and that the service is having difficulty finding senior
officers to sign it.
   ``I wouldn't describe it as hung up. It's under review,''
Williams said.
   The spokesman said the report must go up the chain of command
for review, and that it will next be seen by the commander in chief
of the Atlantic fleet, Adm. Powell F. Carter Jr., in Norfolk.
   Adm. Carlisle A. H. Trost, the chief of Naval Operations will
see the report before passing it to the Secretary of the Navy H.
Lawrence Garrett, who will then refer it to Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney, Williams said.
   ``The senior officer, and only the senior officer, at each of
those eschelons of command in the review process will sign the
forwarding endorsement,'' Williams said.
   The spokesman added that at each point, the signatore has the
option of forwarding the report without comment, sending the report
back to the investigating officer for additional work, or
forwarding it ``as is'' and express his disagreement with some or
all of the material.
   ``I'm not implying that anyone has done any of those things
yet,'' Williams said.
   A Navy source, who spoke on condition he not be identified, said
it is expected that each level of command will take about a week to
go over the report.
   ``It won't get here before August,'' said the source.
</TEXT>
