<FIRST>r w AM-Aspin-Stealth 2ndLdWritethru a0708 07-20 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aspin-Stealth, 2nd Ld Writethru, a0708,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aspin Wants ``Cold Turkey'' Freeze on Funds for Stealth</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs:Updates with 12 new grafs to add Bush lobbying effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Armed Services Committee Chairman Les
Aspin, said Thursday he wants a ``cold turkey'' freeze on funds for
the stealth bomber, and President Bush stepped up his lobbying
effort for the radar-evading plane and other defense systems.
   Aspin, D-Wis., said Congress needs more information on the
costly stealth bomber, as the B-2 plane is known.
   ``The problem this year is ... we don't really know what we
got,'' he told reporters.
   Aspin said he wants to give opponents of the plane, at $530
million a copy the most expensive aircraft ever produced, a chance
to kill the program. But if Congress doesn't want to do that, it
needs more information about the program before moving forward, he
added.
   Bush on Thursday called Aspin and other members of the House
Armed Services and Appropriations committees to the White House. He
pressed them to back his budget proposals for the B-2, as well as
the strategic defense initiative, the MX missile and the Midgetman
missile.
   The House and Senate are scheduled to vote next week on those
programs and a package of Pentagon cuts the administration proposed
to meet the $10 billion reduction agreed on by Congressional
negotiators and the White House for the 1990 defense authorization
bills.
   Bush told the group he is fully committed to that package and
the weapons systems as essential to the nation's deterrent
capability and to the U.S. strategy at the arms reduction talks
ongoing in Geneva, according to Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   Given the amount of congressional hesitation, especially
regarding the administration's insistence on not cutting the B-2
program, Bush wanted to re-emphasize his policy reasons for those
programs, Fitzwater said.
   Bush was to host another meeting Friday to lobby those committee
members who could not make the Thursday session.
   Bush is emphatic that the plane ``represents the future of
bomber aviation,'' and is needed despite its expense, the spokesman
said.
   Aspin told reporters after the meeting that he could not predict
which way Congress would go on the Pentagon spending bill next week.
   At the Pentagon, a spokesman for Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
said Aspin's B-2 plan would not meet with his approval. ``Any delay
in the program will only make it more expensive,'' said Pete
Williams. ``He'd be opposed to such a scenario.''
   Cheney reiterated the importance of the B-2 bomber in a meeting
with House Republicans, who are divided on the issue.
   Supporters of the plane were cheered when it made its first test
flight Monday.
   The Pentagon hopes to buy 132 planes at a cost of about $70
billion.
   In fiscal 1990, the Defense Department has proposed spending
$4.7 billion for the B-2, but last month the House armed services
panel cut $800 million from the budget.
   Money for the plane is expected to be the most controversial
item next week when the House and Senate consider the Pentagon
budget bill.
   Reps. Ron Dellums, D-Calif., John Kasich, R-Ohio, and John
Rowland, R-Conn., have proposed stopping production after the 13
planes now in the pipeline are completed.
   If their effort fails, Aspin said, he intends to propose funding
production of only two bombers in 1990 and 1991, when the
administration wants eight bombers. His amendment would meet the
full request for research and development work over that period.
   ``I say, give the opponents of the B-2 an up-or-down vote. If
the Congress is willing to step up to this issue this year, I say
let's do it,'' Aspin said.
   He called his amendment ``a cold turkey fence of the procurement
money until Congress acts again.''
   Aspin said his plan ``shuts down the program, but it gives the
administration a chance to come up with another program that's
politically more acceptable _ financially.''
   He said he could not predict how his colleagues will vote on the
issue because there has never been a public debate on the
once-secret program.
   Aspin added he wants the Air Force to ``come up with a cheaper
program'' by seeking fewer planes. ``I don't know anybody who
thinks they're going to get 132 planes,'' Aspin said.
</TEXT>
