<FIRST>u w AM-Woerner-Panama     07-20 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Woerner-Panama,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Announces Woerner Retirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of the U.S. military's Southern
Command, Gen. Frederick F. Woerner, is retiring, Pentagon officials
said Thursday. Sources said the outspoken officer was forced out by
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
   Woerner has been critical of Bush administration policy in
Panama and has clashed in the past with the Pentagon and State
Department over policy in the region.
   In a speech earlier this year to a Panama City group, the
general criticized what he called an ``absence'' of United States
policy toward Panama.
   Woerner has served as the commander in chief of the Panama-based
U.S. forces since June 1987. He will retire after 34 years of
service on Oct. 1, and will be replaced by Gen. Maxwell R. Thurman,
the Pentagon said in a statement.
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams, who released a letter from
Cheney praising Woerner for his ``dedicated service,'' denied that
the change in command had anything to do with the political
situation in Panama.
   One Defense Department source familiar with the situation said
Woerner was forced into retirement.
   ``He was canned,'' said the official, who spoke on condition he
not be identified by name. Another government official made a
similar comment, saying Woerner was being forced out because of
unhappiness with his outspokenness.
   Over the past months, Woerner's troops have been the object of
harassment and intimidation at the hands of Panama's Defense Forces.
   This follows a U.S. campaign begun under the Reagan
administration to oust Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, who has remained in power despite the administration's
attempt to remove him following an indictment on drug trafficking
charges in Florida.
   Williams noted that Thurman, who had put in for retirement
himself, was asked to stay on and accept the command.
   The spokesman said Cheney has known Thurman, who is presently
assigned to the U.S. Army Training and Doctrine Command in Fort
Monroe, Va., for years and ``has great confidence'' in him.
</TEXT>
