<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2223EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma-SuuKyi     07-20 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-Suu Kyi,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Burmese Opposition Leader Emerged Less Than a Year Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aung San Suu Kyi, who was placed under
house arrest by Burmese military authorities Thursday, appeared on
the political stage less than a year ago to become Burma's leading
voice for democracy.
   The daughter of Burma's assassinated independence hero, Aung
San, she returned to Rangoon, Burma's capital, from her home in
Britain in April 1988 to care for her ailing mother. She found
herself in the midst of an unprecedented nationwide campaign to end
authoritarianism.
   She sided with student protesters and stayed with them after the
September military coup in which troops of Army Commander Gen. Saw
Maung crushed dissent by killing hundreds of people.
   Her campaign rallies commonly draw thousands of people, and
Western diplomats say authorities are concerned she could win a
general election scheduled for early next year.
   The slight frame of Ms. Suu Kyi, 44, belies a steely political
will that brushes off military intimidation and veiled threats
against her life. She had no political experience before last year.
   Many Burmese attribute her widespread support to her
unprecedented denunciation of the military and strongman Ne Win,
whom she charges is still pulling the strings although he
officially retired last year after 26 years of autocratic rule.
   Her first appearance on the Burmese political scene was on Aug.
15 last year, when she attempted to mediate between the protesting
students and the army by writing an open letter to then President
Maung Maung.
   But when she spoke outside Rangoon's glittering Shwedagon Pagoda
on Aug. 26, the height of the pro-democracy movement, she drew what
may have been the largest crowd ever seen in Rangoon.
   An estimated 1 million people packed the streets to hear her
call for democracy and an end to one-party rule. Demonstrators
camped in the streets for days to see her.
   After brutal clampdowns on dissent that killed thousands, the
army crushed open street protest after Sept 18. Ms. Suu Kyi
subsequenty emerged as the most prominent of the Burmese opposition
leaders.
   Her popularity has increased steadily and she has drawn large
crowds during political campaign tours throughout the country this
year.
   In December, crowds filled the streets of Rangoon for the
funeral of her mother, Kyin Gyi, who was Burma's first female
ambassador.
   Her party, the National League for Democracy, is the largest
political opposition group and claims over 700,000 members in
Rangoon alone.
   Over the past month she has openly defied martial law
regulations, which forbid open air political rallies and gatherings
of more than five persons. Her speeches in Rangoon have drawn
crowds of up to 15,000 despite the persistent presence of armed
troops.
   Suu Kyi was born in Rangoon in 1945 and married British academic
Michael Aris in 1972. Her two sons traveled recently to Rangoon.
   She went to school in India where her mother was Burma's first
female ambassador. She won a scholarship to Oxford in 1967 and
obtained an honors degree in politics, philosophy and economics.
   She later worked at the United Nations in New York and in the
early 1980s researched the life of her father and the origins of
Burmese nationalism at Kyodo University in Japan.
   She has written two books, a guide to Burma for children and a
short biography of her father.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Floods     07-20 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Floods,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Dies in Flash Flood; Three Float Away in Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARRENTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A creek swelled by a surprise storm rose
13 feet in a half-hour Thursday, washing about 10 vehicles off a
bridge and killing a pregnant woman, authorities said.
   Divers battled the raging current of Goose Creek to search for
up to three people seen floating by in a car, but three others were
rescued from the creek, said Lt. David Flohr of the Fauquier County
Sheriff's Department.
   Eight other people managed to escape the fast-moving water on
their own after their vehicles were swept away, said Flohr.
   More than 100 military personnel and rescue workers searched for
the three people seen in the floating car, Flohr said. But rain
started to fall again and the search was suspended after 5 p.m.,
said Sgt. Butler Grant of the sheriff's department.
   The search was concentrated along a one-mile area downstream of
the bridge on U.S. 17. Water from the creek covered the bridge and
carried the vehicles off shortly after midnight.
   Flohr identified the dead woman as Tammy Woolf Conneway of
Bloommerry, W.Va., who was alone in a pickup truck that was washed
into the creek. Her age was not immediately available.
   The creek, which normally runs about 10 feet below the bridge,
rose an estimated 13 feet within a half-hour, said Chuck Thompson,
director of county emergency services.
   He said many drivers tried to cross the bridge despite the high
water. ``It's the age-old story: people forget about the tremendous
force of running water,'' he said.
   The storm caught everyone by surprise, said Thompson. ``We had
no warning whatsoever. There was nothing from the National Weather
Service.
   Up to 3.8 inches of rain fell in nearby Linden Wednesday night,
the National Weather Service said.
   Thompson said the creek receded as quickly as it rose.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
