<FIRST>u i AM-Cyprus 1stLd-Writethru a0733 07-20 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0733,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Cypriot Women Claim Victory, End Sit-in at Green Line</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with protest over, women leaving; picks up
10th `Turkey's Anatolia'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 Greek Cypriot women declared
victory Thursday and left a stretch of the island's ethnic dividing
line after two days of protesting the 15-year-old Turkish
occupation of northern Cyprus.
   The protest had threatened to wreck 11 months of U.N.-sponsored
negotiations on reuniting the eastern Mediterranean island.
   ``We have achieved our purpose of emphasizing the Greek
Cypriots' right of return'' to their homes in the north, said
Athena Violari, one of the organizers. ``This is not the right
place to continue our action for the release of those detained.''
   On Wednesday night, Turkish Cypriot riot police backed by
Turkish soldiers entered St. George's church in the buffer zone
Wednesday night and arrested 100 women and 11 men, including Greek
Orthodox Bishop Chrysostomos of Kition.
   At midnight Thursday, the demonstrators walked backward out of a
narrow alley that marks the line between the Greek and Turkish
communities, singing the Greek national anthem.
   They said they would march on Friday to the home of U.N. special
representative Oscar Camilion and seek his help in freeing the
detainees.
   Many residents of northern Cyprus fled when Turkey invaded on
July 20, 1974, after a short-lived coup against the late President
Makarios.
   The protesters entered the buffer zone by breaking through U.N.
checkpoints.
   After the violence at the church, they withdrew to the nearby
alley and held an all-night vigil, singing hymns and Greek songs
and shouting anti-Turkish slogans.
   Turkey's Anatolia news agency said 108 protesters appeared in
court in the Turkish sector Thursday and were ordered jailed for
two days pending trial proceedings. It was not known what charges
they face.
   The agency said three foreign reporters seized by riot police
had been released. They were Katherine McElroy and Steve Weizman,
both of the British Reuters news agency, and Dutch radio reporter
Hetty Lubberding.
   Ms. McElroy said she and Weizman were injured during Wednesday's
clash.
   ``I wasn't treated well .... I was kicked and beaten,'' Ms.
McElroy, a dual Cypriot-American national, said after her release.
   After he was freed, Weizman was treated for a bayonet wound in
the leg, Ms. McElroy said.
   In a speech marking the anniversary of the Turkish invasion,
President George Vassiliou, the Greek Cypriot leader, pledged
support for the protesters ``who were attacked brutally while they
were praying without provoking anyone.''
   ``We demand the immediate release of those arrested and the
withdrawal of Turkish troops from the buffer zone,'' he told
several thousand Greek Cypriots in central Eleftheria Square.
   Vassiliou said all refugees must be allowed to go home and the
island must be reunified.
   He earlier protested to the U.N. Security Council over the
Turkish move into the buffer zone.
   The women's protest was part of a series of anniversary
demonstrations to protest the Turkish invasion of the island's
northern third.
   Turkish troops moved in after an Athens-inspired coup by
supporters of union with Greece. The Turks said they came to
protect the 120,000-member Turkish Cypriot minority, which forms 17
percent of the island's population.
   The mounting tension threatened reunification talks between
Vassiliou and Rauf Denktash, leader of the Turkish Cypriots.
   The official Turkish Cypriot Radio Bayrak said that sector's
government would meet later Thursday to decide if Denktash should
attend the next round of talks set for July 26.
   Turkish Cypriots attended rallies and held a military parade
Thursday to celebrate the anniversary of the Turkish invasion.
</TEXT>
