<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Lucas 2ndLd-Writethru a0794-a0799 07-20 0933</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0794-a0799,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conyers Withdraws Support of Lucas for Rights Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: UPDATES with Biden opposition in lede and INSERTS grafs 7-11
bgng: ``The committee,'' on Biden. ^By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The congressman who introduced William Lucas
at a Senate hearing on Lucas' nomination to be the government's
chief civil rights enforcer abruptly took back his support Thursday
and the chairman of the committee in charge said he might vote
against Lucas.
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., returning to the Senate Judiciary
Committee hearing room where he had strongly urged Lucas'
confirmation a day earlier, said, ``It is with a slightly heavy
heart I come to withdraw my endorsement of Bill Lucas.''
   Conyers said he made the decision after being ``frankly
astounded'' when Lucas told the panel that a series of recent
Supreme Court decisions on civil rights did not undermine
enforcement of anti-discrimination laws.
   ``We are in a crisis in the civil rights movement,'' said
Conyers, who, like Lucas, is black.
   ``If you can't figure out these cases are seriously cutting back
very modest progress that we made, then there is no point waiting
for you to become the assistant attorney general of the civil
rights division for me to argue it with you then,'' Conyers said.
   He stopped short of urging the panel to reject the nomination,
suggesting the committee should give Lucas the benefit of the doubt
and perhaps a chance for on-the-job training.
   The committee chairman, Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., said at the
hearing, ``I was inclined to vote for him until yesterday.''
   But now, ``I'm inclined to vote against him.''
   ``My doubt about this man doesn't relate to his lack of
experience,'' Biden said.
   He expressed concern about ``whether you're going to have
somebody as assistant attorney general for civil rights who is
going to fight for civil rights.'' He testimony from Lucas on
Wednesday failed to satisfy him.
   ``When I asked him whether we were moving in the right direction
or the wrong way on civil rights he didn't have an opinion,'' Biden
said.
   On Wednesday, Conyers had predicted that ``Bill Lucas will go on
to greatness'' as assistant attorney general for civil rights. ``If
he doesn't,'' Conyers added, ``I will be the first one calling for
his head on a pike.''
   Reacting to Conyers' withdrawal of support, Sen. Paul Simon,
D-Ill., who has been serving as chairman of the hearings, said that
``it obviously hurts the Lucas candidacy _ how much, I can't
quantify.''
   ``In all my 15 years on Capitol Hill, I've never seen anything
like it,'' Simon said. He said the vote on the committee ``is
close.''
   ``It may hurt him some,'' Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., ranking
Republican on the Judiciary Committee, said of Conyers' new stand.
``But I hope that it won't mean much.''
   ``He did say that he believed that the nominee is committed to
civil rights,'' Thurmond said.
   Civil rights groups contend that Lucas, 61, a Republican who
served as sheriff and later chief executive of Wayne County, Mich.,
lacks professional qualifications for the Justice Department job.
   Such criticism has been echoed by some members of the Senate
panel. Lucas has never tried a court case and has practiced law
only since he left public office in 1986.
   Conyers' spirited speech in support of the Lucas nomination was
repeatedly commended to the attention of reporters Wednesday by
supporters while Lucas was being grilled by senators about
questions relating to his honesty and character.
   Conyers had agreed to introduce Lucas after the state's
Democratic senators, Carl Levin and Donald Riegle Jr., broke with
Senate custom and declined to accompany Lucas to the committee
hearing. The senators said they were withholding judgment on the
nomination.
   In his testimony Thursday, Conyers said he was disturbed to
learn that Lucas had told the committee that ``he could live with
these cases.''
   ``I cannot live with these cases,'' Conyers said of the recent
high court decisions that civil rights lawyers say will make it
harder to win discrimination suits in court.
   ``We've got some problems,'' Conyers said. ``We're not going to
wait to get them cleared up. They are going to get cleared up with
me and Lucas today or they are not going to get cleared up at all.''
   Lucas, adhering closely to the Bush administration's policy,
said on Wednesday that he did not regard the decisions as hurting
civil rights enforcement.
   He promised, like Attorney General Dick Thornburgh had already
done, to closely monitor the impact of the decisions on court cases
to determine if legislation is needed to overturn the rulings.
   Conyers telephoned Lucas Thursday morning to say that he thought
Lucas' position on the Supreme Court decisions ``was diametrically
opposed to his own,'' said Julian Epstein, a spokesman for Conyers.
   Lucas' testimony had ``put him in a very difficult position,''
Epstein said of Conyers, who is supporting legislation being
drafted in the House to overturn the effect of several high court
rulings.
   Epstein said Conyers and Lucas had discussed the nominee's views
on civil rights over the past two or three months. ``Mr. Conyers
was led to believe the positions were very much closer than that,''
Epstein said.
   David Runkel, a spokesman for Attorney General Thornburgh,
discounted the significance of Conyers' withdrawal of support,
saying, ``I still expect Mr. Lucas to be confirmed by the Senate.''
   Of Conyers' criticism, Runkel said, ``It is unrealistic for
anybody to expect the nominee of the president for this position
would go before a congressional committee and disown a position
taken by the president and by the attorney general.''
</TEXT>
