<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2231EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Senegal-Mauritania     07-20 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Senegal-Mauritania,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senegal Says Mauritania Expelled 26,000 Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senegal Thursday accused Mauritania of
deporting 26,000 of its black nationals following racial violence
that left between 250 and 400 dead in the two countries.
   ``It is to be feared that not a single black Mauritanian will be
unaffected by the measures,'' Senegal's acting foreign minister
said in letter to the U.N. security council.
   Kane Kharass, from Mauritania's U.N. mission said, ``There is no
such policy in my country.''
   Tensions between the black Senegalese and the fairer-skinned,
Arab and Berber Mauritanians have long historical and racial roots,
but a confrontation in April and May began as a minor border
incident. Tens of thousands of Mauritanians and Senegalese were
repatriated in a U.N.-sponsored airlift.
   To reduce tensions, both nations sent home workers from the
other country after the violent clashes, which left between 250 and
400 people dead, Kharass said. He denied Mauritania was expelling
any of its own citizens.
   But Medoune Fall, Senegal's acting foreign minister, said,
``Beginning in mid-May, the Mauritanian government took steps to
expel its black nationals belonging to ethnic groups also found in
Senegal.
   ``In just a few weeks, the operation has affected 26,000
individuals, who have been driven from their own country solely by
reason of their ethnic origin,'' Fall said.
   Those deported to Senegal were arriving completely stripped of
property, he said. Between July 16 and 18 alone, 2,000 blacks were
deported, Fall said.
   Fall said the deportations would increase tensions between the
two countries.
   Mauritania was the last nation in the world to officially
abolish slavery, in 1980. Most slaves were black, while the traders
and owners were usually Arabs or Berbers.
   Hard economic times have worsened ethnic tensions between the
two nations as hundreds of thousands of people have crossed the
border seeking work in the other country.
   Senegal estimates that up to 50,000 Senegalese, mainly seasonal
workers, lived in Mauritania before the latest clashes broke out.
About 500,000 Mauritanians, most of them tradesmen, live in Senegal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
