<DOCNO> AP890720-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DroughtRelief     07-20 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Relief,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Deadlocked On Drought Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Agriculture Committee failed to
reach agreement Thursday on a Democratic plan to provide $1 billion
in relief for farmers who are losing crops to this summer's drought
and flooding.
   Committee Chairman Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., postponed a vote on the
package until next week after Republican senators argued the
measure covers too many crops and costs too much.
   Leahy said he did not want to risk a vote on the Senate floor
without bipartisan support.
   ``Drought and disaster isn't a partisan issue and relief
shouldn't be either,'' Leahy said.
   The Bush administration has threatened to veto a drought-relief
bill passed by the House last month that is estimated to cost $1.3
billion and cover more than 500 crops, from corn to cherries.
   Senate Democrats, agreeing the House measure is too expensive,
proposed to scale it back by $300 million by reducing the payments
to farmers and tightening qualifications for the program.
   The administration wants to limit the bill to $870 million, but
Democrats say the government can afford an additional $200 million,
if some of the payments to farmers come from this year's budget
instead of next year's.
   The deep division within the committee became evident earlier in
the day when the panel voted 10-9 along party lines to kill an $800
million Republican proposal that would have targeted a greater
share of the drought assistance to crops that are in the
government's price support program _ wheat, corn, rice and cotton.
   ``Where money is limited we must set priorities,'' said Indiana
Sen. Richard Lugar, the committee's ranking Republican.
   Sen. Thad Cochran, a Mississippi Republican whose state's rice
and cotton crops have been devastated by flooding, said the
Democratic plan would spread the aid so thin ``there's going to be
precious little benefit to anybody.''
   Senate Republican Leader Robert Dole of Kansas, where the winter
wheat crop was cut back sharply by drought, said the GOP plan would
mean an extra 15 cents a bushel for wheat and an additional 21
cents a bushel for corn.
   Dole argues that winter-wheat farmers should get first crack at
drought relief since much of the savings in the farm program that
is being used to pay for drought relief is the result of a smaller
wheat crop.
   ``Where does the money come from? It comes from program crops,''
Dole said. ``If we're going to cover non-program crops, we should
find the money elsewhere.''
   The Republican plan would have provided relief to wheat, corn,
rice and cotton on the same basis as the House bill and the 1988
drought legislation; other crops could have received assistance if
the money was available in the federal budget.
   Dole acknowledged for the first time today that losses have
occurred in at least one other crop _ namely spring wheat in North
Dakota, where drought-related crop losses already are estimated at
$660 million.
   Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., who is concerned about getting relief
for sunflowers and other non-program crops in his state, said the
Democratic proposal was modest and more fair. ``Nobody's going to
get a windfall out of this,'' he said.
   ``An act of God,'' said Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., ``doesn't
distinguish between program and non-program crops.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
