<FIRST>u w AM-AssaultWeapons     07-20 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Assault Weapons,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Assault Weapons Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee, going against
heavy pressure from gun owners' organizations, Thursday narrowly
approved a three-year ban on sales of nine military-style assault
weapons.
   ``It's designed to deny drug dealers the use of these types of
weapons,'' said Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., following 7-6
approval at a hectic session ending with a gun lobbyist complaining
about a senator's decision not to vote.
   The measure would ban nine varieties of semiautomatic assault
weapons, five already covered by the Bush administration's import
ban and four others produced domestically.
   The bill also would provide for up to 10 years of additional
prison time for those convicted of crimes involving firearms. The
measure would automatically go off the books in three years under a
``sunset'' provision.
   Critics of the measure called it too restrictive, although it
was modest in comparison with a flurry of bills that went into the
hopper in February following a mass slaying in a California
schoolyard with a semi-automatic assault rifle.
   ``I think it does a great deal of damage to the right of the
people to keep and bear arms,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, told the
committee. Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said the bill headed
in the right direction but should be stronger in banning assault
weapons.
   ``Frankly it is a letdown to the law enforcement groups in
America,'' Metzenbaum said.
   At the start of the meeting, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., told the
committee he would not be able to attend because he was tied down
with evidence hearings in the impeachment trial of U.S. District
Judge Alcee L. Hastings of Miami, accused of plotting to obtain a
$150,000 bribe. He then left.
   When it came time to vote an hour later, however, there was a
question as to whether the committee should wait for Specter. The
Hastings hearing was taking place in a room about a three-minute
walk away.
   ``The problem is he's on the Hastings matter and I know he takes
that very, very seriously,'' Hatch said.
   Because of the razor-thin margin, senators held open the roll
call for 10 minutes or more in case Specter might want to vote. A
minute after the vote was announced, the Pennsylvania senator
arrived but told Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph Biden, D-Del.,
he would need time to study any changes made in the legislation.
   Biden banged the gavel and adjourned the meeting. The chairman
and Specter were both quickly out the door, but Sen. Charles
Grassley, R-Iowa, told reporters that ``as a matter of courtesy
they could have given him five or six minutes to study the bill.''
   National Rifle Association lobbyist Wayne LaPierre, however,
told reporters he had been with Specter ``at the Hastings hearing,
in the back of the room,'' urging him to come to the Judiciary
Committee meeting to vote against DeConcini's bill.
   ``Basically,'' LaPierre said, ``Specter just decided to be
absent.''
   The lobbyist said he still expected the Pennsylvania senator to
be on the side of gunowner groups when the measure comes to the
floor.
   Earlier, Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., and Republican followers
sought to substitute the Bush administration's omnibus crime
control bill for the gun measure, but that effort failed 8-5.
   Thurmond warned that strong anticrime measures are needed and
cited the case of a South Carolina man convicted of murder a decade
ago. ``He hasn't been electrocuted yet,'' Thurmond said. ``People
are are losing respect for criminal justice procedures.''
   Biden said crime-control measures are needed but not before
President Bush implements broad powers granted him in last year's
drug bill. He said the administration has been authorized to hire
225 new FBI agents but has not done so.
   ``I don't doubt the president's sincerity,'' Biden said. ``I
just don't think he's tough enough.''
</TEXT>
