<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-20 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widespread Thunderstorms Dump Heavy Rain, Cause Flash Flood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms dumped locally heavy rain Thursday over parts of
Michigan and the central East Coast, causing flash flooding blamed
for at least one death.
   Overnight and morning rainfall in the East included 3.80 inches
at Linden, Va.; 3.90 inches at Flint Hill, Va.; 2.10 inches at
Cacapon State Park, W.Va.; and 2.11 inches at Wilmington, Del.
   Near Warrenton, Va., a creek swollen by the surprise rain rose
13 feet in a half-hour Thursday, washing about 10 vehicles off a
bridge and killing a pregnant woman, Fauquier County authorities
said.
   Southeastern Lower Michigan also had locally heavy rain. Total
rainfall from early Wednesday until noon Thursday included 2.14
inches at Livonia, 2.56 inches at Mount Clemens and 2.66 inches at
Detroit.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended from southern Maine to
Maryland, from southern and western New York state to Pennsylvania,
New Jersey, Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, the southeastern third of
Missouri, eastern Arkansas and from the North Carolina coast to
western North Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia, Florida, southern
Alabama, southern Mississippi and southern Louisiana.
   During the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 2.12 inches of rain fell at
Toledo, Ohio, with 1.86 inches at Wrightstown, N.J.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered over Idaho and western
Montana, as well as southwestern Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 61
degrees at San Simeon, Calif., to 109 at Needles and Palm Springs,
Calif. Thursday's low for the Lower 48 states was 42 at Gunnison,
Colo.
   Friday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern New England to southern Florida, Alabama, Mississippi and
Louisiana, and from southern Illinois to the southeastern
two-thirds of Missouri; and scattered showers and thunderstorms
over the Rockies and eastern section of the Great Basin, covering
Nevada and western Utah.
   High temperatures in the upper 60s and 70s were predicted along
the northern Pacific Coast; in the 70s from much of Missouri to
Illinois, Wisconsin and lower Michigan; in the upper 70s and the
80s from New England to New Jersey, the rest of the Great Lakes,
the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley, the remainder of the
Mississippi Valley, from South Dakota to northern Texas and along
much of the southern three-fourths of the Pacific Coast; around 100
degrees or above over the interior of central and Southern
California; near 115 degrees through the desert Southwest; and in
the 90s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
