<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2253EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SSCFunds     07-20 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SSC Funds,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Votes For $225 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate Appropriations subcommittee voted
Thursday to spend $225 million to begin construction of the ``super
collider'' particle accelerator.
   The chairman called the collider project the most important
scientific effort in the nation.
   But the chairman, Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., said an
amendment may be introduced in the full Appropriations Committee
that would hold up the $4.4 billion project until foreign
governments agree to participate.
   Johnston, head of the Appropriations Committee's energy and
water development subcommittee and also of the Senate Energy and
Natural Resources Committee, said he would oppose such a condition.
   ``There's sentiment in our committee to adopt report language
which will, in effect, say don't give away the great technological
contracts to the Japanese or to any other participant,'' Johnston
said.
   Committee reports are not binding, but the reports are very
influential in guiding administration decisions.
   Explaining his support of the collider, planned for a site 30
miles south of Dallas, Johnston said, ``It unlocks the secret of
what we're made of, what the universe is made of, what energy and
matter and all of the basic stuff of the universe is made of and
it's exciting.''
   He said he has ``limited enthusiasm'' for enlisting other
countries to share the cost: ``I think this research is so
important we ought to do it in this country if we can and not farm
it out to have somebody else build the most important technological
parts of it.''
   While President Bush had sought $250 million for the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1, Johnston said budget constraints forced him to
settle on $225 million. The House has voted $200 million, and if
the project survives, the two Houses will have to agree on an
amount.
</TEXT>
