<FIRST>u a AM-DC-10Crash-Mood 1stLd-Writethru a0717 07-20 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash-Mood, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0717,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Pitches In To Help Crash Survivors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf to CORRECT name of institution to Marian Health
Center, sted Marian Medical Center.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-DC-10 Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By J.L. SCHMIDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Missouri River city demonstrated
its big heart and big shoulders Thursday as it pitched in to help
survivors of United Flight 232.
   ``I don't think anyone slept very much. There was a lot of food.
Telephone lines were set up for people to call relatives,'' said
social worker Judy Wiskus. ``There was no hysteria. Everyone was
very calm.''
   Grief was tinged with determination as volunteers poured into
this town of 82,000 that sits on the east bank of a giant bend in
the Missouri River.
   ``It's just an overwhelming sense of disbelief, an overwhelming
sense of grief for the people,'' said Marian Health Center
President Doug Johnson.
   Johnson marveled at the unity of the city, a beef, pork and
grain processing center. Dr. David Greco, head of emergency
medicine at Marian Health Center, said there were two doctors to
every injured passenger at times Wednesday night when injured were
being brought to the hospital a dozen at a time.
   ``It's united most of the time but boy, during a crisis, it's
really united, '' Johnson said.
   Vacationing, off-duty and former employees of the city's two
hospitals pitched in to deal with the emergency.
   ``Our chief of staff chartered an airplane and flew home from
vacation in Minnesota,'' said St. Luke's Medical Center spokeswoman
Sue Conner.
   ``We had offers of help from doctors and nurses at hospitals in
three states,'' she said. ``Several hospital burn units also
offered to send nurses or treat our patients.''
   Rick Griencewic, a spokesman for Briar Cliff College where many
survivors spent the night, said a lot of local businesses and
residents donated food, clothing and toiletries.
   ``Everybody's bending over backwards to help these people. The
community is really coming together to help these people,''
Griencewic said.
   Marian Health Center Vice President Andrew Allen said supplies
arrived from hospitals in Sioux Falls, S.D., and Omaha, Neb.
   ``We probably got five months of inventory inside of three
hours,'' Allen said.
   Psychology students from the University of South Dakota in
nearby Vermillion came to the hospital to help with counseling,
said Cesar Narvaez, a social services worker at St. Luke's.
   Students at Briar Cliff College ``acted just like family'' for
the travelers who were treated, released and spent the night at the
Sioux City school, Wiskus said.
   After people were treated for physical injuries, ``we turned to
their emotions. We encouraged them to talk, to just be as open and
as candid as possible about their feelings,'' Narvaez said.
   Feelings ranged from guilt to anger.
   ```So why me?' The guilt, there are different stages,'' Narvaez
said. ``Sometimes the feelings won't come out until they see
friends or relatives or get to their destination.''
   At the Hair Affair Beauty Salon, proprietor Marsha Barrs had
five customers by early morning. ``Talk in the beauty shop this
morning is what a great job the pilot did. He might have hit a
building nearby,'' she said.
   David Anderson, vice president of marketing at the city's
chamber of commerce, stood in a block-and-a-half line Wednesday
night to give blood.
   ``There were people I didn't even know who volunteered to give
blood, talk to people and donate clothes,'' said Dr. Stuart
Leafstedt, chief of staff at St. Luke's.
   The Siouxland Blood Bank reported that 305 units of blood were
available at the two hospitals. Greco said less than a third of
that blood was needed.
</TEXT>
