<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2114EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-FlagBurning     07-20 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Burning,580</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Effigy Doused When No Flag Ignited ^By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Republicans congressman on Thursday
drenched an effigy of a flag-burner with water as a Medal of Honor
winner and a former POW were urging Congress to resist amending the
constitution to ban flag burning.
   When rumors of an impending flag burning swept the Capitol, more
than a dozen GOP lawmakers armed with fire extinguishers and a
bucket of water marched to the scene.
   Two fire trucks were already waiting, as were the television
cameras.
   The flag burning never happened, and the lawmakers were forced
to make do with throwing their water at a stuffed-clothing dummy on
the steps of the Supreme Court.
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., said the congressman were
setting an example for Americans who witness flag burnings.
   ``If they don't have a bucket of water, I hope they take care of
business however they can,'' he told the crowd of colleagues and
others protesting the Supreme Court's decision that allows flag
burning as a form of political expression.
   ``You're not going to come to Capitol Hill and burn the United
States flag,'' warned Rep. Larkin Smith, R-Miss.
   The object of Thursday's scorn was Gregory Lee Johnson, whose
conviction for burning of the American flag at the 1984 Republican
National Convention in Dallas led to the court's 5-4 decision.
   Johnson held a news conference in a building across the street
to protest Congress' decision not to invite him to testify. He said
he never intended to burn a flag on Thursday.
   ``I'm not going to, like fall into this silly trap,'' he said.
   Major veterans groups, meanwhile, told the House Judiciary
Committee's constitutional law subcommittee that Congress should
take action to ban flag burnings.
   Two of the groups _ the American Legion and the Veterans of
Foreign Wars _ said a constitutional amendment was the only course
of action. The Disabled American Veterans said it could also
support support a new statute, if one could be drawn that would
pass the court's muster.
   Subcommittee chairman Don Edwards, D-Calif., has said his panel
hopes to produce a statute for House approval before Congress'
August recess. Edwards and others who fear a constitutional
amendment would weaken the Bill of Rights are hoping a statute will
calm the political uproar.
   James Warner, a Marine flight officer who was shot down and
spent 5{ years in a North Vietnamese prison camp, testified that a
constitutional amendment would put American freedoms at risk.
   ``If this amendment be issued by this House, and ratified by
this nation, there will come a deluge against the Bill of Rights,''
said Warner, an attorney.
   ``Our Bill of Rights has served as a legal restraint upon our
government for 200 years,'' he said. ``If these restraints be
removed, we shall not survive as a free nation.''
   Gordon Roberts, who won the Medal of Honor in Vietnam battle,
recalled how he would think of the flags given ``to relatives of
brothers in arms of mine (as) a last token of gratitude for the
ultimate sacrifice.''
   But he said that men do not ``serve this country for the flag
alone.'' He said an amendment to the constitution might spark a
competition among politicians for who could put the toughest
penalty for flag burning.
   ``Each of us that has worn the uniform of this country are fully
aware that the Pledge of Allegiance ends in the words, `And Justice
for All,''' he said.
   On a recent visit to the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, Roberts said
he saw the flag reflected on the granite face etched with the names
of the dead.
   ``They were as much a part of the flag as the cloth and
stitching,'' he said.
</TEXT>
