<FIRST>r a AM-Crash-SiouxCity     07-20 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash-Sioux City,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Known Mostly For Meatpacking, Advice Sisters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-DC-10 Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sprawling commercial center with 82,000
residents, Sioux City is best-known for its meatpacking industry and
advice sisters.
   The city is situated in northwest Iowa on the east bank of a
giant bend in the Missouri River, at a spot where the Lewis and
Clark expedition stopped in 1804.
   Sioux Gateway Airport is used by five commercial airlines,
including United. It has about 22 arrivals a day, mostly 737s and
727s, but DC-10s have landed there.
   Two of the city's most famous natives are twins Esther Pauline
and Pauline Esther Friedman, who grew up to write the Ann Landers
and Dear Abby advice columns.
   Meatpacking giant IBP and John Morrell and Co. each operate large
meatpacking operations in the city, as do 10 smaller packing
operations.
   The city is part of Iowa's 6th congressional district,
represented by Fred Grandy, a Sioux City native who starred as
``Gopher'' in ``The Love Boat'' television series.
   The only fatality of Lewis and Clark's expedition to scout the
Louisiana Purchase occurred while it was camped on the river _ just
across from what is now Nebraska. Sergeant Floyd's grave is marked
by a monument overlooking the Missouri.
   The last fatal plane crash at Sioux City occurred in May 1987,
when three people died in a light plane.
</TEXT>
