<DOCNO> AP890720-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2146EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DollRecall     07-20 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Doll Recall,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cupie Dolls Recalled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cupie is the company's trademark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve models of ``Doll Craftin'' may present
a choking hazard to young children and are being voluntarily
recalled by the Nebraska manufacturer, the Consumer Product Safety
Commission said Thursday.
   The Cupie Dolls, sold as home craft products since June 1982,
are being recalled by Mangelsen's of Omaha. Tests conducted by the
commission show that the dolls' arms may come off, officials said.
   Cupie Dolls are soft plastic unclothed baby dolls with rooted
fake hair, yarn hair or molded hair. The dolls, made in Hong Kong
or Taiwan, were sold in clear plastic bags with cardboard headers.
   Sold under the label, ``Doll Craftin,'' the recalled models are:
Cupie Doll models 155-67, 156-07, 156-09 and 156-13; Sitting Honey
Doll model 156-63; ``Jill Doll'' with Top Knot model 157-96; Honey
Bun Doll models 158-43, 158-45, 158-46; Curly-One Doll models
158-69, 158-70; Sitting Curly-One Doll models 158-71 through
158-76; Honey Dear Dolls models 158-77 through 158-82; and two
unnamed dolls, models 156-61 and 157-97.
   The commission said consumers who have the recalled Cupie Doll
should immediately take them away from young children or return
them to Mangelsen's Inc, 5455 South 90th St., Omaha, 68127, for a
full refund and postage.
   Consumers also may request the next largest size doll, which has
no hazardous small parts, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
