<DOCNO> AP890720-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Lebanon-BombMagician Adv26   07-20 0899</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Bomb Magician, Adv 26,0929</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs July 26 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lebanon's `Bomb Magician' Has Defused 2,000 Bombs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They call Warrant Officer Youssef Bitar,
formerly of the French Foreign Legion, the ``bomb magician.'' He
calls himself a ``bomb charmer.''
   Either name fits, for he has defused more than 2,000 terrorist
bombs in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war, probably more than any
other demolitions specialist.
   Bitar, who also fought the Germans with Gen. Charles de Gaulle's
Free French forces in World War II, has survived three assassination
attempts by terrorists whose actions he has thwarted, been shot
twice and blown up by a mine _ all for the equivalent of $200 a
month and free gasoline.
   ``If all the bombs he's defused had gone off, the death toll of
the civil war would have more than doubled,'' said a police colonel,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Bitar is indispensable.''
   More than 150,000 people have been killed in the civil war,
hundreds of them in car bombings.
   When car bombs explode before he can get to them, Bitar can
usually tell after examining the blast scene how much explosive was
used, sometimes even the type.
   Bitar, 61, has defused 300 car bombs outside hospitals, airline
offices, newspaper buildings, embassies, government ministries,
movie theaters, churches and mosques.
   Most of the others were time bombs planted in jetliners,
supermarkets, banks, schools, universities and gasoline stations.
   Bitar estimates the total explosive weight of the bombs he had
defused since 1975 at more than 100 tons, ``enough to blow up New
York.''
   Bitar is a Greek Catholic. But he defies Lebanon's
Christian-Moslem sectarian barriers and regularly races across
Beirut's dividing Green Line to the Moslem sector dodging shells and
sniper fire to defuse bombs.
   The biggest bomb he has dismantled was in the Bir Hassan district
of west Beirut in 1983. It contained 1,320 pounds of TNT with four
Katyusha rockets attached to it, enough to pulverize a city block.
   Bitar said it was apparently planted by the Israelis before they
withdrew from west Beirut after their 1982 invasion.
   ``That was probably the worst disaster I've prevented,'' he said
in an interview in his elegant penthouse apartment in the Sad
el-Boushrieh district of Christian east Beirut.
   The stocky Bitar sat stroking his Siamese cat Rambo on his lap as
he talked dispassionately about his spine-chilling exploits,
gesticulating with hands missing three fingertips.
   He lost one fingertip on his right hand when he grabbed a
detonator, taken from a bomb he had defused, that a police officer
was playing with. It exploded in Bitar's hand.
   He lost two fingertips on his other hand in 1982 when he stepped
on a mine after he had defused a bomb in a Palestinian guerrilla
base in the mountains overlooking Beirut. He was also wounded in the
chest and feet.
   ``That cost me three months in hospital,'' Bitar said.
   Talking of his nerve-wracking exploits seemed somehow incongruous
amid the comfortable domesticity of Persian carpets, brass ornaments
and exotic Oriental decor in his marble-floored lounge.
   Bitar joined the Foreign Legion as a teen-ager when Lebanon was
still ruled by France and served with special forces and demolition
teams in North Africa and Europe.
   ``I was with de Gaulle's Free French forces in Algeria when I
heard about the American atom bomb dropped on Hiroshima Aug. 6,
1945,'' he recalled. ``It sort of kindled my interest in
explosives.''
   After joining the Lebanese army in 1946, Bitar became Lebanon's
top explosives expert. But he really came into his own when the
civil war erupted in 1975 and the car bombings started.
   ``I operate with great faith in God,'' Bitar said. ``But I rely
mainly on intuition _ and a little bit of luck.
   ``I can tell the kind of bomb I've got to tackle the moment I see
it. I try to disconnect it as quickly as possible. I feel as if it's
placed under the bed of one of my children,'' he said.
   ``I never panic. From the moment I see the bomb, I know what has
to be done.
   ``The bombs don't frighten me. But I'm always afraid of the
people who planted them.''
   Bitar said the first assassination attempt against him came as he
was defusing a car bomb in the Barbir neighborhood of Moslem west
Beirut on Sept. 19, 1975.
   ``Two bullets hit my neck and chest, but I managed to finish
dismantling the bomb before I collapsed. I stayed two months in a
hospital that time.''
   Gunmen shot at him, and missed, three years later, as he was
defusing a bomb near the entrance to a movie house in the Moslem
sector.
   The third assassination attempt was in 1985 while he was visiting
the Helou police station in west Beirut.
   ``Someone tossed a hand grenade into the room,'' he said. ``I
threw myself to the floor to grab it and threw it out the window
into the parking lot. No one was hurt.''
   Bitar was retired from the army in 1980, but was immediately
hired by the Defense Ministry.
   ``I don't think of quitting,'' he said. ``When I look in the eyes
of people when I arrive to tackle a bomb, I see their faith in me.
I'll fight the bombers as long as I live.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs July 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv20   07-20 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 20 ,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Thursday, July 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eldercare Is Here</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Child-care became an important employee benefit
when a bulge of youngsters worked its way through the population. It
still is, but now Americans are growing older, and elder-care is on
the way.
   It is coming not simply because of demographic dictate; business
efficiency might have even more to do with the development.
Whatever, a growing number of companies concerned with their own
future are considering it.
   Basic to their thinking is the realization that nearly one-fourth
of a typical employer's workforce already provides adult care-giving
services _ for a parent, grandparent or spouse.
   Generally, such services are provided directly and personally at
home. Many of the corporate employees who provide these services
hold critical positions, and as a result their work performance is
sometimes less than efficient.
   Their inability to meet the highest standards often is related to
the strain of their dual reponsibilities. The problem, therefore,
becomes a concern of corporate management.
   Janice Stanger, who holds a doctorate in gerontology, recently
completed a study for William M. Mercer Meidinger Hansen, an
international adviser on employee benefits. She found sound reasons
for considering elder-care.
   She observes that with more and more women entering the
workforce, the number of employees with at-home responsibilities is
hardly likely to decline. These employees often are in their 30s and
40s, which means that not only do they have valuable experience but
also years of further service to offer.
   Already, she suggests, there is evidence that the home-work
conflict may interfere with their performance. It shows up, she
says, in such behavior as missing work, turning down overtime and
training, and even quitting.
   The corporation's role, she says, has two aspects: Long-term care
insurance to pay for medical and associated support services, and
special assistance to those workers with responsibilities for an
older adult.
   Her definition of elder-care refers primarily to the second
aspect, and has as its goal ``to improve the productivity and the
health and quality of life of employed care-givers.'' And, you might
add, the company too.
   The benefit helps the worker cope with three things that make
taking care of elders difficult.
   First, she points out, the frail elderly often have interrelated
needs that involve medicine, finance, and social and psychological
factors.
   Next, the care of the elderly often involves conflicting opinions
and wishes of a number of individuals _ the patient, spouse,
siblings, children. Most of the care-givers can use help in
resolving these conflicts.
   Finally, existing community resources consist of a maze of
federal, state and local public programs, private non-profit
agencies and for-profit providers. The red tape can be overwhelming.
   The elder-care program as she envisions it can be indirect and
direct. The indirect programs involve personnel policies or benefits
which are potentially of value to all employees, such as flextime,
personal leaves and job sharing.
   Direct programs include information, including printed materials,
lectures and other sources; and referral programs to specific
agencies, nursing homes and other resources.
   In addition, they might include support groups and counseling,
and even access to an adult day-care center for the older relative.
Reimbursement programs also might be used to subsidize the cost of
respite care.
   All this sounds expensive, as most benefits are, not just in
themselves but as a growing percentage of business costs. But,
according to the report, the cost of an elder-care program is
usually ``modest and clearly defined.''
   At a time when employers are resisting additional benefits and
even taking away some benefits granted earlier, Stanger believes
they have something to gain with elder-care, because it addresses so
specific a need.
   She calls it an opportunity for them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, July 20.</NOTE>
</DOC>
