<FIRST>a a PM-MarchingCobras Adv27   07-20 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marching Cobras, Adv 27,0850</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thurs PMs, July 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Award-Winning Drill Team Helps Inner-City Members</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AMANDA DAVIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The children who swing their hips, bob
their heads and fling their knees and elbows up and out to throbbing
drumbeats have left crowds wide-eyed from Kansas City to the
nation's capital and beyond.
   The Marching Cobras, an award-winning drill team, also leave a
mark on the members, many of them from poor, inner-city homes with
one parent.
   ``For one, you get a chance to travel and do all sorts of things,
and another, it keeps you out of trouble,'' said Aaron Byrd, 15, a
Cobra for five years. ``I think I might be on the street and in
trouble if I wasn't in the group. ... There are no down sides to
being in the Cobras.''
   ``I've made a lot of friends in the Cobras,'' said A'yanna
Gilmore, 14, who has been in the drill team three years. ``And it
makes you learn independence, and responsibility for your uniform,
your performance and everything.''
   Willie Smith, drillmaster for 20 years, said it's virtually
impossible to understand what the Cobras are without seeing their
flashy uniforms and intricate routines, elbows and knees pumping 1{
times for every drumbeat.
   As much a part of Kansas City as its fountains, the Cobras
average 300 invitations a year and accept 100 to 200. They performed
117 times last year, including what Smith called a ``dream come
true,'' for President Reagan.
   ``He kind of pepped up when we started,'' Smith said. ``I really
wanted to go grab him and get him to dance, but the security men, we
couldn't go past this line, or that line. But he would have liked
it.''
   The Cobras made their first overseas trip in February, to Nice,
France, where they competed in the City of Carnivals Festival. They
won awards in three categories, including best international drill
team.
   ``We saw Monte Carlo, Cannes, stayed in the best hotels, ate the
best meals,'' Smith said. ``I'd never get to do that by myself. And
here are these kids going to a place they never even heard of.''
   For the members, being in the Cobras is ``their big chance,'' he
said. ``When we went to France, we found out that some of the kids
have never been to the airport, they've never been to the (Country
Club) Plaza,'' an affluent Kansas City restaurant and shopping area.
   The Cobras began in 1969 when Smith coached a group of
seventh-grade boys to dance in a talent show. That group evolved
into a drill team and eventually became the Kansas City Marching
Cobras _ so named after a school librarian watching from a
third-floor window said it looked like a snake.
   Whites aren't excluded but all the members, who range in age from
8 to 18, are black, Smith said. ``I don't think there's too many
whites who want to come to the inner city to practice.''
   Money problems nearly ended the Cobras in 1986, but the team
affiliated with the Boys and Girls Club in Kansas City, which eased
the money crunch, Smith said. ``Until we came to the boys and girls
clubs, we raised the money ourselves. Bake sales, car washes,
raffles.
   ``But in some ways we were happier when we were scuffing it. The
kids now are getting spoiled. They know they get the uniform, so
they don't take care of it like they did before. If the parents paid
$70 or $80 for it, it would be taken care of.''
   The glitzy uniforms cost $150-$175 each, so only 85 Cobras can be
in uniform at any time. The colors vary each year.
   Also each year, two Cobras are honored as the mascot and senior
imperial. The mascot wears a rubber cobra headpiece and leads the
group.
   ``The person who wears the cobra headpiece is the most
outstanding member,'' Smith said. ``They have to compete for it. An
11-year-old dreams of wearing the mascot head. It's prestigious and
it's an honor.''
   The Cobras are based at the Boys and Girls Club. The windowless
brown brick building squats in the inner city, clusters of children
lounging outside. Cars stop on the street, disgorging more children.
Practice is three times a week.
   Smith's office exhibits honors from past performances. Plaques,
trophies, photographs and letters cover the walls. A box of awards
sits in a corner.
   After 20 years, Smith is more than drillmaster, and many members
call him ``Dad.'' They knock on his door to tell him of problems or
ask advice. Being on the team keeps them off the street, which has
always been his goal.
   ``Children have changed. The kids aren't as interested in
extracurricular activities. We need to spend even more time with
them now than before, because they spend more time on the streets
now. And the streets are worse.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, July 27</NOTE>
