<FIRST>a i PM-CaribbeanUnity Adv24   07-20 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Caribbean Unity, Adv 24,0884</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMS July 24 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>English-Speaking Caribbean Islands Seek to Unite</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The idea of merging the Caribbean's
smallest English-speaking islands into a single nation or federation
has been around for half a century with little ever coming of it.
   But now that a major trading partner, Western Europe, is moving
toward economic integration, the fervor of unity advocates has
increased.
   Prime Minister James Mitchell of St. Vincent and the Grenadines,
a leader of the most promising attempt at political union since the
West Indies Federation collapsed nearly 30 years ago, maintains the
eastern Caribbean faces economic disaster if it doesn't unite by the
time the 12 nations of the European Economic Community form a single
market by the end of 1992.
   Mostly at stake are Caribbean bananas.
   Mitchell, attending a recent regional meeting on Grenada, said
that without political unity, individual islands won't have the
political power to protect their banana sales in England after the
European trade barriers fall.
   ``Who will respect you when you go to Europe representing a
ministate? How much time will they have for you?'' Mitchell said in
a recent interview. ``We don't need unity to survive. We need it to
get our voice heard in the international community.''
   ``I'm bone-tired of trying to convince people,'' he added. ``I
think we've lost the momentum in spite of how urgently it's needed.''
   Vaughn Lewis, secretary-general of the Organization of Eastern
Caribbean States, said, ``If you go to Europe and say you represent
a chain of islands, the impact is greater than if you say you
represent one.
   The Caribbean benefits today from preferential trade access for
its agricultural products into the EEC.
   Under current agreements, Caribbean bananas are protected in
Britain, which does not import bananas from other regions. Caribbean
bananas grow on small farms and are more expensive than those
mass-produced in Central and South America.
   With the dismantling of EEC trade barriers, Caribbean bananas
will have to compete in an open market. British consumers then could
be expected to buy the cheaper Central and South American bananas
and the Caribbean's $175 million annual market would collapse.
   The West Indies Federation was founded in 1958 as the first
attempt at political integration but disintegrated four years later
when Jamaica withdrew.
   Mitchell, supported by Prime Minister John Compton of St. Lucia,
renewed the unity drive at the 1987 summit meeting of the
Organization of Eastern Caribbean States, a regional sub-grouping
within the Caribbean Community and Common Market.
   The idea of creating a single country or a regional federation of
states by mid-1989 out of the eastern Caribbean islands of Antigua,
St. Kitts-Nevis, Montserrat, Dominica, Grenada, St. Lucia and St.
Vincent was approved in principle.
   But Antigua withdrew almost immediately and was followed later by
Montserrat and St. Kitts-Nevis.
   Mitchell and Compton still favor political union of the remaining
four, known as the Windward Islands.
   The eastern Caribbean islands share a central bank, common
currency and high court.
   All are small and relatively undeveloped with a combined
English-speaking population of 400,000. In land mass, the largest is
Dominica with 289 square miles and the smallest is Montserrat, the
only remaining British colony of the group, with just 39 square
miles.
   Geographically, they resemble a 450-mile kite tail stretching
from Puerto Rico in the north to Trinidad in the south. Their
populations range from 12,000 in Montserrat to 119,000 in St. Lucia.
   Detractors say a political marriage is unrealistic; each island
is as unique as any nation, regardless of size. They say economic
integration, not political, is what is needed.
   ``We go to the United Nations and the World Bank and fight
tooth-and-nail to portray small island states as having special
characteristics and requiring special treatment. We cannot ignore
this reality in our forums,'' Prime Minister Kenneth Simmonds of St.
Kitts-Nevis said in an interview.
   ``We already go to Europe as a team speaking for the region,'' he
said. ``The EEC is not a national front, it's a regional front. The
process should be the same for us.''
   The Windwards export 220,000 tons of bananas a year to Britain,
accounting for two-thirds of the bananas consumed in England.
   The four islands plan to hold a political union referendum after
parliamentary elections, still unscheduled, are held in Grenada and
Dominica.
   The Caribbean Community, an organization of 13 English-speaking
states that includes the Windwards and Leewards, already has taken
steps to form a common market.
   ``At present there is little immediate prospect for political
unity,'' Prime Minister Herbert Blaize of Grenada said in welcoming
heads of government to a recent meeting here. ``But we continue to
knock at the door for closer cooperation and cry fervently for
economic integration.''
   Caribbean leaders say economic unity is imperative if they are to
survive the trading blocs being formed around the world, including
the recent U.S. and Canada trade agreement.
   Prime Minister Michael Manley of Jamaica has called it ``the only
way a group of small countries can survive.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs July 24</NOTE>
