<FIRST>a i PM-KhabarovskReacts Adv25   07-20 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khabarovsk Reacts, Adv 25,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs July 25 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reserve Troops in Far East Assail Sakharov for Afghanistan Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Vladivostok Notes, b0294</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHABAROVSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of miles from Moscow, the
name Andrei Sakharov kindles fire in the hearts of young men still
smarting from the wounds of the Soviet adventure in Afghanistan.
   In a riverside square in this century-old Siberian city, a
platoon of Afghanistan veterans staged a bit of street theater one
evening recently to demonstrate their reserve group's combat
training, play some popular songs _ and take a swipe at the Nobel
Peace laureate regarded as the founder of the Soviet human rights
movement.
   Between numbers played by a military band in fatigue uniforms, an
announcer told the few hundred people in the audience, ``We all
remember how academician Sakharov insulted us at the Congress of
People's Deputies.''
   Sakharov was heckled during the parliamentary session in June and
lambasted by a parade of speakers who accused him of blaspheming the
military in an interview in Canada earlier in the year in which he
was quoted as saying Soviet pilots killed soldiers they could not
save from being captured by Afghan rebels.
   The 68-year-old physicist and now a Congress deputy endured
almost seven years in exile in the closed city of Gorky for his
outspoken opposition to the Soviet military intervention that began
in December 1979. He told the Congress he would not retract his
charge, pending the outcome of an investigation by Soviet
authorities.
   The emotional, nationally broadcast attack on Sakharov
reverberated weeks later in this Far Eastern city built on the banks
of the great Amur River to protect against Chinese invasion 4,400
miles from Moscow.
   The reservists loaded their assault rifles and machine guns with
blanks and climbed atop an armored personnel carrier that bore a red
banner proclaiming, ``Afghanistan _ in my heart forever.''
   With police motioning the crowd to make way, a squad of troops
ambled up the street and was gunned down by mock Mujahadeen rebels
lying in ambush by the side of the road.
   Guns blazing, the armored personnel carrier sped to the rescue,
and the ``wounded'' Red Army soldiers were hastily loaded into an
ambulance truck that escaped in a hail of fire, its driver nearly
grazing the crowd in a hair-raising demonstration of evasive driving
tactics.
   The chatter of machine guns and ear-splitting roar of artillery
rocked the night as first the truck was halted by fire, then the
personnel carrier was captured by rebels and recaptured by the
Soviets.
   The Red Army men risked their lives over and over until they
finally succeeded in hauling their wounded to safety.
   The last Soviet troops pulled out of Afghanistan on Feb. 15 after
more than nine years of fighting, but as the street drama in
Khabarovsk illustrated, the withdrawal was no instant cure for what
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev once called his nation's ``bleeding
wound.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs July 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
