<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose a modest 0.2 percent in
June, the smallest advance since early last year, the government
said in a report that bolstered the view that inflationary pressures
are beginning to ease.
   The slowdown reported Wednesday in the Consumer Price Index
reflected the fact that energy and food costs, which had been
shooting upward this year, finally moderated last month.
   Stock prices responded to the upbeat news with a strong rally
that carried the market to new highs since the crash of October
1987. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 39.65 points to
2,584.41.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing starts, led by a steep rise in
apartment building, rebounded 7 percent in June as interest rates
fell, the government reported.
   But analysts said Wednesday that single-family construction would
remain weak as the economy continues to slow.
   New homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.4 million units last month, up from 1.31 million
units in May when construction fell 2.5 percent, the Commerce
Department said.
</TEXT>
