<FIRST>r f PM-DaytonHudson-Lechmere     07-20 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dayton Hudson-Lechmere,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dayton Hudson Agrees to Sell Lechmere</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dayton Hudson Corp. says it has agreed to sell
its Lechmere Inc. retail chain for an undisclosed price to an
investment group, two mall developers and members of Lechmere's
management.
   Terms of the definitive agreement with the Boston-based Berkshire
Partners investment group were not disclosed. The transaction,
announced Wednesday, is expected to be completed by the end of
September, Dayton Hudson said.
   Under the agreement, Dayton Hudson plans to sell Lechmere to
Berkshire Partners, regional mall developers Stephen R. Karp and
Stephen R. Weiner of Boston and members of Lechmere's management.
   Dayton Hudson President Bruce G. Allbright said the
Minneapolis-based retailer is pleased with the agreement.
   ``Lechmere is growing and profitable and we are pleased that the
company will continue to serve its customers,'' Allbright said.
   Allbright said the investment group has advised Dayton Hudson
that it intends to operate the business of Lechmere in substantially
the same manner as in the past, including retaining the Lechmere
name.
   Allbright credited the management team at Lechmere with running a
solidly profitable operation.
   ``Lechmere is a fine company. However, Dayton Hudson has decided
to dedicate its resources to the expansion of our principal growth
companies,'' he said.
   In the past two years, Dayton Hudson has acquired 80 stores which
are now Target discount stores and has opened another 46 Target
stores and 38 Mervyn's stores. Since 1986, the corporation has
increased its total number of stores by 54 percent.
   When Dayton Hudson acquired Lechmere in 1969, there were two
Lechmere stores, in Cambridge and Dedham, Mass. Today, Lechmere is a
hardlines retail company operating 27 stores in nine states.
   Lechmere stores offer products in consumer electronics, major
appliances, home-office, housewares and leisure-time equipment. The
company employs about 5,000.
   Lechmere's 1988 revenue totaled $769 million, or 6 percent of
Dayton Hudson's total. Operating profit in 1988 was $22 million, 3
percent of Dayton Hudson's total.
   Dayton Hudson has about 135,000 employees and operates 660 stores
in 38 states.
</TEXT>
