<FIRST>r f PM-ZenithComputer     07-20 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zenith Computer,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zenith Announces 5.9-Pound Portable Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. has announced a portable
personal computer about the size of a 1-inch stack of paper and
weighing under 6 pounds.
   Zenith's Minisport, unveiled Wednesday, is the first computer to
use a 2-inch-wide diskette, the smallest yet, for storing data. Most
computers still use 5\-inch diskettes, although the 3{-inch format
is increasingly popular.
   Packaged software is not available on the Japanese-made 2-inch
diskettes, but users will be able to load programs into the portable
by hooking it up to another computer or a device that handles bigger
diskettes.
   Zenith spokesman Matthew Mirapaul said the Glenview, Ill.-based
company is not counting on the tiny diskettes to become a new
industry standard, although that may happen because they hold as
much information in less space.
   Portable computers are getting steadily smaller. Zenith's is
heavier than NEC Corp.'s 4.4-pound Ultralite, which was announced
last year, but it is also cheaper, starting at $1,999 vs. $2,999 for
the Ultralite.
   Zenith claims a battery life of more than three hours for the
Minisport, compared to about two hours for the the Ultralite. NEC's
machine has an internal modem, a device that permits communication
over phone lines, something that the Minisport lacks.
</TEXT>
