<SECOND>PM-Economists-Deficit,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economists Call for More Investment in Programs that Aid People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers intent on debating the federal
deficit are ignoring the basic need for investment in people, Nobel
Prize-winning economist James Tobin told a congressional panel.
   Tobin joined 326 other economists Wednesday in signing a
statement saying that failure to increase investment in such things
as education, public health, transportation and technology ``will
have a crippling effect on America's future competitiveness.''
   The increased investment must be paid for through cuts in
military and agriculture subsidy spending, as well as with revenue
from new taxes, according to the statement written by the Economic
Policy Institute, a Washington-based think tank.
   Princeton University economist Alan S. Blinder, also testifying
before the Congressional Joint Economic Committee, said the
government's ``unending obession'' with the deficit will adversely
affect future productivity and standards of living.
   Blinder said the government must invest more in such things as
programs to aid disadvantaged children and to improve roads, bridges
and sewer facilities.
