<DOCNO> AP890720-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AntitrustLaws     07-20 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Antitrust Laws,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bar Association Panel Criticizes Justice Department Over Antitrust</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department cannot adequately enforce
federal antitrust laws because of budget cuts that have reduced
funding and staffing, an American Bar Association panel said in a
report.
   The 15-member panel's report, released Wednesday, also called on
Bush administration officials to end ``rhetoric'' that some existing
antitrust laws are outdated and shouldn't be enforced.
   ``...the task force members uniformly believe that the antitrust
division's core mission _ to preserve competitive markets _ cannot
be carried out at the current reduced levels of staffing and
resources,'' says the 59-page report.
   The report was submitted to the bar association's antitrust
section and was not considered as representing the position of the
section or the association. It was released in New York by Irving
Scher, chairman of the bar association's antitrust section, which
monitors and recommends changes in antitrust law.
   Scher said copies of the report were sent to Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh and the recently appointed antitrust division head,
James F. Rill. The ABA antitrust section was likely to approve the
report and refer it to the full association, Scher said.
   Asked for his reaction to the report, Rill said, ``On balance,
it's positive.
   ``It confirms the enforcement priorities of the division _
criminal enforcement and merger enforcement,'' Rill said.
   He said the report ``makes some useful suggestions regarding
structural and competition analysis that can be brought into play in
deregulation and still somewhat regulated industries.''
   While Rill said the report ``probably is a bit off the mark in
suggesting that the merger guidelines have not been fully
enforced,'' he said, ``it does represent a public perception'' that
the antitrust division has not enforced those guidelines.
   Noting his brief tenure, Rill said he has not made any final
assessment as to whether the division has enough manpower and money
to do its job. The division has about 500 people, he said, including
230 attorneys and 40 economists.
   Under 1982 and 1984 modifications in federal antitrust laws, many
constraints against mergers in a range of industries were eased as
the Reagan administration endorsed allowing market forces to
regulate competition.
   ``Although it was important to highlight the excesses of prior
enforcement policies and substantive antitrust doctrines, the task
force believes that further reliance on this rhetoric will undermine
self-policing and voluntary compliance with the law,'' the panel
stated.
   It added that ``diminished support for antitrust enforcement has
allowed the talent and other resources of the division to shrink, as
its mission was lost in the `non-action' enforcement rhetoric of the
times.''
   Panel member Paul J. McGrath, a former assistant attorney general
for antitrust, disagreed with the contention that criticism of
exisiting laws had undercut enforcement policies. He and various
other panel members also dissented from several key criticisms
contained in the report.
   The panel said that under the Reagan administration's
deregulatory philosophy enforcement of actions other than
bid-rigging and price-fixing have become ``extremely rare.''
   It said that during the 1980s, when merger activity skyrocketed,
antitrust division resources devoted to merger enforcement actions
declined and the Justice Department allowed a significant number of
mergers it did not statistically define as competitive.
   While supporting overall changes in antitrust laws, the panel
recommended a ``more vigorous and visible merger enforcement
program'' and said antitrust laws should not be relaxed further. It
also called for more criminal price-fixing investigations.
   In pressing for increased funding, the group said the antitrust
division staff had been reduced by 50 percent in the last eight
years and many of its most experienced lawyers had left. It said
support for antitrust division lawyers appeared to be at an
``all-time low.''
   The panel included three former assistant attorneys general in
charge of the antitrust division, former senior staff members,
private antitrust attorneys, scholars and economists.
   Rill said some of the report's criticism ``is misdirected. The
suggestion that the division is using some set of standards other
than the merger guidelines simply isn't the case.''
   Rill rejected the report's contention that criminal enforcement
of antitrust laws had been aimed mostly at small companies instead
of regional or national ones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
