<FIRST>r f PM-Mirabella Bjt   07-20 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mirabella, Bjt,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Fashion Magazine Settles Down to Hard Work of Making It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The glittering coming-out party for Mirabella,
the new women's fashion magazine, is history. The upbeat reviews
have been written, and the gossip columnists have turned their
attention elsewhere.
   Now begins the waiting game. Will the upscale fashion and
lifestyle guide for the well-educated woman be a lasting hit? Or
will it join the heap of new magazines that fold after only a few
years?
   ``It's going very well. I think wonderfully well,'' Grace
Mirabella, the monthly's editor and namesake, said Wednesday. All
600,000 copies of the premier issue in June sold out, she said.
   But this veteran of the competitive, crowded world of magazines
knows success can be fleeting. ``I'm anxiety-ridden,'' she says.
   And the sales figures for the July issue _ 70 to 75 percent of
600,000 copies are expected to sell _ could be interpreted as
cautionary. But Julie Lewit-Nirenberg, the magazine's publisher,
noted that summer is traditionally a slow time in the magazine
business and that the first issue sold for $1 compared to the hefty
$2.95 that the buyer must now fork out.
   She also said the number of advertising pages dropped from 123 in
June to 85 in July and 50 in August. But the picture is rosy for the
September issue, which just closed for printing with 149 advertising
pages, she added.
   Ms. Mirabella described the pitfalls to avoid if the magazine is
to succeed.
   ``We have to keep our eye on the reader we think we have _ where
her head is and how she sees us. The reader we have is an
intelligent reader, selective in her view and selective in her eye.''
   By targeting a narrowly defined audience of well-educated, older
and affluent women, Mirabella has a chance of surviving in the
crowded fashion magazine market, said Joseph Ostrow, worldwide media
director of Foote, Cone and Belding, a New York ad agency.
   But a good six months will have to pass before any meaningful
judgment can be made on the publication, said Nancy Smith, senior
vice president of media services at Young &amp; Rubicam Inc., another
New York ad agency.
   ``Grace Mirabella is a well-known personality. And the launching
of the magazine was very gossiping and jet-setting,'' she noted.
``Once that dies out, then you are going to see what you are dealing
with. It's still too early to tell.''
   Ms. Smith said the money and backing of communications magnate
Rupert Murdoch bode well for Mirabella, as does the fact that Ms.
Mirabella is the creative force behind it.
   ``She is an extremely talented woman who has demonstrated her
strength before. I would be very optimistic about the long-term
success.''
   Ms. Mirabella was editor in chief of Vogue for 17 years before
she was abruptly dismissed in June 1988 by S.I. Newhouse Jr., the
head of magazine publisher Conde Nast. In November, Murdoch
approached her about presiding over a monthly bearing her name.
   In six months Ms. Mirabella not only assembled a staff but
produced a new magazine.
   Despite its goals, the glossy, oversized publication has some
features that can hardly be considered intelligent reading material.
One article in the June issue lists the favorite lipstick color of
actress Joan Collins, designer Caroline Herrera and jewelry designer
Paloma Picasso.
   But its tone is more subtle than many other fashion magazines _
both in its fashion coverage and its features. And Ms. Mirabella and
her staff pride themselves on the fact that the monthly is almost
half text.
   ``It's a smart and intelligent magazine for women interested in
style and fashion but like a little more protein in reading matter,
not just a sugar high,'' Ms. Lewit-Nirenberg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0240 </DOCNO>
