<FIRST>r f PM-TexasAir-Boeing     07-20 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Air-Boeing,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Air to Buy Boeing Jets in $2.8 Billion Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp.'s plans to order up to 100 new
jets in a $2.8 billion deal signifies its ailing carriers,
Continental Airlines and Eastern Airlines, expect improved financial
conditions, analysts say.
   Analysts said Wednesday the deal was an important one for
Eastern, now in the midst of bankruptcy reorganiztion and a
lingering strike, but said both Texas Air subsidiaries probably are
speculating on better times before the start of deliveries in 1992.
   ``Each of them, along with a couple of other carriers in the
industry, have been facing some financial difficulty,'' said George
James, president of Washington-based Airline Economics Inc., an
aviation consulting firm.
   ``But with the first delivery in 1992 they could be betting on
the fact that they will have improved significantly in their
financial performance by that time and be able to arrange some good
financing,'' James said.
   Sixty of the Boeing Co. jets are earmarked for Continental and 40
for Eastern.
   Houston-based Texas Air also announced Wednesday that Continental
soon would purchase 11 widebody Airbus A300 jets and spare parts
from Eastern for $303.5 million. In addition, Continental plans to
lease two McDonnell Douglas DC-10s from Eastern and in return lease
34 of its jets to its sister carrier.
   ``I think this is an important step in Continental's return to
profitability and confidence in the future of the airline,'' said D.
Joseph Corr, Continental's chairman and chief executive officer.
``Overall, we're looking at more seats to more destinations than
prior to these changes.''
   Continental agreed to buy as many as 60 of Boeing's narrow-body
737-300s, with deliveries of 30 aircraft planned for 1992 to 1994
and with an option to purchase another 30 of the jets in 1995 and
1996.
   The total cost of the Continental purchase would be about $1.7
billion, Corr said, adding that about three-quarters of the new
fleet would replace aging aircraft.
   Corr declined to discuss financing for the purchase. Continental
posted a first-quarter loss of $16.5 million, narrowed from an $80.6
million loss in the same quarter of 1988.
   In a statement, Texas Air said it would obtain financing for the
planes ``in later years, nearer to the delivery dates, based on
prevailing capital market conditions and projections.''
   Airline analyst Louis A. Marckesano, of Philadelphia-based Janney
Montgomery Scott, said the airlines' competitive position in the
1990s strongly depended on orders for new jets.
   ``The biggest difference we find right now between the haves and
the have-nots in the industry is the airplanes on order,'' he said.
   ``It may sound like a trite thing to say, but when you're
spelling out the differences that will exist between these two
groups, the share of market these airlines hold in the future ... is
going to directly hinge on the size of their fleets,''he said.
   Continental, a non-union carrier that emerged from bankruptcy
reorganization in 1986, and Eastern were among only three major U.S.
airlines that did not have new planes on order. Troubled Pan Am
Corp. is now the only one in that category.
   The agreement with Boeing allows Continental to substitute a
portion of its order for Boeing's 737-400s or 737-500s, which have
different seating capacities, allowing for greater flexibility as
the airline's needs change in the coming years, Corr said.
</TEXT>
