<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Chrysler-Trucks Bjt   07-20 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler-Trucks, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler: Trucks 'R' Us</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the time being, Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee
Iacocca says, the nation's No. 3 automaker is more of a truckmaker
than a carmaker.
   ``If you call minivans trucks, it looks that way because in the
last 40 days in total, we've sold one car for every truck,'' Iacocca
said in an interview this week.
   ``Other companies aren't quite in that position,'' he said, ``but
that's just because of (Jeep) Cherokee strength and minivan
strength.''
   Auto industry analysts say the struggling company's emphasis on
the profitable Jeeps and minivans may be the best tonic.
   ``Right now, it's a truckmaker that also makes cars,'' said auto
analyst Ronald Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. of San
Francisco. ``I think it's an intelligent decision on Chrysler's part
because trucks make more money that cars.''
   Chrysler is expected to announce Monday that its second-quarter
earnings were near or slightly lower than those during the same time
last year. This time around, the company will be relying more on the
dollars generated by trucks than in the past.
   Chrysler, through its Dodge Caravan and Plymouth Voyager, holds
56 percent of the minivan market in the United States. It pioneered
the popular vehicles back in 1983 and has held most of the market
since.
   Through the first half of this year _ and for the first time in
history _ Chrysler sold more domestically made light trucks than
cars. Together, those vehicles make up more than 90 percent of the
company's fleet.
   Trough June 30 this year, the company sold 0.97 cars for each
truck. A year ago at the same time, the ratio was 1.14 cars per
truck. The gap was wider in the first half of 1987, as the company
sold 1.56 cars per truck.
   General Motors Corp.'s car sales have run slightly more than
twice the rate of its truck sales, and Ford sells better than 1.5
cars for every truck.
   Despite the dominance of truck sales at Chrysler, Iacocca said
the company is very much in the carmaking business.
   ``We can't become just a truck company,'' he said. ``We've got
good car programs. First of all, our luxury cars are in pretty good
shape because they're not too big.
   ``Then we have an all new platform coming in late '92,'' he said.
``That's a billion-dollar effort at a new mid-size group of cars and
they're coming along nicely.
   ``The one that's tough is we don't have an (Dodge) Omni
replacement at the moment. Our smallest car really is the P-car, the
Plymouth Sundance-Dodge Shadow.''
   Chrysler isn't letting today's truck business take care of
tomorrow. There will be more competition in the segment beginning in
the next few months as the new GM minivans come to the market and as
foreign companies, including Mazda, introduce more versions.
   A growing number of companies also are offering sport-utility
vehicles like Chrysler's Jeep line. But Chrysler isn't standing
still.
   The company has broken ground for a new assembly plant in Detroit
that will make a Jeep model code-named the ``ZJ.'' Earlier this
year, Iacocca announced that Chrysler and the French automaker
Renault would join forces to make a smaller sport-utility vehicle
named the ``JJ.''
   Both of those products are to be introduced in the early 1990s
and mean the company will have more truck production capacity than
it does now.
   Anyone watching Chrysler's profits knows the company these days
is making money from minivans and Jeeps.
   ``People look at the car side and wonder if they are at a
competitive disadvantage to Ford and General Motors,'' said analyst
Charles Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co. of New York. ``That's hopefully
just a temporary condition.
   ``But clearly, now you can make an excellent case if you want to
classify it as a truckmaker,'' he said. ``Over the next couple of
years, you'd have to say the show belongs mostly to the truck side
of the operation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
