<DOCNO> AP890720-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0329EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time     07-20 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Releases Brief in Delaware Supreme Coury Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc., maintaining its board has the right to
decide the company's long-term strategy, has asked the Delaware
Supreme Court to uphold a lower court decision allowing the media
giant to proceed with its $14 billion tender offer for Warner
Communications Inc.
   Time made the request in a brief filed Wednesday with the Supreme
Court, two days after Paramount Communications Inc. asked the court
to overturn the ruling by Chancery Court Judge William T. Allen and
block the planned Time-Warner merger.
   Paramount is trying to buy Time in a hostile $12.2 billion tender
offer.
   Allen ruled last week the proposed Time-Warner merger resulted
from Time's long-term business strategy and that Paramount and Time
shareholders, who are also trying to stop the merger, had not proved
they possessed a right to interfere with the transaction.
   Paramount claimed in its brief that Allen's decision would allow
Time to proceed although the merger _ and Time's long-term strategy
_ would cost Time shareholders the financial benefits of the
$200-a-share Paramount bid.
   Time responded that the state Supreme Court itself noted, in a
1985 case involving Unocal Corp. and takeover strategist T. Boone
Pickens, that ``there is substantial evidence that director
resistance to hostile bids, even at a premium over market price,
tends in the long run to enhance market prices.''
   The Supreme Court also has stated that ```a board of directors is
not a passive instrumentality' even in matters of fundamental
corporate change,'' and that directors are allowed and even
obligated to take steps to protect shareholder interests in the face
of a tender offer, Time contended.
   Delaware's highest court will hear the case Monday, and the
justices could rule at any time after arguments are concluded.
Time's $70-a-share tender offer for Warner is scheduled to expire at
5 p.m. Monday.
   Paramount charged in its brief that Allen used improperly used
standards for director actions set in the Unocal case, but Time said
the judge's decision was ``unquestionably the product of an orderly
and logical deductive process.''
   Time said further there was support for the board's actions in a
case arising from the takeover battle for Macmillan Inc. last year.
The case allowed a board to use several criteria in refusing to
entertain offers that threaten corporate policy, including a firm's
long-term plans, Time said.
   Nothing in the Macmillan decision ``suggests that these criteria
_ particularly `long-term strategic' plans _ become inoperative in
the face of an all-cash, all-shares tender offer,'' Time said.
   Time stock closed up $1.37{ a share to close at $139.37{ in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading. Warner was unchanged at
$65.62{ a share, and Paramount picked up $1.62{ to close at $58.62{
a share.
   Separately, Time announced Wednesday its second-quarter earnings
rose 12 percent to $94 million, or $1.61 per share, up from $84
million, or $1.45 a share, in the same period of 1988.
   Revenue for the period rose to $1.22 billion from $1.1 billion.
   Time said in a statement all of its business segments _
magazines, books, programming and cable television _ had improved
results during the quarter.
   For the first half, Time had it earned $143 million, or $2.49 a
share, down from $150 million, or $2.58 a share, in the first six
months of 1988.
   The first-half results were affected by Time's lower
first-quarter profits, which fell due to lower operating earnings
from the company's magazine segment, heavier interest expenses and
costs related to the Warner deal.
   First-half revenue totaled $2.35 billion, up from $2.17 billion a
year earlier.
   Warner announced its earnings on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
