<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     07-20 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the yen and major European
currencies this morning.
   Spot gold was steady at lower levels in quiet trading.
   Traders said the dollar appeared to be on an upward course.
   ``We tried to take it lower yesterday, but that got nowhere. So
today we'll try to take it in the other direction and see what
happens,'' said a trader at a large West German bank in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, the dollar was up 0.43 yen to close at 142.33 yen.
Later in London, the dollar eased to 141.91 yen.
   In London late Wednesday, one British pound cost $1.6112,
compared with Wednesday's late $1.6195.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.9147 West German marks, up from
1.9007; 1.6520 Swiss francs, up from 1.6465; 6.4950 French francs,
up from 6.4490; 2.1600 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1340; 1,385.25
Italian lire, from 1,374.50; 1.1863 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1887.
   Gold opened in London at $367.80 per troy ounce, down from
$371.75 late Wednesday. At mid morning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $368.80.
   Gold traded in Zurich at $368.50 per troy ounce, compared with
$371.00 late Wednesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at a bid $369.11 per troy ounce,
down $3.75 from Wednesday.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $5.19 a troy ounce, down from
$5.23.
</TEXT>
