<FIRST>r f PM-CoalStrike-Talks     07-20 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike-Talks,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>UMW, Pittston Accuse Each Other of Inflexibility</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Richmond, Va., dated PM-Coal Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUFFIELD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Mine Workers and Pittston Coal
Group Inc. resumed contract talks with both sides digging in their
heels on the key issue of benefits for retired miners.
   Pittston Coal President Michael Odom stated flatly Wednesday that
the company won't take part in the ``union-sponsored health and
retirement funds. Period.''
   The company's attempt to withdraw from the union's industrywide
pension and health care plans in favor of a program for Pittston
employees has been a main issue in the 3{-month-old strike. The
union fears that if Pittston pulls out of the plan, other employers
will too.
   ``We've given everything we have to give,'' Odom said at company
headquarters in Lebanon. ``Give us a proposal that displays this
(union) flexibility.''
   Odom's statement was ``basically another demonstration of bad
faith,'' UMW President Richard Trumka said.
   Pittston has never said it is unable to afford any proposal the
UMW has offered including the pension plans, Trumka said.
   The two sides met for the first time in six weeks at a motel in
this southwest Virginia town. They sat in separate rooms with
federal mediators shuttling notes back and forth. Talks were to
resume today.
   Trumka said Pittston refuses to rescind what the company calls
its final offer, which the union rejected last month.
   ``They want us to be flexible but they don't want to be,'' union
spokesman Joe Corcoran said.
   Odom said earlier Wednesday on ``CBS This Morning'' that the
company was standing by its previous contract proposal.
   ``At this point the movement will have to come from the union,''
Odom said. ``We have our proposal on the table.
   The 1950 UMW retirement fund covers 130,000 pensioners who
retired between 1947 and 1976. It was established so miners who went
from company to company when mines shut down could have pensions,
Corcoran said.
   Pittston, which has 560 retirees covered by the fund, said it
doesn't make sense for the company to contribute to pensions
received by retirees of other companies.
   Trumka said the union wouldn't give in on the issue. The UMW
won't ``turn our backs on 130,000 pensioners,'' he said.
   Later, Trumka told a rally of about 3,000 union members and
supporters in St. Paul that the UMW plans to increase pressure on
directors of The Pittston Co., parent of the coal company.
   Union officials said that pressure will be demonstrated today
with a visit by Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn to the region.
   The Boston City Council has threatened to pull city funds out of
Shawmut Bank unless William Craig, a member of Pittston's board who
is connected to the bank, resigns his board seat.
   About 1,900 UMW miners in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky
went on strike against Pittston beginning April 5, because of the
company's refusal to sign a national contract outlawing mandatory
overtime and Sunday work, in addition to the retirement benefits
issue.
   Up to 46,000 miners in 10 states had been off the job until
Monday in wildcat strikes to support Pittston workers. Most have
gone back to work but the union said up to 40 percent of the 7,900
union miners in south-central and southwestern West Virginia
remained on strike Wednesday.
   Fred Tucker, contract administrator for seven UMW Districts, said
he expected all to return to work by today.
</TEXT>
