<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     07-20 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed higher against the Japanese
yen Thursday, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index rose
moderately.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 107.70
points, or 0.32 percent, ending the day's trading at 33,664.87. The
index had gained 213.44 points Wednesday.
   The dollar ended at 142.23 yen, up 0.43 yen from Wednesday's
141.80-yen close. Opening higher at 142.80 yen, the currency
gradually moved downward, ranging between 142.05 yen and 142.90 yen.
   The currency started higher in Tokyo following an overnight rise
in New York despite a lower-than-expected consumer price index
figure released Wednesday, said Hisashi Matsuda, a trader with Daiwa
Bank.
   The U.S. Department of Commerce reported the nation's index for
June rose by 0.2 percentage point, compared with a 0.6-percentage
point increase in May.
   The small increase in the index indicates a slowdown in the
economy, meaning inflationary pressure is easing.
   ``It seems that market players bought the dollar regardless of
the U.S. economic fundamentals,'' Matsuda said. Indicators showing a
slowdown in the economy normally discourage investors from buying
the currency.
   ``Concerns over the upcoming election have made the yen less
attractive, but many investors seem to be buying the dollar not
because they are avoiding the yen temporarily but because they think
it's still profitable to invest in the U.S. currency,'' he said.
   Many believe that the ruling Liberal Democratic Party will lose
badly in the parliamentary election scheduled for Sunday. The LDP
has been hurt by an influence-peddling scandal, an unpopular sales
tax and Prime Minister Sousuke Uno's alleged relationships with paid
mistresses.
   On the stock exchange, the index rose moderately during the
morning session and kept the gains though trading slowed in the
afternoon, dealers said.
   Afternoon trading was directionless, said a dealer with a major
securities firm in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said many market players remained on the sidelines ahead of
Sunday's polls.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 500
million shares, up from Wednesday's 330 million.
   Meanwhile, the Tokyo Stock Exchange announced that it suspended
trading of the shares of Iseki and Co., a manufacturer of farm
machinery, from 1:00 p.m. to the closing of the day at 3:00 p.m.
   The price of Iseki plunged 34 points and more than 2 million
selling orders were filed due to a rumor about the company's capital
reduction, said a TSE official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The TSE suspended transactions in the firm's stock to check the
rumor, which was later denied by company officials, he said.
</TEXT>
