<DOCNO> AP890720-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0845EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Martha'sVineyard     07-20 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Martha's Vineyard,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Martha's Vineyard, Wary of Tourist Glut, Now Faces Slump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VINEYARD HAVEN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rich, the famous and the
beautiful love to summer on Martha's Vineyard. So does everyone else.
   But this year, locals who feared their idyllic island was being
overrun by tourists are complaining of a summer spending slump.
   The Martha's Vineyard Chamber of Commerce blames a weakening
economy that has depressed tourism across New England and a tougher
ferry policy for cars adopted in an effort to control traffic.
   ``Things are off regionally,'' the chamber's executive director,
Angeljean Chiaramida, said Wednesday. ``They're off for us a little
more because of the perception that people are not going to be able
to get here.''
   Receipts at local hotels, restaurants and stores are down at
least 20 percent and for some merchants as much as 40 percent, said
Jane Tomassian, executive director of the Martha's Vineyard
Historical Preservation Society.
   Many hotels post vacancy signs even on Saturday night.
Reservations are not essential at elegant seaside restaurants where
old money and new talent rub shoulders. The real estate market is
sluggish, and some private homes were not rented this summer.
   After area residents complained of endless traffic jams, the
Steamship Authority agreed to stop guaranteeing passage to autos
without reservations. Though 99 percent stand-by motorists are
ferried across within a day, merchants say the lack of a guarantee
deters many travelers.
   ``I think word has filtered out, `Forget going to the Vineyard
unless you made your reservation a year ago because you can't
possibly get your car over,''' Tomassian said.
   A spokesman for the Steamship Authority said the number of
passengers and cars ferried to the island from Jan. 1 to July 4
actually increased slightly compared with last year.
   ``I could speculate and say that while we're carrying people we
don't search them and check them to see how much they're going to
spend,'' spokesman Ray Martin said. ``Maybe people traveling these
days have a tighter budget once they get off the vessel.''
   Conservationists, however, welcome a season of sanity after a
decade of unrelenting growth.
   ``The business people are never satisfied,'' said Eleanor H.
Krantz, head of the Martha's Vineyard Conservation Society. ``They'd
like to have every road filled with people and all the cars and all
the stuff that makes life miserable.''
   Celebrities are certainly not deserting the resort. Already this
summer islanders have spotted the likes of Jackie Onassis, Walter
Cronkite, Beverly Sills, Mike Wallace, Dan Akroyd and James Reston.
Year-round residents include Carly Simon, actress Patricia Neal and
heirs to the Spalding, Corning Glass and Vanderbilt fortunes.
   The slump is bad news for year-round Vineyard residents, who must
earn the bulk of their annual income in 100 summer days, Chiaramida
said. It is also bad news for the Oak Bluffs, Edgartown and Vineyard
Haven, which depend on a 4 percent hotel tax to stay afloat, she
said.
   According to Tomassian, the slump has renewed tensions between
workaday islanders who thrive on tourists and well-to-do summer folk
who fear their T-shirt shops will overrun the island.
   ``I'm afraid that things have become so polarized,'' she said.
``You are either an environmentalist or you are pro-development and
pro-business. Maybe this (slump will) ... make people realize that
what's needed is a happy medium.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1031EST</FILEID>
