<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed today, bogging down
after Wednesday's rally to new post-crash highs.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up .57 to 2,548.98
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 407 up, 523 down and
536 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 28.65 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said traders were proceeding cautiously as Alan
Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, testified before
the House Banking Committee on the Fed's credit policies.
   As expected, Greenspan said the central bank had taken note of a
slowing in the pace of economic activity, and was seeking to avoid
``an unnecessary and destructive recession.''
   However, he also noted that inflation remained clearly above
where the Fed would like to see it.
   Brokers said that gave investors few concrete clues about what
steps the Fed was likely to take next.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph led the active list, up ] at 37\.
The company reported second quarter earnings of 65 cents a share, up
from 55 cents in the like period last year.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks dipped
.01 to 187.11. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .58 at 371.82.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 39.65 to
2,584.41, stretching its gain since the start of the month to 144.35
points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by nearly 5 to 2 on the
NYSE, with 1,065 up, 440 down and 483 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 215.74 million shares, up from 152.35
million in the previous session.
