<DOCNO> AP890720-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Earns-Phone     07-20 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Phone,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Earnings Rise 18 Percent In Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s
second-quarter profit grew 18 percent to a record $699 million,
according to a statement Thursday that showed the company coping
with intensifying competition in long-distance service.
   Separately, Southwestern Bell Corp. said its earnings rose 22.8
percent in the quarter.
   AT&amp;T's sales of services _ primarily long-distance _ climbed 9.8
percent, while sales of products ranging from decorator phones to
million-dollar switches rose 3.8 percent.
   ``It was an excellent quarter all around,'' AT&amp;T Chairman Robert
E. Allen said in a news release.
   AT&amp;T achieved the record earnings in spite of strong gains made
by its nearest rivals in long-distance. Earnings more than doubled
in the latest quarter at both MCI Communications Corp. and United
Telecommunications Inc., the majority owner of US Sprint
Communications Co.
   AT&amp;T said its profit rose to $699 million, or 65 cents a share,
from $594 million, or 55 cents a share, a year earlier. Overall
revenue from services, products and rentals rose 5.2 percent to
$9.26 billion from $8.8 billion.
   For the first half, earnings rose 19.1 percent to $1.29 billion,
or $1.20 a share, from $1.09 billion, or $1.01 a share, a year
earlier. Revenue rose 4.2 percent to $17.9 billion from $17.2
billion.
   St. Louis-based Southwestern Bell, one of AT&amp;T's offspring, said
its earnings rose to $261.5 million, or 87 cents a share, from
$212.9 million, or 71 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose
5.3 percent to $2.14 billion from $2.03 billion.
   For the first half, Southwestern Bell's profit rose 15.9 percent
to $500.3 million, or $1.66 a share, from $431.6 million, or $1.44 a
share. Revenue rose 4.1 percent to $4.2 billion from $4.03 billion.
</TEXT>
