<FIRST>r f PM-BrunswickCuts     07-20 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brunswick Cuts,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brunswick to Cut 4,000 Jobs Nationwide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brunswick Corp. says it will cut the jobs of 4,000
workers _ about 20 percent of its employees _ from its troubled
marine operations because of a sharp drop in demand for pleasure
boats and engines.
   Workers will be laid off at more than 30 plants in 28 states,
Brunswick said Wednesday, announcing an expected 75 percent plunge
in second-quarter earnings from record results of $68.3 million, or
78 cents a share, in the same quarter a year earlier.
   The biggest cuts will be at the Skokie-based company's largest
facility, a Mercury Marine engine plant in Fond du Lac, Wis., where
300 workers will be let go, the company said. About 300 were laid
off there earlier this year.
   Projections for the quarter would mark it as the second
consecutive period of sinking profits at Brunswick because of
problems in the marine group, comprised of Sea Ray, U.S. Marine,
Mercury Marine and Mercury Powerboat divisions.
   Profits dived 68 percent in the first quarter to $17 million.
   At the time, the company blamed higher costs of materials, and
industry observers cited assembly problems and the practice of
selling boats and engines as a unit rather than separately.
   Chairman Jack F. Reichert said the slumping consumer demand in
the second quarter was ``virtually unprecedented'' after record
sales in the first quarter.
   Given the buildup in dealer inventories and the end of the normal
selling season, the company said it can't predict when and at what
level there might be callbacks of laid-off workers.
   Layoffs are to take place over the next two months.
   Brunswick's rival, suburban Waukegan-based Outboard Marine Corp.,
also reported dismal results at the beginning of the month. It
projected a 50 percent drop in its third-quarter earnings, blaming
its results on decreased demand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
