<FIRST>r f PM-Japan-BlackDoll 1stLd-Writethru f0044 07-20 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Black Doll, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0044,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Company To Stop Making Black Doll</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs after last pvs, ``In January...'' with background
on minority population in Japan. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese toymaker said today it will stop selling
a black inflatable doll with big round eyes and a grass skirt, but
the company denied it was acting because critics called the doll
racist.
   Shusuke Kubota, a spokesman for Takara Co., said it also was
discontinuing the use of the doll, named ``Dakko-chan,'' as its
corporate symbol.
   Takara, which also makes ``Transformer'' robots that can be bent
and twisted into other objects, is the second Japanese company in
less than 10 days to say it is abandoning symbols that critics have
called derogatory to blacks.
   Last week, Calpis Food Industry Co. said it was discontinuing a
65-year-old trademark portraying a top-hatted black man sipping a
drink through a straw because some customers had found it
objectionable.
   But Kubota said Takara's decision to discontinue ``Dakko-chan''
had no connection with racial issues.
   ``It's not a black. It represents a Japanese child whose skin has
darkened from being out in the sun all summer long,'' he said.
   Takara has sold 2.4 million of the round-faced dolls, which can
cling to an arm or leg and wink as they move, since they were
introduced in 1960 and became a big hit, Kubota said.
   He said Takara had been planning to eliminate the doll for some
time but didn't have a hit product to replace it with. That changed
with the recent worldwide success of its ``Flower Rock'' toys,
Kubota said.
   The toy consists of a fake flower that wears sunglasses and moves
in its pot when music is played nearby. The new toy has been popular
among adults as well as children, Kubota said.
   The mass-circulation newspaper Mainichi Shimbun said Takara
apparently was concerned that criticism of the black doll in the
United States might hurt ``Flower Rock'' sales.
   In August 1988, U.S. Congressional Black Caucus criticized Japan
for mannequins and dolls which the caucus said stereotyped and
degraded blacks by exaggerating their physical features.
   A department store in Tokyo removed two black mannequins with
distorted features, including huge lips, and Sanrio, a major gift
manufacturer, stopped producing three dolls with black features.
   In October, Kanebo Ltd. stopped making a brand of chewing gum
bearing a face with big round eyes and big lips after receiving a
protest from the African National Congress, an anti-apartheid group.
   In January, a Japanese publisher said it would no longer publish
``Little Black Sambo'' books, one of the best-selling children's
books in Japan for more than 30 years, because of racist
connotations.
   Japan has only about 50,000 non-Asian foreign residents among its
120 million population.
   Government officials, particularly before World War II,
frequently emphasized the country's unity and relative racial purity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0256 </DOCNO>
