<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-20 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>July Soybeans Plummet In Contract's Final Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower
in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade with the
contract for July delivery of soybeans plummeting on its final day
of trading.
   The July soybean contract, which is at the center of a dispute
over a possible market-cornering attempt _ was off 35{ cents at
$6.92 a bushel in the first hour of trading. The contract expires at
noon Central time.
   Analysts said thin trading conditions have made the July contract
extremely volatile. Traders have been exiting the July soybean
market since July 12, following the Board of Trade's emergency order
requiring them to limit their holdings in the July contract.
   Some said it appeared that the Italian grain concern Ferruzzi
Finanziaria S.p.A., the reputed target of the exchange's unusual
order, was switching its large position in the July contract into
the August contract, possibly setting up another confrontation with
the exchange.
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if that were probably the case but I
have no knowledge that that is the case,'' said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.87} a bushel; corn was { cent to
2} cents lower with July at $2.52 a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 4{
cents lower with July at $1.43{ a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents to
35{ cents lower with July at $6.92 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .08 cent higher with August at
72.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchnaged to .23 cent higher
with August at 83.95 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .42 cent
higher with July at 48.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.50 cent to 1.20 cents higher with July at 30.05 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday while pork futures were
mostly higher.
</TEXT>
