<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   07-20 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Judge Makes Ruling Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 7 new grafs to UPDATE with judge approving $75 million
release, reports of Eastern considering sale of Latin American routes.
Picks up 5th graf pvs, Frank Lorenzo...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge today approved the
release of $75 million cash from escrow to Eastern Airlines, which
the strikebound carrier's creditors indicated should help meet the
company's financial needs through the end of the quarter.
   The Miami-based airline initially had asked U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Burton R. Lifland for the release of $100 million from its
creditors, while a committee representing Eastern creditors asked
for only $40 million to be released.
   However, the parties agreed to the $75 million figure and the
judge approved it, with the understanding Eastern could request
additional funds in the future.
   Eastern was expected to file a plan for reorganizing with the
bankruptcy court by the end of the week.
   Separately, published reports indicated Eastern was prepared to
sell Latin American routes and most of its terminal space to
American Airlines because of continuing difficulties in contract
negotiations with its striking pilots' union.
   A memo from Eastern senior vice president Tom Matthews to the Air
Line Pilots Association said the route sale idea would be scrapped
if the company reached a contract agreement with the pilots,
according to today's editions of The Sun-Sentinel in Fort Lauderdale
and The Miami Herald.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said the company would not
comment on the report. Al Becker, spokesman for American, said the
Dallas-based airline has ``done no deals with Eastern,'' but added:
``We are an acquirer. If any airline has assets it wants to sell,
we'll look at them.''
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent Texas Air Corp., and
Eastern President Phil Bakes said in Atlanta on Wednesday that
Eastern's rebuilding is moving along well. They said a measure of
their confidence was evident in their announcement of the aircraft
purchase.
   Under the plan, Texas Air will acquire $2.8 billion worth of
Boeing 737-300 aircraft. The order includes 50 firm purchases and
options to buy 50 more of the jets.
   Sixty of the jets were earmarked for Continental Airlines,
another Texas Air subsidiary, and 40 for Eastern. Lorenzo also
announced a number of other aircraft transactions involving
Continental and Eastern.
   He said the transactions demonstrate confidence that Eastern will
be a thriving operation in the 1990s. The company is in the midst of
a rebuilding program launched during the 4-month-old strike by
Eastern's Machinists union members, pilots and flight attendants.
   ``We've arrived at the point where we're able to make a major
acquisition of this type,'' Lorenzo said.
   However, Ron Cole, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots
Association, called the aircraft purchase a ``joke.''
   ``It's nothing but a stunt to draw attention away from the fact
that Eastern is falling apart,'' Cole said from Tampa, Fla.
   Lorenzo and Bakes announced the aircraft purchase at a news
conference at a downtown Atlanta hotel. On the street outside, about
20 strikers picketed in protest of Lorenzo.
   The two Eastern officials acknowledged that the August expansion
of Eastern's flight schedule will not be as big as originally
announced. But they maintained that the smaller expansion is not a
sign that the rebuilding program is failing.
   Bakes said too much attention is being paid to the actual number
of flights Eastern will have in its August expansion.
   The airline originally promised to have 390 flights a day by Aug.
1, but it said this week some reductions may be necessary. Before
the strike March 4, Eastern had about 1,100 daily flights. It now
has 220.
   Bakes refused to say exactly how many flights will be on the
schedule in August. But, he said, the airline is refusing to take
bookings on flights for which crew training is incomplete.
   Bakes said the company has made progress in revenue, hours flown
and passengers carried. He insisted that Eastern has enough money
from the sale of assets to persevere through the rebuilding period,
though he would not respond when asked how much money the airline
was losing each day.
   The appearance by Lorenzo and Bakes in Atlanta followed reports
that negotiations between the company and the pilots union had
broken down. The officials refused to discuss specifics of the talks
but said they were not making progress.
   ``I can't be here bubbling with optimism about where they (the
talks) are going,'' Lorenzo said.
   Lorenzo also dismissed a plan by Chicago businessman Joseph
Ritchie to buy Eastern as a ``public relations attempt.''
   Ritchie, who has been trying to buy Eastern in alliance with its
unions, said Tuesday he is close to securing a ``highly confident''
letter from his financial adviser, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. In
the letter, Shearson says it would agree to raise $280 million in
debt financing for the Eastern bid, Ritchie told The Wall Street
Journal.
   Ritchie, owner of a commodities trading firm, also said he has
been talking with the AFL-CIO about an additional $200 million for
an employee stock ownership plan.
</TEXT>
