<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-UnionPacific     07-20 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Union Pacific,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Pacific Income From Continuing Operations Up 15 Percent^</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Pacific Corp. Thursday reported a 15
percent gain in second-quarter earnings from operations it still
owns, but a 1 percent drop when including its discontinued refining
interests.
   The company said favorable tax claims and more carloads of
higher-priced commodities helped offset a rise in fuel prices and a
slowdown in grain and aggregate carloads for its Omaha, Neb.-based
railroad.
   The company reported earnings of $152 million, or $1.41 per
share, on revenue of $1.6 billion for the quarter, compared to
income of $153.6 million, or $1.35 per share, on sales of $1.5
billion a year ago.
   Income from continuing operations a year ago totaled $131.7
million, or $1.15 per share.
   For the first half of this year, the company reported a profit on
continuing operations of $290.3 million, or $2.63 a share, on
revenue of $3.2 billion, up 11 percent from last year's $262.6
million, or $2.30 a share, but down slightly from $291.4 million, or
$2.56 a share, including the spun off operations.
</TEXT>
