<FIRST>u f PM-PrintingScam 1stLd-Writethru f0028 07-20 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Printing Scam, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0028,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maine Company Bilked Investors Out of Nearly $30 Million, Feds Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Case Equipment's' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
comment from company owner. Adds one graf with further comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors who believed they could get rich
selling T-shirts and bumper stickers were bilked of up to $30
million by the company that made the printing equipment, the Federal
Trade Commission said.
   The Case Equipment Co. was ordered to temporarily stop making
promises about its ``sublicolor'' system, which actually consists of
old-fashioned mimeograph machines that were sold for $10,000 each.
   A federal judge also ordered Case Equipment's assets frozen while
the FTC tries to recoup money believed to have been lost by people
from all 50 states and Canada.
   The company's scam cheated ``somewhere between 2,000 and 4,000
people, multiplied by a minimum of $10,000 each,'' said FTC attorney
Sara Greenberg. ``We estimated up to $30 million in court papers.''
   Case Equipment's owner, Anthony J. Casella, said this morning
that his equipment works as advertised. He said customers who made
no money using it probably were just not cut out to be in business
for themselves. Casella said he had sold about 3,800 of the machines.
   ``We sell to an awful lot of people who have never been in
business before, and they think the equipment is going to make them
a millionaire, and that's not true,'' Casella told The Associated
Press in a telephone interview. ``People make themselves
millionaires.''
   The FTC last week asked U.S. District Judge Gene Carter to issue
a temporary restraining order against Case Equipment.
   Ms. Greenberg said from her Boston office that FTC lawyers plan
to return to U.S. District Court on Friday to seek a preliminary
injunction that would halt the allegedly fraudulent sales until the
FTC's civil lawsuit against the company is resolved.
   ``It's OK if he sells the equipment,'' she said. ``He just has to
tell the truth about it. We're seeking restitution for customers,
which is plenty. There's your $20 million to $30 million.''
   Case Equipment is also named in a separate lawsuit in U.S.
District Court in which customers from several states say they were
bilked. They are asking for compensatory and punitive damages.
   Case Equipment has operated in Turner since 1984. Prior to that
Casella, also known as A.J. Casella and A.J. Case, abandoned a
similar operation in Massachusetts when that state's attorney
general's office began investigating complaints, Ms. Greenberg said.
   She said potential investors were lured to Case Equipment by
national magazine advertisements, flown into Portland International
Jetport and picked up in limousines that took them to Case
Equipment's showroom in Turner.
   They were shown impressive samples of printing and given a sales
pitch that said making money with the ``sublicolor'' system would be
easy, and that Case Equipment had service centers around the country
and long lists of potential customers, Ms. Greenberg said. The
customers' living expenses were paid during their visits.
   ``It's a wine 'em and dine 'em sort of operation, and the people
are impressed,'' Ms. Greenberg said. ``Even people who had some
knowledge of the printing industry were taken in. They have told
customers stories about how a 15-year-old could use it. They said
anyone can use it.''
   But once people bought the Case Equipment machinery, they were
ignored and given little training in using it, FTC documents say.
The machinery could not be operated by untrained workers and
produced sloppy printing without regular maintenance, the FTC said.
   The company falsely claimed to have service centers all over the
nation, when it had none, the FTC said.
   ``Consumers not only lose their initial $10,000-plus investment,
they spend significant additional sums and valuable time in vain
trying to get the equipment to function,'' the FTC said.
   The commission accuses Case Equipment of cheating ``mostly
working people looking to start or expand their own small business
ventures. However, the only ones to profit have been Case and
Casella.''
   Casella said the companies that make and distribute his equipment
provide numerous service centers. He said his company provides food
and lodging to potential customers to make sure they come see what
they are buying. He said he insists buyers attend training sessions
and sign a form saying they are trained in the use of the sublicolor
and satisfied with its performance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
