<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-AlliedSignal     07-20 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Allied Signal,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allied-Signal Reports Rise in Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allied-Signal Inc. reported a 30
percent rise in second-quarter earnings, reflecting strength in the
company's aerospace sector.
   For the three-month period ended June 30, the advanced technology
company said its net income totaled $166 million, or $1.11 per
share, compared with $128 million, or 85 cents a share, in the same
1988 period.
   Included in 1989 second-quarter results was a one-time gain of
$23 million, or 16 cents a share, stemming from an insurance
settlement awarded to Union Texas Petroleum Holdings, Inc. in which
Allied has a 40 percent equity interest.
   Excluding the one-time gain, Allied-Signal's net income for the
quarter was $143 million, or 95 cents a share, up 12 percent.
   Sales for the second quarter edged up to $3.1 billion from $3
billion in the 1988 period, Allied said.
   Edward L. Hennessy Jr., Allied-Signal chairman, said the
company's strong performance was aided by the improved showing of
the company's operating units, particularly its aerospace sector.
   ``Earnings are expected to remain strong through the second half
of 1989 as we continue to concentrate on improving our operating
performance,'' Hennessy said.
   Allied-Signal is an advanced technology company with businesses
in aerospace, automotive products and engineered material.
   For the first half of 1989, the company's earnings grew 22
percent to $292 million, or $1.96 a share, compared with $240
million, or $1.60 a share, in the first half of 1988.
   Revenue in the first half totaled $6.06 billion, nearly unchanged
from $6.04 billion in the year-earlier period.
</TEXT>
