<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Textron     07-20 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Textron,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Textron Earnings Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textron Corp. said Thursday its
second-quarter earnings declined nearly 14 percent, reflecting an
arbitrator's decision that Textron owed money to Iran and because of
weakness in its aerospace division.
   The diversified company said it had income of $59.3 million, or
67 cents per share, compared with $68.9 million, or 78 cents per
share, in the 1988 quarter. Revenue was $1.85 billion, compared with
$1.79 billion a year earlier.
   Earnings were depressed by an arbitrator's ruling that Textron
owed Iran $9.5 million under an agreement to jointly produce
helicopters, said company spokesman Raymond W. Caine Jr.
   Iran had paid for materials in 1978, but they had not been
shipped before Textron was prohibited by the U.S. government from
providing any further supplies to Iran, he said.
   The aerospace division's earnings decreased nearly $2.5 million,
primarily because of increased costs on fixed-price development
programs for the V-22 Osprey and on some rocket and smart-bomb
systems, Caine said. That was offset by an increase of almost $10
million in earnings for financial services.
   Textron also recorded a $14 million increase in interest expense,
mostly from its acquisition of Avdel PLC, a British fastener
manufacturer. Textron has been unable to complete the acquisition
and absorb the earnings, however, because of Federal Trade
Commission opposition.
   Textron has interests in a number of industries including
aerospace technology, commercial products and financial services.
</TEXT>
