<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-20 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Close Higher, Corn and Soybeans Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices closed higher while corn and
soybean futures finished mostly lower Thursday on the Chicago Board
of Trade, where attention was focused on the expiration of the July
soybean contract.
   Trading in soybeans for July delivery ended at 12:01 p.m. central
time after a spurt of selling that pushed the contract's price down
to $6.88{ a bushel, 39 cents below Wednesday's settlement price.
   Analysts said thin trading conditions made the July soybean
contract extremely volatile. Traders had been exiting that market
since July 11, when the Board of Trade issued an emergency order
requiring them to limit their holdings in the July contract.
   Some said it appeared that the Italian grain concern Ferruzzi
Finanziaria S.p.A., the reputed target of the exchange's unusual
order, had switched its large July position into the August
contract, possibly setting up another confrontation with the
exchange.
   Trading companies believed to be representing Ferruzzi were large
sellers in the minutes before the July contract expired, traders
said.
   The wheat market gained support from expectations of new export
business and perceptions that the market has reached its seasonal
bottom, said Katharina Zimmer, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc.
   The corn and soybean markets were pressured by rain in the
Midwest in addition to the pronounced weakness in the expiring July
contracts.
   July wheat expired } cent higher at $3.90} a bushel; July corn
expired 6} cents lower at $2.47{ a bushel; July oats expired 3 cents
lower at $1.43{ a bushel.
   At the close, other wheat contracts were 3 cents to 7{ cents
higher with September at $3.90} a bushel; corn was 2\ cents lower to
{ cent higher with September at $2.39} a bushel; oats were 2{ cents
to 3 cents lower with September at $1.51\ a bushel; soybeans were 6{
cents lower to 4} cents higher with August at $6.81 a bushel.
</TEXT>
