<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2110EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-WORSale     07-20 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WOR Sale,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Approves Sale of NY Radio Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission said
Thursday it has approved a $25.5 million sale of New York talk
radio station WOR-AM to Buckley-WOR Broadcasting Corp.
   Under the FCC-approved settlement, the seller, RKO General Inc.,
would receive only 65 percent of the proceeds, with the remainder
going to six other applicants who had challenged the fitness of RKO
and its parent, GenCorp. of Fairlawn, Ohio, to hold the WOR license.
   The other applicants were: South Jersey Radio Inc. of Atlantic
City, N.J.; Freedom Broadcasting Corp. of Riverside, R.I.; Women
Owning Radio Inc., whose principals include broadcaster Gail Trell
Barker and TV-radio personality Arlene Francis; COZZIN
Communications Corp. of Cleveland, which numbers comedian-actor
Bill Cosby among its stockholders; S-G Communications of Atlanta;
and Magna Media Corp.
   The FCC, in a 2-1 decision on July 14 that was released
Thursday, said RKO's license renewal application would be dismissed
and RKO will transfer the station to S-G Communications. S-G will
transfer the license to an RKO subsidiary, GRADH-107, which in turn
will transfer the license to Buckley upon consummation of the
settlement.
   The Greenwich, Conn.-based Buckley will pay RKO $24 million, of
which RKO will pay $7.425 million to the other applicants. Buckley
also will pay $1.5 million, in addition to the $24 million,
directly to principals of the competing applicants.
   The FCC said ``RKO's receipt of less than full market value for
the station would serve as an effective deterrent against license
misconduct.''
   The sale was the latest step in the FCC-ordered dismantling of
the RKO network, which began in the 1960s when challenges were
filed to RKO's fitness to operate its stations.
   In a 1980 ruling that stripped RKO of one TV license, the FCC
noted that GenCorp, the former General Tire &amp; Rubber Co., had been
accused of improper domestic political contributions and of bribery
overseas.
   The FCC has approved similar sales agreements for WOR's sister
station, WRKS-FM, for $50 million; KHJ-TV and KRTH-AM-FM, Los
Angeles, $320 million and $86.6 million, respectively; plus
WHBQ-AM, Memphis; WGMS-AM, Bethesda, Md.; WGMS-FM, Washington; and
WRKO-AM-FM, Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
