<FILEID>AP-PX-07-20-89 2113EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-ConsumerProducts 1stLd-Writethru   07-20 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Consumer Products, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0131,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bristol-Myers, Colgate-Palmolive Post Double-Digit Quarterly Income
Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES thruout with American Brands results.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bristol-Myers Co. and Colgate-Palmolive Co. Thursday reported
they had double-digit income growth in the second quarter despite
suffering adverse consequences from the dollar's strength.
   American Brands Inc., meanwhile, reported its net income fell 22
percent despite a strong performance by its tobacco units.
   Bristol-Myers, maker of medicines, toiletries and household
products, posted an 11.6 percent profit increase in the quarter
ended June 30. After-tax income rose to $212.51 million, or 74
cents a share, from $190.48 million, or 66 cents a shares, in
1988's second quarter.
   Sales came to $1.53 billion vs. last year's $1.46 billion, an
increase of about 5 percent.
   Colgate-Palmolive, a major manufacturer of consumer products
ranging from soap to pet food, said its second-quarter net income
increased 12.4 percent to $73.6 million, or $1.06 a share, from
$65.5 million, or 96 cents a share, in the second 1988 quarter.
Sales rose about 9 percent to $1.29 billion from $1.19 billion.
   American Brands, whose products include Lucky Strike cigarettes
and Jim Beam alcoholic beverages, said its profit sank to $120.2
million, or $1.25 a share, from $154.7 million, or $1.57 a share,
in the year-ago quarter. Revenue edged up 0.1 percent to $2.722
billion, from $2.718 billion.
   American Brands, based in Greenwich, Conn., said its 1988
results included a $46 million gain from discontinued operations.
   Richard L. Gelb, Bristol-Myers' chairman, said international
sales edged up just 1 percent while, domestically, sales were up 7
percent. Changes in the dollar's value against other major
currencies during the quarter cut international sales by an
estimated 6 percent, Gelb said.
   For the first half of the year, Bristol-Myers earned $449.6
million, or $1.56 a share, up 12.1 percent from $401.1 million, or
$1.39 a share, a year earlier. Sales amounted to $3.14 billion, up
about 5 percent from $2.98 billion in the first six months of 1988.
   Reuben Mark, Colgate-Palmolive's chairman, president and chief
executive officer, said the financial improvement reflected
continuing momentum in international operations and the Hill's Pet
Products division.
   The second-quarter earning included $6.5 million, or 9 cents a
share, from the sale of land in England. This real estate gain
partially offsetthe negative impact of a higher dollar.
   Colgate-Palmolive said in a news release that the dollar's
strength, combined with economic difficulties in Venezuela and
currency translation losses in other hyperinflationary countries,
reduced second-quarter income by about $13 million, after taxes.
   For the first six months of this year, Colgate-Palmolive earned
$140.8 million, or $2.04 a share, up 7.6 percent from $130.9
million, or $1.91 a share, in the first half of 1988. Sales grew
about 7 percent to $2.5 billion from $2.3 billion.
   Both Colgate-Palmolive and Bristol-Myers have their corporate
headquarters in New York.
   Some of Colgate-Palmolive's well-known brands include Ajax
cleanser, Fab laundry detergent and Irish Spring soap.
   Among Bristol-Myers' brands are Bufferin and Excedrin pain
relievers, Windex window cleaner and Drano drain de-clogger.
   For the first half of 1989, American Brands had net income of
$292.4 million, or $3.05 a share, down 4 percent from $305.2
million, or $2.97 a share, in the comparable 1988 period.
   Revenue in the fist six months was $5.97 billion, up 2 percent
from $5.8 billion in 1988.
   William J. Alley, American Brands chairman, said tobacco
operations were strong both at home and abroad despite a strong
dollar, which makes U.S. products more expensive overseas.
   Domestically, American Tobacco Co. had record results in the
quarter with operating income up 5 percent to $131 million.
International operating income rose 46 percent to $63 million.
   It said its Jim Beam brands of liquor had record profits of $22
million, up 8 percent for the quarter.
   American Brands' products include Carlton, Lucky Strike and Pall
Mall cigarettes; Jim Beam bourbon and Gilbey's gin; Master Lockand
other hardware; life insurance, housewares and sports products.
</TEXT>
