<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Banks     07-20 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>BankAmerica, Bank of Boston Earnings Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp.'s turnaround continued in the second quarter
as earnings jumped 88 percent over the same 1988 period, the
company said Thursday. Bank of Boston Corp. also reported a profit
rise.
   The parent of Bank of America, the nation's second-largest bank,
reported net income of $304 million, or $1.50 a share, in the
quarter ending June 30, up from $162 million, or 85 cents a share,
in the same period last year.
   BankAmerica Chairman A.W. Clausen said in a statement the
results reflected strength in key areas, including expansion of
domestic loans and deposits, particularly in consumer loan and
mortgage portfolios.
   Earnings for the first six months of 1989 were $579 million, or
$2.88 per common share, up 114 percent from $271 million, or $1.41
per common share, in the same period last year.
   Two years ago, San Francisco-based BankAmerica lost $955 million
but bounced back in 1988 to report $726 million profit.
   BankAmerica's net interest income for the second quarter totaled
$1.03 billion, up from $806 million in the same 1988 period.
Non-interest income rose slightly, to $453 million from $448
million.
   Bank of Boston said its second-quarter profit rose 29 percent to
$98 million from $76 million in the same 1988 period. Per-share
profit increased to $1.34 from $1.10.
   For the first half of 1989, Bank of Boston reported net income
of $187 million, or $2.57 a share, up 17 percent from $160 million,
or $2.34 a share, a year ago.
   Bank of Boston Chairman Ira Stepanian said the quarterly rise
came ``despite the impact of higher levels nonperforming assets.''
The bank's domestic nonperforming assets in real estate rose by
about $195 million because of weakening in the industry.
   The bank also reported a $2.6 million loss from trading profits
and commissions, compared with profits of $1.5 million in the
second quarter last year.
   H.F. Ahmanson &amp; Co., parent of Home Savings of America, reported
second- quarter earnings of $39.6 million, or 40 cents a share, an
18.9 percent drop from $48.8 million, or 49 cents a share in the
same 1988 quarter.
   Los Angeles-based H.F. Ahmanson attributed the decline a sharp
drop in net gains from loan sales, to $750,000 from $9 million in
the second quarter last year.
</TEXT>
