<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-PPG     07-20 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-PPG,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quarterly Net Drops Nearly 5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PPG Industries Inc. said Thursday weakness in
its glass business and unfavorable currency exchange rates led to a
4.8 percent drop in second-quarter profit.
   The company earned $127.3 million, or $1.13 per share, in the
second quarter compared with $133.8 million, or $1.22 per share, a
year earlier.
   Sales for the comparable quarters edged higher by 2.7 percent
from $1.45 billion to $1.49 billion.
   ``Despite the slowing North American economy, we are optimistic
that 1989 will rank among PPG's best years for both sales and
earnings,'' Chairman Vincent A. Sarni said in a statement.
   First-half net earnings totaled $257.1 million, or $2.28 per
share, up 1.9 percent from $252.4 million, or $2.29 per share, a
year earlier.
   Six-month sales rose 4.6 percent from $2.82 billion to $2.95
billion.
   PPG said it benefited in the second quarter from continued
strong sales of fiber glass products and auto replacement glass. It
was hurt, however, by high product development costs and softness
in North American markets.
   New production capacity in the North American and European flat
glass industry lowered sales volumes for some products, PPG said.
   Sales of PPG's paints and other coatings were strong worldwide.
   In its chemicals business, chlor-alkali sales volumes and prices
remained strong, but markets showed weakness for chlorine
derivatives.
</TEXT>
