<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     07-20 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Multimedia Reports Higher Earnings in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimedia Inc. said Thursday its
second-quarter earnings rose 31 percent, spurred by the success of
television programming such as the Phil Donahue and Sally Jessy
Raphael shows.
   Revenues rose 6 percent overall, including gains in its
newspaper, broadcasting, cable and entertainment divisions, the
company said.
   Multimedia reported earnings of $10.8 million, or 87 cents a
share, on revenues of $121 million for the quarter ending June 30.
During the same period in 1988, the company earned $8.2 million, or
67 cents a share, on revenues of $114.3 million.
   Revenues from the entertainment division rose 21 percent, to
$19.2 million, up from $15.8 million. The three other divisions
each reported revenues increases of less than 10 percent.
   The broadcasting division accounted for $39.5 million of the
company's second-quarter revenues. Newspapers brought in $35
million and cablevision $19.2 million.
   First-half earnings climbed 65 percent from $9.3 million, or 77
cents a share, to $15.4 million, or $1.24 a share. Revenues rose 6
percent in the first six months from $214.3 million to $227.3
million.
   ``The quarter and the first six months were as expected,'' said
Walter E. Bartlett, president and chief executive officer.
``Newspapers were weak in retail advertising. Broadcasting was
good, fortunately, because of our two major NBC properties in St.
Louis and Cincinnati.
   ``Cable was very strong and entertainment was very strong due to
the continued success of Donahue and the expansion of the Sally
Jessy Raphael show to more markets and to an hour in length.''
   The gain in first-half earnings was the result of higher revenue
and less interest payments on a recapitalization project that began
in 1985, Bartlett said in a statement.
   Multimedia is a mediacommunications company that publishes 14
daily and 40 non-daily newspapers. It also owns and operates four
television and seven radio stations, more than 100 cable franchises
in four states and produces and syndicates television programming,
including the Phil Donahue and Sally Jessy Raphael shows.
</TEXT>
