<FIRST>r f BC-Campeau     07-20 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Campeau,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campeau Says It Has No Acquisitions Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp., a Canadian holding company of real
estate and retail interests in Canada and the United States, plans
to concentrate on its existing businesses and has no acquisition
plans, Campeau's chairman and chief executive said Thursday.
   ``We have no intention of seeking further acquisitions,'' Robert
Campeau said at the annual shareholders' meeting. ``We're going to
keep our noses to the grindstone'' and focus on existing operations.
   Campeau's past acquisition campaign included the hostile $6.7
billion takeover of Federated Departments Stores Inc. last spring.
   Federated, which operates Abraham and Straus, Bloomingdale's,
Burdines and other chain stores, has become part of Campeau's
department stores group.
   Also within the group is Allied Stores Corp., which Campeau
acquired in 1986 for $3.4 billion. Allied operates 130 department
stores in 16 states under the Jordan Marsh, Stern's, Maas-Jordan
Marsh Florida and The Bon Marche names.
   Both Allied and Federated have headquarters in Cincinnati.
   At the meeting in Toronto, Campeau forecast sales for the
current year of about 12.5 billion Canadian dollars, up from about
10.3 billion Canadian dollars in the previous year.
   He didn't present the projection in U.S. dollars even though the
company regularly reports its financial results in U.S. dollars.
   The company's annual report for the year ended Jan. 31, 1989
showed revenue from continuing operations totaled $8.67 billion,
boosted by the acquisition of Federated and Ralphs Grocery Co.,
compared to $3.53 billion in the 13 months ended a year before.
   Campeau did not provide an estimate for this year's earnings at
the meeting.
   The Toronto-based corporation lost $34 million in its past
fiscal year, an improvement from a loss of $196 million in the 13
months ended Jan. 31, 1988.
   In separate remarks, Ronald Tysoe, Campeau's president and chief
operating officer, said Campeau's Canadian division plans to sell
up to 45 properties, producing gross proceeds of about $500
million. The cash proceeds from the sales could come to about $250
million.
</TEXT>
