<FIRST>r f AM-Portugal-Privatization     07-20 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Portugal-Privatization,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Unveils Privatization Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced plans Thursday
to sell to the public stakes in three state companies, including
the country's leading commercial bank, as part of a long-term
economic liberalization program.
   A government statement said Banco Portugues do Atlantico will
have 49 percent of its capital placed on the market. He said the
state-run cement giant Cimpor and the Centralcer brewery will be
partially privatized.
   Since election in July 1987, Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva
has launched series of free-market measures to relax state control.
   The latest privatization plans follow the successful sale
earlier this month of 49 percent of the government's shares in
Banco Totta e Acores, a leading public bank, and April's partial
privatization of the brewery UNICER.
   Like previous transactions, the sales revealed Thursday will be
limited to 49 percent of company's capital.
   However, government spokesman Fernando Nogueira said new
legislation slated to permit complete privatizations was being
prepared, the Portuguese newsagency Lusa reported.
   The government statement said BPA and Centralcer were likely to
be fully privatized eventually, although the government would
maintain a stake in Cimpor ``due to the nature of its activity and
its importance in the national economy.''
</TEXT>
