<FIRST>r f BC-USAToday-Soviet     07-20 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-USA Today-Soviet,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>USA Today To Be Distributed in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gannett Co. said Thursday it will begin
distributing its USA Today newspaper in the Soviet Union within a
month.
   Gannett, publisher of USA Today, said about 200 copies of the
newspaper's international edition will be distributed in Moscow and
Leningrad by Sovaminco, a joint U.S.-Soviet venture.
   The newspaper will cost either $2 or 2 rubles, depending on
which currency a vendor accepts.
   Gannett International President David Mazzarella said the
newspaper initially will be sold in hotels by Sovaminco, which
imports and sells foreign language books and holds licenses to open
bookstores.
   ``We also expect that Sovaminco will make it available through
their own devices to other sales points, meaning to newsstands run
by other people,'' he said.
   Mazzarella said the Soviet venture is designed for American
tourists, business officials and temporary residents, but Gannett
hopes the newspaper also will be read by Soviet citizens.
   ``I would hope there's some interest there on the part of
Soviets in developments in the United States,'' he said. ``Our
target is those who have a strong interest in the United States.''
   About 50,000 copies of USA Today's international newspaper are
distributed in more than 80 countries, he said.
   Gannett said in a statement that it had distributed the
newspaper in China from 1986 but the government cut off supplies
last week.
   Other English-language publications, including the International
Herald Tribune and Time magazine, already are sold in the Soviet
Union.
</TEXT>
