<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   07-20 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sudden selloff near the close pushed stock
prices lower Thursday, wiping out an early gain that carried the
Dow Jones industrial average briefly past 2,600 for the first time
since the fall of 1987.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up about 30 points at
its midsession peak, closed with an 8.92 loss at 2,575.49.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
646 up, 871 down and 482 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 204.59 million
shares, against 215.74 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 241.87 million shares.
   Analysts said the late decline stemmed in part from selling by
professional traders engaged in computer program strategies
involving options and index futures contracts, some of which expire
after the close on Friday.
   They also said investors seemed to back away from an initially
enthusiastic response to testimony by Alan Greenspan, chairman of
the Federal Reserve Board, before the House Banking Committee on
the Fed's credit policies.
   Greenspan said the central bank had taken note of a slowing in
the pace of economic activity, and was seeking to avoid ``an
unnecessary and destructive recession.''
   However, he also noted that inflation remained clearly above
where the Fed would like to see it.
   Brokers said Greenspan's comments squared with the recent belief
that the Fed was proceeding gradually to try to steer the economy
toward a ``soft landing'' that could set the stage for renewed
growth.
   But they added that his testimony was typically noncommital,
leaving open the question of whether and when the Fed might take
further steps toward easier credit.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph led the active list and rose \ to
37[. The company reported second quarter earnings of 65 cents a
share, up from 55 cents in the like period last year.
   Losers among the blue chips included General Electric, down { at
55}; Procter &amp; Gamble, down ~ at 116\; Philip Morris, down { at
146{; USX, down \ at 35|, and International Business Machines, down
1| at 112}.
   Some brokerage stocks gained ground, aided by recent increases
in stock trading volume and improving industry earnings. Shearson
Lehman Hutton rose 1] to 21~; Merrill Lynch \ to 33[; Advest ~ to
7~, and Legg Mason ~ to 15[.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $17.43 billion, or 0.53
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .99 to 186.11.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index slumped 2.26 to 381.96, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was down 2.22 at 333.51.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
1.99 to 449.24. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 371.19, down 1.21.
