<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1816EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-20 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pork Belly Futures Soar On Signs Of Stronger Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pork belly futures prices soared Thursday by as much as 2 cents
a pound, the permitted daily limit on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, on signs that lower bacon prices may finally be
stimulating demand for the sizeable supplies of pork bellies in
cold storage.
   Hog futures prices also rose while cattle futures were mixed.
   On other markets, orange juice futures fell sharply for the
fifth straight day; grains and soybeans finished mixed as the July
contracts expired; precious metals erased some of Wednesday's
losses; and energy futures advanced.
   Frozen pork bellies settled 1.53 cents to 2 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in July at 30.55 cents a pound; hogs were
.03 cent lower to .98 cent higher with July at 49 cents a pound;
live cattle were unchanged to .20 cent higher with August at 72.75
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .07 cent higher
with August at 83.72 cents a pound.
   The pork-belly market turned in its strongest performance in
more than six weeks in a delayed reponse to Tuesday's weekly
exchange report on pork-belly stocks in U.S. commercial freezers
outside of Chicago.
   The report showed a net out-movement of nearly 5.4 million
pounds last week compared to 3.9 million pounds for the same period
a year ago.
   Supplies of frozen pork bellies, the part of the pig from which
bacon is made, are at near-record levels. Stocks normally decline
during the summer, due to a seasonal drop in hog slaughters, but
reports since spring have failed to confirm the development of the
trend this year.
   The slack demand has prompted grocers to sharply cut retail
prices for bacon, which has been running 8 percent to 20 percent
below last year for most of the summer, said Tom Morgan, president
of Sterling Research Corp. of Arlington Heights, Ill.
   ``Maybe we're beginning to see that reflected in the demand,''
he said.
   A monthly Agriculture Department report scheduled for release
after the close on Friday is expected to again show near-record
supplies of frozen bellies nationwide, but Morgan said the
importance of that report to traders has been diminished.
   ``Their views are going to be tempered because of the recent
out-movement'' reported on Tuesday, he said.
   Orange juice futures prices fell the 5-cents-a-pound daily limit
on the New York Cotton Exchange on perceptions that large supplies
of Brazilian juice will soon hit the market.
   Frozen concentrated orange juice settled 3.25 cents to 5 cents
lower with September at $1.546 a pound.
   Wheat futures prices closed higher while corn and soybean
futures finished mostly lower Thursday on the Chicago Board of
Trade, where much attention was focused on the expiration of the
July soybean contract.
   Trading in soybeans for July delivery ended at 12:01 p.m.
Central time after a spurt of selling that pushed the contract's
price down to $6.88{ a bushel, 39 cents below Wednesday's
settlement price.
   Analysts said thin trading conditions made the July soybean
contract extremely volatile. Traders had been exiting that market
since July 11, when the Board of Trade issued an emergency order
requiring them to limit their holdings in the July contract.
   July wheat expired } cent higher at $3.90} a bushel; July corn
expired 6} cents lower at $2.47{ a bushel; July oats expired 3
cents lower at $1.43{ a bushel.
   Wheat settled 3 cents to 6{ cents higher with September at
$3.97} a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to { cent higher with
September at $2.40 a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 3 cents lower
with September at $1.51\ a bushel; soybeans were 6\ cents lower to
4{ cents higher with August at $6.81\ a bushel.
   Gold and silver rebounded on New York's Commodity Exchange in
reaction to a weaker dollar, partially erasing Wednesday's losses.
   Gold settled $2.90 to $3.10 higher with August at $372.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 1.4 cents to 2.8 cents higher with July at $5.181
a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices advanced on the New York Mercantile
Exchange in a technically inspired rally following a sharp decline
on Wednesday.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 23 cents
higher with August at $19.90 a barrel; heating oil was .98 cent to
1.56 cents higher with August at 51.83 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .89 cent lower to .56 cent higher with August at 53.80
cents a gallon.
