<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-20 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heating Oil Prices Higher, Other Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale home heating oil prices rose Thursday
amid expectations of energy supply shortages overseas due to the
labor and ethnic unrest in the Soviet Union. Crude oil and unleaded
gasoline futures were mixed.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, No.2 heating oil for August
delivery rose 1.46 cents to 51.83 cents a gallon, after falling
0.13 cent on Wednesday.
   Contracts for heating oil delivery in more distant months also
posted gains and the September contract rose 1.56 cents, settling
at 52.57 cents a gallon.
   Among other refined products traded on the exchange, the August
contract of unleaded gasoline declined 0.59 cent to 54.10 cents a
gallon, adding to Wednesday's drop of 1.37 cents.
   Other unleaded gasoline contract months settled with moderate
gains and losses, with the September contract falling 0.29 cent to
53.08 cents a gallon.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for August delivery settled 5
cents higher at $19.90 per 42-gallon barrel on the last trading day
for that contract. The September contract for the benchmark grade
of U.S. crude oil rose 13 cents to $19.68 a barrel.
   Evan Baron, of the energy group at Elders Futures Inc., said
continuing troubles in the Soviet Union which have disrupted
production in various industries ``is creating tight supplies in
European heating oil markets right now and that, in turn, is
affecting our markets.''
   He said there have been reports that scheduled oil shipments
from the Soviet Union have not moved.
   News that saboteurs in the country's Abkhazia region have
damaged the electric power system added to speculation that the
Soviet Union will need to keep more of its oil at home to
compensate for energy shortages due to strikes at coal mines.
</TEXT>
