<FIRST>u f AM-WhiteCollarCrime Bjt   07-20 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White Collar Crime, Bjt,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bevill, Bresler Felons Rebuild Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man helps run a restaurant on the Jersey
shore after cleaning toilets in jail. Another solicited companies
as a consultant on business ethics. A third maintains a 4.0 grade
point average studying for an MBA at a prison camp.
   A fourth just sold his horse transporting business and the
fifth, serving a six-year prison term, is scheduled to be sentenced
Monday for lying on the witness stand at trial.
   Those are the lives of five former wealthy exectives of Bevill,
Bresler &amp; Schulman Inc., once New Jersey's largest brokerage house.
All have gone to jail for crimes in connection with the April 1985
collapse of the Livingston firm and related entities.
   The collapse has cost customers _ which include more than 75
financial institutions, municipalities and individuals in 20 states
_ more than $100 million.
   Authorities have said the executives siphoned off $15 million
for personal use.
   Half-million-dollar homes, jewelry, boats, investments, furs,
Mercedes-Benz autos belonging to the defendants are long gone now,
seized by trustees overseeing the former firm's assets.
   Robert L. Bevill, 46, was the firm's chairman. He is scheduled
for release July 27 from a federal prison camp at Maxwell Air Force
Base in Montgomery, Ala. Bevill will have served slightly more than
21 months of a sentence that began on Black Monday, the Oct. 19,
1987, stock market crash.
   ``I feel guilty, I feel shameful _ wish I could make it go
away,'' Bevill said in a telephone interview from prison. Bevill's
grade-point average is a perfect 4.0 in business courses from Troy
State University.
   He said he is considering taking a job managing apartment
complexes in Tennessee and Alabama owned by his brother.
   John D. Rooney, the former treasurer at Bevill, Bresler, cleaned
bathrooms at the federal prison in Allenwood, Pa., during his
1{-year prison term. The 43-year-old Rooney called the experience
``very humbling'' in a letter to U.S. District Judge Dickinson R.
Debevoise.
   Several miles from the Monmouth Beach condominium he once owned,
Rooney now works as as a bookkeeper at a restaurant in which his
mother made an investment. He prefers not to discuss his life or
the case in detail.
   ``I feel better about things,'' Rooney said. ``I'm trying to
start my life all over again. It's behind me.''
   He is working on a unique part of the sentence imposed by
Debevoise on the four defendants who pleaded guilty and cooperated
with the government: to read six books about ``suffering and
afflicted'' people and write reports in the form of a syllabus and
description of a possible college course on social ethics.
   Stuart Gottlieb, a former senior vice president at the firm, was
sentenced to nine months in prison. He is trying to parlay the
book-reading assignment into a new business _ using his status as a
white-collar criminal to solicit corporations for a course or
manual on business ethics.
   ``I am now extremely devoted to attempting to prevent others,
because of unethical behaviour, from placing themselves, their
firms or society at large, at risk,'' Gottlieb, 42, says in his
solicitation letter.
   Gottlieb, living in a rented condomimium in Pluckemin, would
only say in an interview, ``It's behind me. It's over.''
   Gottlieb for a time worked at a video rental store, according to
assistant U.S. Attorney Paul Weissman. The store was transferred to
his wife's name, but was padlocked by the Morris County sheriff and
its assets sold at auction March 27 after a video distributor
obtained a judgment for unpaid debts.
   Robert S. Levine, 46, former executive vice president, said he
sold his Jackson horse carrying business in the past several weeks
because ``it just wasn't worthwhile.'' The trustee settlement had
left him and his family about $770,000 in assets. At Allenwood,
where he served three months, Levine washed dishes.
   Gilbert C. Schulman, 42, the firm's former president, was
convicted, sentenced to eight years and had the term reduced to
six. He pleaded guilty to a later charge of giving perjured
testimony. He is to be sentenced by Debevoise on Monday.
   Schulman's later cooperation helped bring about the guilty plea
of Robert A. Rough, a former director of the Federal Reserve Bank
of New York, to charges of leaking secret interest rate data to the
Bevill, Bresler principals.
   Schulman's wife Marsha said in a letter to Debevoise that she
works 16 hours a day running an excavation and construction
business and cares for the couple's five children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
