<DOCNO> AP890720-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1848EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CFTCHearing 1stLd-Writethru   07-20 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CFTC Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0167,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBOT Chairman Defends Emergency Order on Soybeans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Ledes with 13 new grafs to update with Chicago Board of Trade
chairman's testimony, picks up with 7th graf pvs: CFTC Chairwoman ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade took its emergency
action in the soybean futures market last week after federal
regulators took steps against a single concern, the CBOT's chairman
testified Thursday.
   Chairman Karsten Mahlman would not identify the ``major
participant,'' believed to be Italian agribusiness giant Feruzzi
SpA, which took a massive position in July soybean futures.
   Mahlman said the CBOT board voted the emergency order, which
required liquidation of large positions in the July bean futures
market, after determining that only one board member, who was
excused from the meeting and did not vote, owned or controlled
positions in July soybeans.
   ``We hope our strong action in July will not be necessary in
August,'' Mahlman told reporters after testifying before a House
subcommittee.
   Although he conceded, under repeated questioning by Rep. David
R. Nagle, D-Iowa, that several other board members were employed by
companies that controlled or served customers that controlled
soybean positions, Mahlman defended the CBOT's action.
   Outside the hearing room, he said: ``I think we have
dramatically enhanced the credibility of the board.''
   Mahlman said eliminating all board members with employer links
to futures positions would force about one-third of them to resign.
   Mahlman's version of the emergency order differed from that
given by federal regulators earlier this week.
   The hearings are being conducted on proposed legislation that
would tighten anti-fraud rules and also reauthorize the agency that
regulates futures markets, the Commodity Futures Trading Commission.
   In earlier testimony, the head of another Chicago exchange said
Congress should not ban the controversial practice of dual trading
_ where brokers trade for themselves and their customers.
   Critics say dual trading allows brokers to take care of their
own needs first, but banning it outright ``would be dangerous,''
said Leo Melamed, chairman of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange's
executive committee.
   Mahlman concurred with that position. In a prepared statement
submitted to the subcommittee, Mahlman, chairman of the world's
oldest and largest futures exchange, also opposed a ban on dual
trading, saying it ``will adversely affect the liquidity of futures
markets, particularly agricultural markets, by increasing the cost
of doing business.''
   The CBOT's emergency order last week, and federal regulators'
reaction to the order was a hot topic during a subcommittee session
on Tuesday.
   CFTC Chairwoman Wendy Gramm exasperated committee members
Tuesday with her cautious answers to questions about the agency's
consulting role in the Chicago soybean situation.
   Ms. Gramm, who also said more study was needed before dual
trading was banned, said her agency was reviewing the CBOT's
emergency order but neither directly approved or disapproved the
action.
   Subcommittee Chairman Glenn English, D-Okla., alluded to his
frustration with the CFTC at the start of the second session when
he said the congressmen present ``want to get complete answers
instead of the ones they got Tuesday.''
   The proposed bill, sponsored by English and the subcommittee's
ranking Republican, E. Thomas Coleman of Missouri, would allow dual
trading in only certain circumstances including futures that have
an average daily trading volume of less than 7,000 contracts.
   But Melamed, the Chicago Mercantile Exchange official, said dual
trading was needed to maintain liquidity when there are few
customer orders. He added that pegging dual trading permissibility
to volume ignores the monthly idiosyncracies of various markets
such as soybeans, cattle, oil or gold.
   On the other hand, Robert D. Josserand, president of the
National Cattlemen's Association, advocated complete elimination of
dual trading to restore public confidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890720-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1916EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Drugs     07-20 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Drugs,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merck Earnings Up 25 Percent, Pfizer Down 36 Percent In 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Merck &amp; Co. Inc. said Thursday its second quarter earnings rose
25 percent over the same period last year, while another drug
maker, Pfizer Inc., posted a 36 percent drop in its second quarter
net income.
   Merck, which is based in Rahway, N.J., posted a profit of $396.6
million, or $1 per share, on sales of $1.6 billion in the three
months ended June 30. That compared with a profit of $316.3
million, or 80 cents a share, on sales of $1.5 billion during the
second quarter last year.
   Increased domestic and international sales of the drugs Mevacor,
Vasotec, Primaxin, Pepcid, Zocor and Prinivil contributed to the
company's strong second quarter showing, Merck said.
   ``Sales outside the United States accounted for 47 percent of
sales for the first six months, compared with 52 percent for the
same period last year,''said Dr. P. Roy Vagelos, Merck's chairman
and chief executive officer.
   For the first six months, Merck's net income rose to $737
million, or $1.86 a share, from $587.7 million, or $1.49 a share, a
year earlier. First half revenue rose to $3.2 billion from $2.9
billion during the period.
   Pfizer posted a profit of $135.7 million, or 80 cents a share,
in the second quarter, compared with $213.1 million, or $1.26 per
share, in the second quarter of 1988. Quarterly revenue dipped to
$1.3 billion from $1.34 billion.
   The New York-based company said sales declined in its health
care business, reflecting worldwide sales drops in pharmaceuticals
and hospital products, and agriculture operations. Sales rose for
Pfizer's consumer products and materials science segments.
   Edmund T. Pratt Jr., the company's chairman and chief executive
officer, said the stronger dollar also hurt sales. A stronger
dollar makes U.S. products more expensive overseas.
   For the first six months of 1989, Pfizer had net income of
$376.5 million, or $2.23 per share, down 13 percent from $432.9
million, or $2.57 per share, in the year-earlier period. Revenue
rose to $2.7 billion from $2.6 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
