<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Share Prices Inch Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened lower against the Japanese
yen Friday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
rose slightly.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added 16.62 points, or 0.05
percent, to move to 33,681.49 within the first 15 minutes. The
index's rise followed gains in the last two trading days.
   The dollar opened at 141.60 yen, down 0.63 yen from Thursday's
142.23-yen finish. The currency ended at 141.32 yen in New York
overnight.
   Traders attributed the U.S. currency's lower opening in Tokyo to
its losses in New York following comments by U.S. Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   Greenspan acknowledged that ``signs of softness in the economy
have shown up'' and said the Fed must closely monitor the slowing
economy.
   Masafuni Koyama, a trader with the Bank of Tokyo, said, ``The
dollar opened lower following the Greenspan comments, but Japanese
investors are inclined to buy it whenever the currency approaches
the 141-yen mark.''
   Analysts say investors fear a heavy loss for the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party in Sunday's parliamentary election, which is
widely expected, will cause the yen to plunge.
   ``Until the election Sunday, the dollar is unlikely to go lower
than its current level,'' he said, adding that interbank trading
dominated the early morning deals.
   Investors have avoided the yen and bought the dollar ahead of
the election, despite prospects of a slowdown in the U.S. economy
shown in several indicators, including a 0.2 percent rise in the
consumer price index for June.
