<FIRST>u f AM-DennisLevine     07-20 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dennis Levine,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Admitted Inside Trader Starts Consulting Practice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dennis B. Levine, the admitted inside trader
whose confessions spawned Wall Street's scandals, told a group of
business students Thursday he has started a financial consulting
practice in mergers and acquisitions.
   On other matters, Levine praised the performance of government
investigators as ``phenomenal,'' said the criminal justice system
treated him fairly, criticized the media's portrayal of him as
greedy, and expressed remorse for breaking the law.
   ``In my case, the combination of inexperience, unbridled
ambition, impatience and gross errors of judgment led me to break
the law,'' Levine told about 100 students and faculty at New York
University's business school.
   ``I blame myself and make no excuses and take full
responsibility for my actions,'' he said.
   Levine, 36, who was not paid to speak at NYU, traced his
involvement in a network of securities trading that used illegally
obtained information about pending corporate takeovers to net $11.6
million in illicit profits.
   Levine, a managing director at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. when
he was charged in May 1986, said his illicit activities included a
network of code names, foreign corporations and overseas bank
accounts.
   ``In a vastly different environment, when I made the decision to
cross the line I didn't think about getting caught,'' he said. ``I
was a wet-behind-the-ears naive rookie who should have known better
but didn't.''
   Answering a student's question, Levine said that since his
parole he has started a financial consulting practice and fought
civil lawsuits he said have sought $1 billion in claims.
   ``I believe as a result of my prosecution and others the insider
trading has declined,'' he said, adding that people who try that
kind of activity today ``are playing Russian roulette.''
   In a plea bargain with prosecutors, Levine pleaded guilty to
four felonies, was fined $362,000 and returned $11.6 million in
illegal profits. He also told the government about Ivan F. Boesky,
the now-imprisoned insider trader who himself made millions of
dollars using information supplied by Levine.
   Levine was paroled last September from a two-year prison term
for securities fraud, tax evasion and perjury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
